	<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading mw-first-heading">COVID-19 pandemic in New South Wales</h1>
	<div id="bodyContent" class="vector-body">
		<div id="siteSub" class="noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</div>

		<div id="contentSub2"></div>

		<div id="mw-content-text" class="mw-body-content mw-content-ltr" lang="en" dir="ltr"><div class="mw-parser-output"><table class="box-Multiple_issues plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-multiple_issues compact-ambox" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div style="width:52px"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png" decoding="async" width="40" height="40" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/60px-Ambox_important.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/80px-Ambox_important.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="40" data-file-height="40" /></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span"><div class="mw-collapsible" style="width:95%; margin: 0.2em 0;"><b>This article has multiple issues.</b> Please help <b><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit">improve it</a></b> or discuss these issues on the <b><a href="/wiki/Talk:COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales" title="Talk:COVID-19 pandemic in New South Wales">talk page</a></b>. <small><i>(<a href="/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal" title="Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove these template messages</a>)</i></small>
<div class="mw-collapsible-content" style="margin-top: 0.3em;">

<div class="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in New South Wales, Australia</div>
<p class="mw-empty-elt">

</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1066479718">.mw-parser-output .infobox-subbox{padding:0;border:none;margin:-3px;width:auto;min-width:100%;font-size:100%;clear:none;float:none;background-color:transparent}.mw-parser-output .infobox-3cols-child{margin:auto}.mw-parser-output .infobox .navbar{font-size:100%}body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-header,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-subheader,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-above,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-title,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-image,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-full-data,body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output .infobox-below{text-align:center}</style><table class="infobox"><tbody><tr><th colspan="2" class="infobox-above" 2022)</small></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Hospitalised cases</th><td class="infobox-data">1,070<img alt="Rise" 2022)</small></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label">Critical cases</th><td class="infobox-data">43 <img alt="Steady" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Steady2.svg/11px-Steady2.svg.png" decoding="async" title="Steady" width="11" height="11" data-file-width="300" data-file-height="300" /> <small>(as of 7 Mar. 2022)</small></td></tr><tr><th scope="row" class="infobox-label"><div style="display:inline-block; padding:0.1em />/</a></span><br /><span class="url"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.health.nsw.gov.au/news/Pages/2021-nsw-health.aspx">www<wbr />.health<wbr />.nsw<wbr />.gov<wbr />.au<wbr />/news<wbr />/Pages<wbr />/2021-nsw-health<wbr />.aspx</a></span></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The <b>COVID-19 pandemic in New South Wales</b> is part of the ongoing <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic" title="COVID-19 pandemic">worldwide pandemic</a> of the coronavirus disease 2019 (<span class="nowrap"><a href="/wiki/COVID-19" title="COVID-19">COVID-19</a></span>) caused by <a href="/wiki/Severe_acute_respiratory_syndrome_coronavirus_2" title="Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2">severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2</a> (<span class="nowrap">SARS-CoV-2</span>). The first confirmed case in <a href="/wiki/New_South_Wales" title="New South Wales">New South Wales</a> was identified on 19 January 2020 in <a href="/wiki/Sydney" title="Sydney">Sydney</a> where three travellers returning from <a href="/wiki/Wuhan" title="Wuhan">Wuhan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hubei" title="Hubei">Hubei</a>, <a href="/wiki/China" title="China">China</a>, tested positive for the virus.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of 7&#160;March&#160;2022<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, there have been over 952,000 confirmed cases from <a href="/wiki/PCR_testing" class="mw-redirect" title="PCR testing">PCR testing</a>, and nearly 440,000 positive <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_rapid_antigen_test" title="COVID-19 rapid antigen test">rapid antigen tests</a> (RAT) since mid-January 2022. The  5 deaths reported on that day,  and 5 on each of the 2 previous days, raised to 1,953 the official number of deaths from COVID-19 in New South Wales since March 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22_5-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> The single day record high is 52 deaths reported on 29 January 2022. Previous highs were 49 deaths on 28 January, 46 on 20 January, and 37 on 2 February in 2022,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22_6-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> up from 29 on 13 January,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and 15 on 28&#160;September 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> New daily case numbers, after being as low as 208 on 5 December 2021, rose sharply in mid-December, jumping to 11,201 cases on 28&#160;December,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-new-cases11k+-29dec&#39;21_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-new-cases11k+-29dec&#39;21-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> and 22,577 on 31&#160;December 2021. New cases then fell to 18,278 on 1&#160;January 2022, then up daily to 35,054, before falling slightly.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> They rose again for 2 days, to 45,098 on 7&#160;January,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> then fell sharply to 30,062 on 8 January<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> before rising again.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 21 September 2021, 55% of the state's over-16-year-old population had been fully vaccinated,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23sept&#39;21_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23sept&#39;21-14">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> and 60% on 26&#160;September.<sup id="cite_ref-the-aust-60%vaccd-26sept&#39;21_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-the-aust-60%vaccd-26sept&#39;21-15">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> On 30 September full vaccination reached 65% and over 87% had received one dose of COVID-19 vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2oct&#39;21_16-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2oct&#39;21-16">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> 70% full vaccination was reached on 6 October<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8oct&#39;21_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8oct&#39;21-17">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> and 75% on 11&#160;October, while over 90% had received least one vaccine dose.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13oct&#39;21_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13oct&#39;21-18">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> 80% full vaccination was reached on 16&#160;October,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-80%-full-vaccd-16oct&#39;21_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-80%-full-vaccd-16oct&#39;21-19">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> 85% on 25&#160;October 2021,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27oct&#39;21_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27oct&#39;21-20">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> and 93.5&#160;% on 23&#160;December, while one dose vaccinations reached 95% that day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21-21">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><br />By 13 January 2022, 24.2% aged 16 and older had received a third 'booster' vaccination, 47.3% on 10 February, and 55.4% by 3 March. 8.9% of 5–11 year-olds had received one dose,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> rising to 44.9% on 10 February, and 47.7% by 3 March.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22_22-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<li class="toclevel-4 tocsection-19"><a href="#Week_4"><span class="tocnumber">1.2.6.4</span> <span class="toctext">Week 4</span></a>
<ul>
<li class="toclevel-5 tocsection-20"><a href="#Lockdown_extended,_again"><span class="tocnumber">1.2.6.4.1</span> <span class="toctext">Lockdown extended, again</span></a></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-21"><a href="#August"><span class="tocnumber">1.2.7</span> <span class="toctext">August</span></a>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Timeline">Timeline</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Timeline">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2020">2020</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: 2020">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg/220px-La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg/330px-La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/12/La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg/440px-La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4032" data-file-height="3024" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:La-Perouse-Beach-Closed-Apr-2020.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Barricades erected by <a href="/wiki/City_of_Randwick" title="City of Randwick">Randwick City Council</a> to discourage access to a beach at <a href="/wiki/La_Perouse,_New_South_Wales" title="La Perouse, New South Wales">La Perouse, New South Wales</a></div></div></div>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg/220px-NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg/330px-NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/32/NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg/440px-NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3468" data-file-height="4624" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:NSW_Government_COVID-19_automatic_signalling_notice.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>NSW Government COVID-19 automatic signalling notice</div></div></div>
<p>On 4 March, the first COVID-19 death in the state, the second in Australia, was reported. She was a 95-year-old resident of, and who died at, the Dorothy Henderson Lodge aged-care facility in <a href="/wiki/Macquarie_Park,_New_South_Wales" title="Macquarie Park, New South Wales">Macquarie Park</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-smh-nsw-first-death-4mar&#39;20_24-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh-nsw-first-death-4mar&#39;20-24">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Former premier <a href="/wiki/Gladys_Berejiklian" title="Gladys Berejiklian">Gladys Berejiklian</a> formed a "war cabinet" to make decisions in relation to the pandemic.<sup id="cite_ref-warcabinet_25-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-warcabinet-25">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> Members include herself, <a href="/wiki/Treasurer_of_New_South_Wales" title="Treasurer of New South Wales">Treasurer</a> <a href="/wiki/Dominic_Perrottet" title="Dominic Perrottet">Dominic Perrottet</a>, <a href="/wiki/Minister_for_Health_and_Medical_Research_(New_South_Wales)" class="mw-redirect" title="Minister for Health and Medical Research (New South Wales)">Minister for Health and Medical Research</a> <a href="/wiki/Brad_Hazzard" title="Brad Hazzard">Brad Hazzard</a> and <a href="/wiki/Minister_for_Police_and_Emergency_Services_(New_South_Wales)" class="mw-redirect" title="Minister for Police and Emergency Services (New South Wales)">Minister for Police and Emergency Services</a> <a href="/wiki/David_Elliott_(politician)" title="David Elliott (politician)">David Elliott</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-warcabinet_25-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-warcabinet-25">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 15 March, Secretary of the <a href="/wiki/Department_of_Education_(New_South_Wales)" title="Department of Education (New South Wales)">New South Wales Department of Education</a>, <a href="/wiki/Mark_Scott_(businessman)" title="Mark Scott (businessman)">Mark Scott</a> ordered that, effective immediately, New South Wales schools introduce social distancing measures to reduce the spread of coronavirus.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> The order required schools to cancel all assemblies, excursions, travel, concerts, large inter-school sporting and arts events, and other events that would require students and staff to congregate in large numbers.<sup id="cite_ref-27" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> Schools were to stay open. Four schools in the state have been shut for periods during the crisis due to confirmed cases within their school communities.<sup id="cite_ref-abc_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-28">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 16 March, <a href="/wiki/Minister_for_Health_and_Medical_Research_(New_South_Wales)" class="mw-redirect" title="Minister for Health and Medical Research (New South Wales)">New South Wales Minister for Health and Medical Research</a> <a href="/wiki/Brad_Hazzard" title="Brad Hazzard">Brad Hazzard</a> announced that he was using his powers, under Section 7 of the 'Public Health Act 2010', to immediately and indefinitely cancel all public events with more than 500 attendees.<sup id="cite_ref-7NEWS.com.au_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7NEWS.com.au-29">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> The order is enforceable by <a href="/wiki/NSW_Police" class="mw-redirect" title="NSW Police">NSW Police</a> and violations of the order can carry a prison term of six months, an $11,000 fine, or both.<sup id="cite_ref-7NEWS.com.au_29-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7NEWS.com.au-29">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/Tom_Bathurst" title="Tom Bathurst">Chief Justice Bathurst</a>, <a href="/wiki/Chief_Justice_of_New_South_Wales" title="Chief Justice of New South Wales">Chief Justice of New South Wales</a>, and Chief Judge Price of the <a href="/wiki/District_Court_of_New_South_Wales" title="District Court of New South Wales">District Court of New South Wales</a> ordered that effective 16 March 2020, new jury trials would be suspended to limit the spread of coronavirus.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> The order did not apply to already empanelled jury trials.<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Corrective_Services_New_South_Wales" title="Corrective Services New South Wales">Corrective Services New South Wales</a> implemented screening mechanisms, early flu vaccination programs and stricter hygiene requirements for staff, visitors and inmates to slow the spread of the virus.<sup id="cite_ref-abc_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-28">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href="/wiki/University_of_Sydney" title="University of Sydney">University of Sydney</a> cancelled all graduations, conferences, academic and student organised events.<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/University_of_New_South_Wales" title="University of New South Wales">University of New South Wales</a> announced that it was cancelling all student and academic events until Easter, encourage staff to work from home and, where possible, shift all lectures, tutorials, demonstrations and labs to online learning.<sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>New South Wales schools were directed by the State Department of Education Secretary, Mark Scott, to cancel all assemblies, excursions, travel, and some events and conferences, including arts and initiative events, as well as whole school sporting events and inter-school sporting events with three or more involved schools.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_34-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-34">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 17 March, the New South Wales government announced a A$2.3&#160;billion stimulus package, including A$700&#160;million for health services. A$450&#160;million was allocated to waive <a href="/wiki/Payroll_tax" title="Payroll tax">payroll tax</a> for 3 months. $250&#160;million so state-owned buildings and public schools could employ more cleaners. A$750&#160;million was allocated for capital works and public asset maintenance.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-econ-stim-nsw-mar-&#39;20_35-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-econ-stim-nsw-mar-&#39;20-35">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Even though there was a ban on gatherings of more than 500 people, huge crowds flocked to the popular <a href="/wiki/Bondi_Beach" title="Bondi Beach">Bondi Beach</a> and other beaches across Sydney on Friday 20&#160;March. Health Minister <a href="/wiki/Greg_Hunt" title="Greg Hunt">Greg Hunt</a> said that such behaviour was "unacceptable" while the New South Wales Labor's Shadow Treasurer, <a href="/wiki/Walt_Secord" title="Walt Secord">Walt Secord</a> urged the government to completely close off the beach. New South Wales Police Minister <a href="/wiki/David_Elliott_(politician)" title="David Elliott (politician)">David Elliott</a> later stated in a televised interview that lifeguards were instructed to keep a head count of the people at the beach and if the number exceeded 500, the beach would be closed. On 21 March, crowds built up yet again which led <a href="/wiki/Waverley_Council" title="Waverley Council">Waverley Council</a> to temporarily close <a href="/wiki/Bondi_Beach" title="Bondi Beach">Bondi</a>, and the other beaches of <a href="/wiki/Bronte_Beach" title="Bronte Beach">Bronte</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tamarama" class="mw-redirect" title="Tamarama">Tamarama</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated1_34-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated1-34">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 22 March, a public health order was issued that declared <a href="/wiki/Lord_Howe_Island" title="Lord Howe Island">Lord Howe Island</a> a public risk area and directed restricted access. As of that date there were no known cases of COVID-19 on Lord Howe Island.<sup id="cite_ref-Lord_Howe_36-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Lord_Howe-36">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 27 March, NSW local council elections due in September 2020 were postponed to September 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-regional-nsw-elect-postponed-mar&#39;20_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-regional-nsw-elect-postponed-mar&#39;20-37">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> They were later postponed again to 4 December 2021 due to a wave of delta COVID-19 variant infections that caused numerous lockdowns in the state.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-elects-postponed-24july&#39;21_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-elects-postponed-24july&#39;21-38">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 March, NSW Parliament passed the "COVID-19 Restrictions on Gathering and Movement" law,<sup id="cite_ref-NSW_Public_Health_(COVID-19_Restrictions_on_Gathering_and_Movement)_Order_2020_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NSW_Public_Health_(COVID-19_Restrictions_on_Gathering_and_Movement)_Order_2020-39">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> which limited public gatherings to two people and directed, "that a person must not, without reasonable excuse, leave the person's place of residence." It listed 16 reasonable excuses and took effect from midnight on 31 March.
</p><p>As of 15 May, some restrictions on public and private gatherings were eased. Private homes were allowed 5 visitors.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-restricts-ease-13-june_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-restricts-ease-13-june-40">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> Free standing cafes and restaurants, and those inside pubs and clubs, were allowed very limited sit-down dining, after being restricted to take-away only since 23 March. Bars and gaming areas remained closed. A maximum of 10 people were permitted in restaurants and cafes, while social distancing rules still had to be followed. Outdoor gatherings of up to 10 people were permitted. Up to 10 guests were permitted at weddings, and funerals could have up to 20 mourners indoors, 30 outdoors. Up to 10 people were allowed at indoor religious gatherings such as churches.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-restricts-eased-nsw_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-restricts-eased-nsw-41">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7news-prem-iview-restricts_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7news-prem-iview-restricts-42">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 13 June, private homes were allowed to have up to 20 guests visit, and groups of 20 were allowed to meet outside. Food courts were allowed to open, so long as the 4-square-metres-per-patron rule was kept, and no more than 50 patrons. Indoor gym classes were allowed 10 participants. Up to 100 persons were allowed inside gyms, so long as area requirements were adhered to.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-restricts-ease-13-june_40-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-restricts-ease-13-june-40">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 1 July, New South Wales eased restrictions further due to the limited <a href="/wiki/Community_transmission" class="mw-redirect" title="Community transmission">community transmission</a> of COVID-19, at that time. No set upper limit on patron numbers at indoor venues, but only one person per 4 square metres. Outdoor venues, with a maximum capacity of 40,000, were allowed up to 25 per cent of normal capacity. Events had to be ticketed, patrons seated and follow guidelines. Restriction on funerals eased, but the four-square-metre rule applied. Other existing restrictions, no more than 20 guests inside homes, 20 outside, remained in force.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-restrict-eased-1-july_43-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-restrict-eased-1-july-43">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> Restrictions were tightened again on 17 July. (<i>See below</i>)
</p><p>From 5 July, the Federal Government introduced restrictions on the number of passengers arriving at Sydney Airport. A maximum of 50 passengers were allowed per flight, and international arrivals were set at 450 per day. This was by request of the NSW Government to reduce pressure on hotel quarantine capacity. More than 32,000 travellers had quarantined in Sydney hotels by this date.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-airport-restrict-5-july_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-airport-restrict-5-july-44">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 6 July, the Victorian and NSW State Governments, jointly announced that their interstate border would be re-closed from the start of 8&#160;July, following a large spike in cases in certain areas of Melbourne.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vic-nsw/vic-border_re-close_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vic-nsw/vic-border_re-close-45">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of 12:01&#160;a.m. on 17 July, after an increase in cases, new rules for <a href="/wiki/Pub" title="Pub">pubs</a> were introduced. Measures included, group bookings and persons at a table were limited to 10 (formerly 20), and a maximum of 300 people allowed inside any venue. COVID Safe Hygiene Marshalls to oversee the venues COVID-19 infection prevention were also required, and venue COVID-Safe registration was compulsory. Paper-based sign-ins are allowed, but a digital record of patrons contact details, for <a href="/wiki/Contact_tracing" title="Contact tracing">contact tracing</a>, must be provided on request.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-pub-rules-17-july_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-pub-rules-17-july-46">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> Breaching the rules can result in a <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>55,000 fine for the venue, plus another <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>27,500 for each day the breach is continued.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-restrict-tighten-24-july_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-restrict-tighten-24-july-47">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> As of 24&#160;July, the tightened venue restrictions were also applied to bars, cafes, clubs and restaurants.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-restrict-tighten-24-july_47-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-restrict-tighten-24-july-47">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Until 18 July, international travellers who had to undergo compulsory quarantine on arrival did not have to pay for their accommodation, at a cost of <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>65 million to the NSW Government. Under new rules announced on 11&#160;July, as of 12:01&#160;a.m. on Saturday 18&#160;July 2020, all new arrivals are being charged for their quarantine. The charge includes meals and room costs, for which one adult will pay <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>3,000, additional adults <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>1,000, children <span style="white-space: nowrap">A$</span>500, and no charge for children under 3 years. Those already quarantined will not have to pay, nor will those who purchased flights, and, had a confirmed international arrival date, before 11:59&#160; p.m. on 12 July 2020 <a href="/wiki/AEST" class="mw-redirect" title="AEST">AEST</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-quarantine-charge-18-july_48-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-quarantine-charge-18-july-48">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 20 July, the number of daily overseas arrivals allowed at Sydney Airport was reduced to 350 from the 450 limit set on July&#160;5.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-syd-airport-restrict-20-july_49-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-syd-airport-restrict-20-july-49">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 5 August, it was announced that as from 7&#160;August all Victorians arriving in NSW would be required to quarantine, at their own expense, in hotels for 14 days. Air arrivals from Victoria were only  allowed at Sydney Airport.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vic-nsw-quarant-5-aug_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vic-nsw-quarant-5-aug-50">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Dine_and_Discover">Dine and Discover</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Dine and Discover">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 17 November 2020 the NSW Government announced the "Dine and Discover" programme in the state budget. All NSW residents over 18 years-of-age were eligible to receive four A$25 vouchers through <a href="/wiki/Service_NSW" title="Service NSW">Service NSW</a> to help stimulate the economy.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vouchers_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vouchers-51">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> Two vouchers are for dining, Monday to Thursday only, excluding public holidays. The other two are to be spent on entertainment, excluding on public holidays.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-service-voucher_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-service-voucher-52">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> Businesses need to be COVID-safe registered, and sign-up for the scheme. The vouchers cannot be used for gambling, alcohol, cigarettes, retail purchases or accommodation. The program was originally called "Out and About".<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vouchers_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vouchers-51">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As early as mid-April 2021, the scheme was said by some regional NSW residents to be "city centric'. At this time, the vouchers had been used by less than 10% of the 5 million who could use it. There were calls by NSW opposition political parties for the scheme to be extended beyond its initial 30 June 2021 deadline to use the vouchers.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-d&amp;d-city-centric_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-d&amp;d-city-centric-53">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> On 9 June 2021, the Dine &amp; Discover scheme was extended by a month to 31 July,<sup id="cite_ref-9news-nsw-d&amp;d-extended_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-nsw-d&amp;d-extended-54">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> and on 29 June extended again to 31 August.  Use for take-away food purchases was also allowed.<sup id="cite_ref-7News-d&amp;d-extend-31aug_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7News-d&amp;d-extend-31aug-55">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> The vouchers were eventually extended to 30 June 2022.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-d&amp;d-voucher-ext-2022_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-d&amp;d-voucher-ext-2022-56">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> In November 2021, two extra vouchers were granted, one for dining and one for entertainment.<sup id="cite_ref-57" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-57">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 23 November, it became mandatory for many businesses to use electronic record systems to collect details of patrons for possible contact tracing.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-elect-record_58-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-elect-record-58">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Northern_Beaches_outbreak">Northern Beaches outbreak</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Northern Beaches outbreak">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<table class="box-Update plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Update" role="presentation"><tbody><tr><td class="mbox-image"><div style="width:52px"><img alt="Ambox current red.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/42px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png" decoding="async" width="42" height="34" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/63px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Ambox_current_red.svg/84px-Ambox_current_red.svg.png 2x" data-file-width="360" data-file-height="290" /></div></td><td class="mbox-text"><div class="mbox-text-span">This section needs to be <b>updated</b>. The reason given is: End of outbreak in January and end of lockdown on Sunday 10 January 2021.<span class="hide-when-compact"> Please help update this article to reflect recent events or newly available information.</span>  <span class="date-container"><i>(<span class="date">February 2021</span>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Sydney_New_Year%27s_Eve#2020–21:_COVID-19_impact" title="Sydney New Year&#39;s Eve">Impact of COVID-19 on Sydney's New Year's Eve celebrations</a></div>
<p>During the second week of December 2020, an outbreak of COVID-19 in <a href="/wiki/Avalon,_Sydney" class="mw-redirect" title="Avalon, Sydney">Avalon</a> began.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (February 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> A stay at home advisory was issued on 17 December.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-nth-beaches-lockdown_59-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-nth-beaches-lockdown-59">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 19 December 2020, a public health order was issued, locking down Sydney's <a href="/wiki/Northern_Beaches" title="Northern Beaches">Northern Beaches</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nort-beach-lockdown_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nort-beach-lockdown-60">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> Residents of the Northern Beaches LGA were required to stay at home from 5&#160;pm on Saturday 19 December, until 11:59&#160;pm on Wednesday 23&#160;December unless they had a lawful reason to travel, including for: essential shopping; essential travel for work and to or from a school or educational institution; exercise; medical care, carer's responsibilities or compassionate needs. Entry to the area was similarly restricted. Public gatherings were limited to two persons.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-nth-beaches-lockdown_59-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-nth-beaches-lockdown-59">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 20&#160;December, there were 68 cases. This prompted restrictions on admission of Sydney residents or visitors to Sydney, to other states. These ranged from 14-day quarantines (ACT, NT, Queensland, South Australia, Tasmania, Victoria) to no entry without an exemption (Queensland). South Australia barred entry to anyone from the Northern Beaches, while Western Australia barred everyone coming from NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-avalon-cluster_61-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-avalon-cluster-61">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup> Measures to stem the spread of COVID-19 in Sydney were again tightened. No more than 10 people were allowed in homes in Greater Sydney, Blue Mountains, Central Coast and Illawarra-Shoalhaven.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nort-beach-outbreak_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nort-beach-outbreak-62">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>New Year's Eve celebrations were restricted in Sydney city, around the harbour and suburbs. The midnight fireworks on Sydney Harbour, normally 20 minutes, were cut back to 7 minutes, with no fireworks at 9&#160;pm.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-nye_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-nye-63">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> The harbour foreshores were closed to prevent crowds congregating. Only residents, guests,  and those with bookings at bars, hotels and restaurants, were allowed in foreshore areas under a pass system. Vantage points in <a href="/wiki/North_Sydney,_New_South_Wales" title="North Sydney, New South Wales">North Sydney</a> were also closed.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-nye_63-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-nye-63">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2021">2021</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: 2021">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>From 1 January, hospitality venues and hairdressers were required to use the NSW Government <a href="/wiki/QR_code" title="QR code">QR code</a> system for patron check-in.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-qr-code_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-qr-code-64">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On Saturday, 2 January 2021, it was announced that as of midnight that day, facemasks would become mandatory in many enclosed places in Greater Sydney. All public transport, shops, supermarkets, cinemas, theatres and places of worship were included. Hospitality workers also had to wear masks. Children under 12 years-of-age were exempt. An A$200 on the spot fine could be charged for non-compliance. Fines were applied from 4 January (Monday).<sup id="cite_ref-abc-masks-syd--2Jan21_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-masks-syd--2Jan21-65">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Maximum gym class sizes were reduced from 50 to 30, worship from 300 down to 100, weddings were limited to 100, or one per 4 square metres. Outdoor performances reduced from 1,000 to 500 patrons. Events which were "seated, ticketed and enclosed" were reduced back to 2,000 maximum. Night clubs were "not permitted".<sup id="cite_ref-abc-masks-syd--2Jan21_65-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-masks-syd--2Jan21-65">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="February">February</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: February">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 21 February, the first public <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_vaccination_in_Australia" title="COVID-19 vaccination in Australia">COVID-19 vaccinations</a> in Australia, with the <a href="/wiki/Pfizer%E2%80%93BioNTech_vaccine" class="mw-redirect" title="Pfizer–BioNTech vaccine">Pfizer–BioNTech vaccine</a>, were administered in Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-smh-pfizer-doses-start_66-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh-pfizer-doses-start-66">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup> Up to 6:00&#160;pm on 23 February in NSW, 3,200 people were immunised across three state-run hospitals.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21-67">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As of 24 February, there was no transmission of COVID-19 in the community in NSW for 38 days. On 17 March restrictions were to be "revisited".<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21_67-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21-67">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> Also on 24 February, further restriction easing was announced in NSW. From 12:01&#160;am on 26 February (Friday):
</p>
<ul><li>Dancing and singing was allowed at gatherings</li>
<li>At weddings, up to 30 people, including guests, could dance at one time. (previously, only the wedding party, a maximum of 20 people. The 300 person limit for wedding guests remained)</li>
<li>Up to 50 people at their home (up from 30) Visitor number includes adults <i>and</i> children.</li>
<li>Up to 50 people allowed in gym classes (4-square metre rule applies)</li>
<li>Up to 30 singers allowed in choirs and religious congregations. Masks required, place of worship must adhere to the 4-square metre rule.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21_67-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-restr-ease-24-feb-&#39;21-67">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="March">March</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: March">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 30 March, a <a href="/wiki/Byron_Bay" title="Byron Bay">Byron Bay</a> man in his 20s was found to be infected. A number of restrictions were enacted in the Byron area as a result:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Masks mandatory when shopping/using public transport
<ul><li>including taxis and ride-sharing services</li></ul></li>
<li>Masks mandatory for hospitality staff</li>
<li>4 square-metre rule area rule in hospitality venues
<ul><li>patrons must be seated</li></ul></li>
<li>home visitors limited to 30 people</li></ul>
<p>It was determined that a person linked to the Brisbane 'nurse cluster' visited venues in Byron, including the Byron Beach Hotel on 26 March,  while unknowingly infectious. The local case also attended that hotel.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel_68-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>As a result, on 31 March the 2021 <a href="/wiki/Byron_Bay_Bluesfest" title="Byron Bay Bluesfest">Byron Bay Bluesfest</a> was cancelled, for the second year, a day before it was to commence. Because of the one case of transmission in the community, a public health order was signed by the Minister for Health <a href="/wiki/Brad_Hazzard" title="Brad Hazzard">Brad Hazzard</a>, banning the event.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel_68-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="May">May</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: May">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 5 May in Sydney, a case of COVID-19 in a man in his 50s who worked as driver for flight crew members in Sydney Airport, was detected with no known physical link to travel or border control/quarantine hotels or workers. His wife also tested positive to COVID-19. Genomic testing provided a link to an overseas (US) acquired infection at the Park Royal in <a href="/wiki/Darling_Harbour" title="Darling Harbour">Darling Harbour</a>. The new cases are believed to have been infectious while visiting at least 20 locations in Sydney from 30&#160;April to 4&#160;March. Due to these community transmitted infections, COVID related restrictions in Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains and Wollongong were tightened, initially for 3&#160;days, from 5&#160;pm on 6&#160;May (Friday), to 12:01 am on 9 May (Monday).<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21_69-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21-70">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Mask-wearing was again made mandatory at indoor places, including:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21_69-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>Public transport</li>
<li>Supermarkets</li>
<li>Other indoor events</li></ul></li>
<li>Hospitality staff at front of house had to be masked<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21_70-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21-70">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>Patrons drinking had to be seated.</li></ul></li>
<li>No singing or dancing at indoor venues, including,
<ul><li>Places of worship and</li>
<li>Entertainment venues.</li></ul></li></ul>
<p>Exemptions included weddings, and dancers or singers performing in shows.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21_69-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-case-restricts-6may&#39;21-69">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Only 20 visitors allowed at private homes</li>
<li>Maximum 2 visitors at aged care facilities<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21_70-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-zero-in-restricts-6may&#39;21-70">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>On 9 May, because the "missing link" in the two community transmitted infections that caused the restriction tightening on 5&#160;May had not been located, most of the extra restrictions were extended another seven days until 12:01 am on 17 May. The main change was mask wearing was not required indoors by patrons of shops and hospitality venues, except for gaming areas where masks are still needed. On public transport and other indoor public venues masks remained mandatory.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-5may-restricts-extended-week-9may-21_71-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-5may-restricts-extended-week-9may-21-71">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup> 13,768 COVID tests were undertaken in the 24&#160;hours to 8:00&#160;pm that day, but NSW recorded no locally acquired COVID-19 infections.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-vacc-hub+_72-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-vacc-hub+-72">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> On 17 May the temporary restrictions from 5 May were lifted. The missing link in the cases of community transmission that led to these restrictions had still not been located.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-live-5may&#39;21-restricts-lifted_73-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-live-5may&#39;21-restricts-lifted-73">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 10 May, a mass vaccination hub opened at <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Olympic_Park" title="Sydney Olympic Park">Sydney Olympic Park</a>. The same day, registrations began for NSW residents aged 40 to 49-years to receive the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-vacc-hub+_72-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-vacc-hub+-72">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="June">June</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: June">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 1 June, it was found that a later confirmed COVID-19 case from Melbourne had travelled to New South Wales, before Victorias' fourth lockdown was imposed on 27 May, while possibly infectious. Possible exposure sites included venues in <a href="/wiki/Goulburn" class="mw-redirect" title="Goulburn">Goulburn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jervis_Bay" title="Jervis Bay">Jervis Bay</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hyams_Beach" class="mw-redirect" title="Hyams Beach">Hyams Beach</a> and <a href="/wiki/Vincentia,_New_South_Wales" title="Vincentia, New South Wales">Vincentia</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-expose-sites-01jun-&#39;21_74-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-expose-sites-01jun-&#39;21-74">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 16 June, NSW residents aged over 50 were able to get an AstraZeneca vaccination from selected pharmacies. 1,250 pharmacies were approved by the NSW health department to administer the vaccine under strict regulations.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-nsw-vacc-phm+_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-nsw-vacc-phm+-75">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup> However,  on 17&#160;June the Commonwealth government decided, on the advice of the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Technical_Advisory_Group_on_Immunisation" title="Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation">Australian Technical Advisory Group on Immunisation</a> (ATAGI), to change their previous advisory of 50 years plus, and only recommend the AstraZeneca vaccine for those over 60 years-of-age.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-astra-zeneca-60years-&amp;over_76-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-astra-zeneca-60years-&amp;over-76">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="Eastern_Suburbs.2FBondi_cluster"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Eastern_Suburbs/Bondi_cluster"><span class="anchor" id="bondi-cluster"></span>Eastern Suburbs/Bondi cluster</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Eastern Suburbs/Bondi cluster">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 16 June, the first COVID-19 case in what became known as the Bondi cluster was confirmed. The case was a man in his 60s who worked as a limousine driver, and had been transporting crew off international flights.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-alert-bondi-16july&#39;21_77-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-alert-bondi-16july&#39;21-77">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup> By 12 August 2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, what began in Bondi spread widely and new cases reported in NSW reached 6,874. There had been at least 38&#160;deaths during the <a href="/wiki/SARS-CoV-2_Delta_variant" title="SARS-CoV-2 Delta variant">Delta variant</a> outbreak, raising the total number of COVID deaths in NSW to 95 since the beginning of the pandemic in 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21_78-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21-78">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup> Greater Sydney, Wollongong, the Blue Mountains, Central and Northern NSW, the Central Coast, Far North Coast and other regions in NSW were, or had been, in lockdown, and the Delta outbreak had spread interstate causing more lockdowns including the ACT, Victoria, and South East Queensland.
</p><p>On 18 June from 4pm in Greater Sydney (not including the Illawarra and Wollongong regions), masks were again made mandatory on public transport for at least the next 5 days. This was after the COVID-19 cluster in Sydneys' Eastern Suburbs had grown to 4&#160;cases. The same day it was announced that from 1:00am on 19 June, the eastern Sydney local government area of <a href="/wiki/Waverley,_Sydney" class="mw-redirect" title="Waverley, Sydney">Waverley</a> would be declared a COVID-19 hotspot by the Queensland government.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-sydney-masks-again-18june&#39;21_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-sydney-masks-again-18june&#39;21-79">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 22 June the cluster in Bondi had increased by 10 to 22 cases,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-#22_80-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-#22-80">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> 31 cases by 23&#160;June,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№31_81-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№31-81">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup> 36 by 24 June,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№-36-24june&#39;21_82-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№-36-24june&#39;21-82">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> 65 by 25 June,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21_83-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21-83">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> and there were 130 cases in Sydney, of which 124 were linked to the Bondi cluster, by 28 June.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-sydney-№-130_84-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-sydney-№-130-84">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup> The cluster reached 160 cases by 30&#160;June,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№160-biggest_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№160-biggest-85">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> 175 by 1&#160;July,<sup id="cite_ref-miragenews-bondi-№175-1july&#39;21_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-miragenews-bondi-№175-1july&#39;21-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup> 188 by 2&#160;July,<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№188-2jul6&#39;21_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№188-2jul6&#39;21-87">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> and 207 by 3 July.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№207-3july&#39;21_88-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№207-3july&#39;21-88">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup> Known linked cases reached 285 by 9 July,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9july&#39;21_89-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9july&#39;21-89">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup> after which NSW Health did not report them separately. By 31 July there had also been 16 deaths linked to this outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-31july&#39;21_90-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-31july&#39;21-90">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>New movement restrictions were enacted from 4pm on 23 June. People from the NSW LGAs of:
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Bayside_Council" title="Bayside Council">Bayside</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Canada_Bay" title="Canada Bay">Canada Bay</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Inner_West" title="Inner West">Inner West</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Randwick,_New_South_Wales" title="Randwick, New South Wales">Randwick</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Waverley,_Sydney" class="mw-redirect" title="Waverley, Sydney">Waverley</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Woollahra" class="mw-redirect" title="Woollahra">Woollahra</a></li></ul>
<p>were not permitted to leave the Sydney <a href="/wiki/Metropolitan_area" title="Metropolitan area">metropolitan area</a>, except for essential purposes.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№31_81-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№31-81">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Tighter social distancing restrictions were also enacted on 23 June, covering residents of Greater Sydney, <a href="/wiki/Blue_Mountains_(New_South_Wales)" title="Blue Mountains (New South Wales)">Blue Mountains</a>, <a href="/wiki/Central_Coast_(New_South_Wales)" title="Central Coast (New South Wales)">Central Coast</a>, <a href="/wiki/Wollongong" title="Wollongong">Wollongong</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Shellharbour,_New_South_Wales" title="Shellharbour, New South Wales">Shellharbour</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№31_81-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№31-81">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Restrictions as of 24 June were scheduled to remain in force until 1&#160;July at 12:01am,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№-36-24june&#39;21_82-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№-36-24june&#39;21-82">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> but were extended on 25 June to 11:59pm on 2 July,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21_83-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21-83">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> and the next day extended again to 11.59pm on 9 July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup> On 14 July, after 97 new cases were recorded, the lockdown was extended another 2&#160;weeks to 11:59pm on 30 July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-sydney-lockdown-+2weeks_92-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-sydney-lockdown-+2weeks-92">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup> On 28 July, the lockdown in Greater Sydney, and other NSW LGAs in lockdown that day, was again extended from 31 July to 12:01am on 28 August.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again_93-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again-93">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup> From 5pm on 14 August, all of regional NSW was also put into lockdown until 12:01am on 22 August.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21-94">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 25 June, after 22 new cases of the <a href="/wiki/Delta_variant" class="mw-redirect" title="Delta variant">delta variant</a> brought infections linked to the Bondi cluster to 65 total, a lockdown was announced for four Sydney LGAs. The City of Sydney, Randwick, Waverley and Woollahra were the affected places. From 11:59pm on 25&#160;June those who live there, or had worked there in the previous 14&#160;days, had to isolate at home until at least 11:59pm on 2&#160;July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21_83-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21-83">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup> (Later extended to 11.59pm on 9 July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup>) The usual 'essential reasons' for leaving home apply. Up to 1 million people may be affected. Current NSW restrictions like mandatory masks indoors and on public transport were extended to the same time and date.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21_83-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4xlgas-lockdown-25june&#39;21-83">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Weddings were permitted on 26 – 27 June, but then banned until 9 July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>By 26 June, infections linked to the Bondi cluster rose to 80. Of these, 20 were also connected to a birthday party in <a href="/wiki/Hoxton_Park" class="mw-redirect" title="Hoxton Park">Hoxton Park</a>. By this date 2,076,483 vaccine doses had been administered in NSW, 18,088 of them in the 24 hours to 8pm on 25 June.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-26&#39;june&#39;21_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-26&#39;june&#39;21-95">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup> The lockdown area in NSW was expanded from 6:00pm to cover Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains, Central Coast and Wollongong, and the lockdown length was also extended until 11.59pm on 9 July.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Restrictions for the rest of NSW were also increased:
</p>
<ul><li>Only 5 visitors allowed in homes (includes children)</li>
<li>Masks mandatory in indoor, non-residential settings</li>
<li>The 4-square-metre space rule applies again for indoor or outdoor settings.
<ul><li>Drinking while standing at indoor venues not permitted</li></ul></li>
<li>Dancing not permitted at indoor hospitality venues and nightclubs,
<ul><li>Dancing is allowed at weddings for the wedding party (20 people maximum)</li></ul></li>
<li>Dance and gym classes, 20 people maximum per class,
<ul><li>Masks mandatory<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup></li></ul></li></ul>
<p>People in NSW who had been in the Greater Sydney region (including Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Wollongong) on, or after, June 21 must adhere to stay-at-home orders for 14 days after they left <sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21_91-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown-extended26june&#39;21-91">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 28 June the outbreak in Sydney had increased to 130 cases, 124 of them linked to the cluster in Bondi.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-sydney-№-130_84-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-sydney-№-130-84">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 29 June, the Dine and Discover stimulus scheme was extended for the second time, to 31 August, and now also allowed take-away food purchases.<sup id="cite_ref-7News-d&amp;d-extend-31aug_55-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7News-d&amp;d-extend-31aug-55">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 30 June, the 'Bondi cluster' of delta variant COVID-19 reached 160 cases, becoming Sydney's largest cluster to this date. The previous high was 151 in the 'Northern Beaches' or '<a href="/wiki/COVID-19_clusters_in_Australia" title="COVID-19 clusters in Australia">Avalon cluster</a>', in December 2020–January 2021. The next largest after Avalon was 116&#160;cases in the <a href="/wiki/Wetherill_Park" class="mw-redirect" title="Wetherill Park">Wetherill Park</a> cluster of July–August 2020. Sydney had <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_clusters_in_Australia" title="COVID-19 clusters in Australia">18 clusters</a> by this date.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№160-biggest_85-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№160-biggest-85">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="July">July</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: July">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Week_1">Week 1</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Week 1">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>By 1 July, there were 175 reported infections linked to the Bondi cluster, 188 by 2 July, 207 by 3 July, and 222 by 4 July.<sup id="cite_ref-miragenews-bondi-№175-1july&#39;21_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-miragenews-bondi-№175-1july&#39;21-86">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№188-2jul6&#39;21_87-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№188-2jul6&#39;21-87">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№207-3july&#39;21_88-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№207-3july&#39;21-88">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№222-4july&#39;21_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cluster-bondi-№222-4july&#39;21-96">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 3 July, stay-at-home orders for people in NSW who had been in the Northern Territory, Western Australia, and some Queensland local government areas were lifted.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stay-home-02july&#39;21_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stay-home-02july&#39;21-97">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h6><span class="mw-headline" id="Lockdown_extended">Lockdown extended</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Lockdown extended">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>
<p>On 7 July, the lockdown in Greater Sydney was extended for 7 days until 12:01am on 17 July. This followed the state having 27 new cases of COVID-19. There were more cases in <a href="/wiki/Canterbury-Bankstown" title="Canterbury-Bankstown">Canterbury-Bankstown</a>, <a href="/wiki/Fairfield,_New_South_Wales" title="Fairfield, New South Wales">Fairfield</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Liverpool,_New_South_Wales" title="Liverpool, New South Wales">Liverpool</a>. Over 45,000 people were tested for COVID "overnight".<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-jun-jul-lockdown-+7days_98-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-jun-jul-lockdown-+7days-98">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup> Also by 7 July, the Bondi cluster linked cases had reached 264. There were another 93 locally acquired cases for a total of 357 since 16&#160;June, when the first Bondi cluster case was reported.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-bondi-7july&#39;21_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-bondi-7july&#39;21-99">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Week_2">Week 2</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Week 2">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>On 8 July, the Bondi cluster linked cases had reached 279. There were 40 hospitalised cases, 11 in intensive care with 3 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8july&#39;21_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8july&#39;21-100">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 9 July, Bondi cluster linked cases had reached 285. There were 43 hospitalised cases, 10 in intensive care with 4 on ventilation. 37 cases have not been linked to a known case or cluster, with another 117 linked to those 37 cases, for 439 total active cases. 44&#160;new locally acquired cases were reported on 8 July up to 8pm. 21 were in <a href="/wiki/South_Western_Sydney" title="South Western Sydney">South Western Sydney</a>, 8 in <a href="/wiki/South-Eastern_Sydney" title="South-Eastern Sydney">South-Eastern Sydney</a> and 7 in <a href="/wiki/Western_Sydney" class="mw-redirect" title="Western Sydney">Western Sydney</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9july&#39;21_89-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9july&#39;21-89">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 9 July from 5pm, social distancing restrictions were tightened in Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Wollongong and Shellharbour:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-sydney-restricts+-9july&#39;21_101-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-sydney-restricts+-9july&#39;21-101">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Only 2 people can gather outside (excluding those who live in the same home)</li>
<li>May only exercise inside their local government area, or within 10&#160;km (6 miles) from their home</li>
<li>Must not <a href="/wiki/Carpool" title="Carpool">carpool</a> with people from different households</li>
<li>For essential shopping, only one person, per household, per day can shop
<ul><li>Browsing in shops prohibited</li></ul></li>
<li>From 11 July, funerals will be limited to 10 mourners.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-sydney-restricts+-9july&#39;21_101-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-sydney-restricts+-9july&#39;21-101">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>On 10 July, it was reported that there were 50 new cases in NSW to 8pm on 9 July, bringing the confirmed case total to 5,972. There were 47 hospitalised cases, 16 in intensive care with 5 on ventilation. Of the 50 new cases 29 are from south-west Sydney, 16 from south-east Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10july&#39;21_102-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10july&#39;21-102">&#91;101&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">&#91;b&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 11 July, the death of a woman in her 90s at <a href="/wiki/Liverpool_Hospital" title="Liverpool Hospital">Liverpool Hospital</a> in Sydney, the first COVID-19 death in Australia since mid-April, was reported by NSW Health. There were also 77 new locally acquired cases reported, with 52 of them from South Western Sydney <a href="/wiki/Ministry_of_Health_(New_South_Wales)" title="Ministry of Health (New South Wales)">Local Health District</a> (LHD), 11 from Sydney LHD and 10 from South Eastern Sydney LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11july&#39;21_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11july&#39;21-104">&#91;102&#93;</a></sup> Among social distancing rule changes, also announced that day, affecting funerals (only 10 may attend, down from 100), were tightened face mask rules, which came into effect on 13 July 2021 in Greater Sydney. From then, a face mask must be worn in indoor <a href="/wiki/Common_property" class="mw-redirect" title="Common property">common property</a> areas of residential premises that have:<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21-105">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-funeral-restrict+10july&#39;21_106-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-funeral-restrict+10july&#39;21-106">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Strata_title" title="Strata title">strata title</a></li>
<li>community title</li>
<li>company title</li></ul>
<p>Places on the common property requiring masks include:<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21_105-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21-105">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>an apartment blocks' lobby or foyer</li>
<li>corridors, stairwells and elevators</li>
<li>shared facilities such as laundries</li></ul>
<p>From 11 July, funerals in Greater Sydney were restricted to 10 people, plus those conducting the service.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-funeral-restrict+10july&#39;21_106-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-funeral-restrict+10july&#39;21-106">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 11 July, from 11:59pm Victoria closed its border to all New South Wales and Australian Capital Territory residents to try to prevent the Delta variant entering the state. 'Border bubble' arrangements for border towns remained in place.<sup id="cite_ref-smh-close-border-nsw-act-11july&#39;21_107-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh-close-border-nsw-act-11july&#39;21-107">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 12 July, the death of a man in his 70s from Sydneys' Eastern suburbs was reported. He was a confirmed COVID-19 case. This raised the number of deaths in NSW to 58.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21_108-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21-108">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup> Also on 12 July, 112 new locally acquired cases were reported, a total of 678 locally acquired cases since 16 June 2021, the start of the Bondi cluster. 84 of the new cases are from South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 16 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 7 Western Sydney LHD and 5 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. 2,703,690 doses of COVID-19 vaccine had been administered in the state.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-12jul&#39;21_109-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-12jul&#39;21-109">&#91;107&#93;</a></sup> Up to 8pm this day 49,055 tests were reported, the previous day's total was 46,478.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21_108-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21-108">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 12 July, the use of <a href="/wiki/QR_code" title="QR code">QR code</a> check-ins in retail stores, hire vehicles and many other settings, became mandatory in all NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-nsw-qr-mandatory-2-july&#39;21_110-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-nsw-qr-mandatory-2-july&#39;21-110">&#91;108&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 13 July there were 89 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June 2021 to 767. Of the new cases, 64 are from South Western Sydney LHD, 15 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 5 Sydney LHD, 3 Western Sydney LHD, 1&#160;Northern Sydney LHD and 1 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 65 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 21 in intensive care, 4 requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,263.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21_108-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-12july&#39;21-108">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also from 13 July, in Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Shellharbour and Wollongong, face masks had to be worn in indoor common property areas of rented or leased residential premises.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21_105-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-mask-restricts+-10july&#39;21-105">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h6><span class="mw-headline" id="Lockdown_extended_again">Lockdown extended again</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Lockdown extended again">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>
<p>On 14 July, the lockdown in Greater Sydney, due to end on 16 July, was extended by two weeks to 11:59pm on 30 July. There were 97 new COVID-19 cases reported, 70 of them in South West Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-sydney-lockdown-+2weeks_92-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-sydney-lockdown-+2weeks-92">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup> There were 71 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 20 in intensive care, 4 requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,362.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-14july&#39;21_111-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-14july&#39;21-111">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Week_3">Week 3</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Week 3">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>By 15 July,  there were 65 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June 2021 to 929. There were 73 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 19 in intensive care, 5 requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,429.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-15july&#39;21_112-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-15july&#39;21-112">&#91;110&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 16 July, one death was recorded, a man in his 80s from South West Sydney, bringing the total NSW deaths to 59.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21_113-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21-113">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup> That day, there were 97 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June 2021 to 1,026. There were 75 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 18 in intensive care, 4 requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,527.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-16july&#39;21_114-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-16july&#39;21-114">&#91;112&#93;</a></sup> Up to 8pm, there was a record of 81,970 COVID-19 tests performed this day, up from the 77,587 on 15 July. Vaccinations in NSW reached 2,975,525.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21_113-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21-113">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h6><span class="mw-headline" id="Lockdown_tightened">Lockdown tightened</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Lockdown tightened">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>
<p>On 17 July from 11:59pm, movement restrictions in some Western Sydney LGAs were increased, and impending business shut-downs and restrictions in NSW were announced. Most workers living in Canterbury-Bankstown, Fairfield and Liverpool LGAs were not permitted to leave those areas for work.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Exempt workers were:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>emergency workers</li>
<li>health workers
<ul><li>Included aged-care and disability workers</li></ul></li></ul>
<p>Carpooling, except with family members is banned in those three LGAs<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>On 19 July from 12:01am, in Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Shellharbour and Wollongong, many non-essential retail businesses will only be able to operate as take-away, home delivery, or "click and collect". From the same time:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>All construction work will be "paused"</li>
<li>In residential premises, all cleaning services, repair, and non-urgent maintenance, also "paused".</li></ul></li>
<li>From 21 July, at 12.01am employees must be allowed to work from home if possible.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-stop-delta_116-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-stop-delta-116">&#91;114&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>All the new restrictions were scheduled to cease at 11:59pm on 30 July,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup> but the lockdown was later extended to 28 August.
</p><p>On 17 July, one death occurred, a woman in her 90s from South Eastern Sydney. NSW COVID-19 deaths then totalled 60.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-18july&#39;21_117-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-18july&#39;21-117">&#91;115&#93;</a></sup> In the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 16 July there were 111 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June 2021 to 1,137. Of those, 29 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 69 were isolated while infectious, 10&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. 83 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD (60 of those from Fairfield LGA), 11 Western Sydney LHD, 8 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 7 Sydney LHD, and 2 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 75 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 18 in intensive care, 6&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,638.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21_113-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-17july&#39;21-113">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 17 July, the same day the new stay-at-home rules were announced for some of Western Sydney, there was a protest that afternoon at Paul Keating Park in <a href="/wiki/Bankstown" title="Bankstown">Bankstown</a> against the added lockdown rules for Canterbury-Bankstown, Fairfield and Liverpool. Two people were arrested and charged.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21_115-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-syd-tighten-17july&#39;21-115">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-news-com-nsw-lock-protest-17july&#39;21_118-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news-com-nsw-lock-protest-17july&#39;21-118">&#91;116&#93;</a></sup>
