</p><p>By 18 July, there were 105 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June 2021 to 1,242. Of those, 27 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 69 were isolated while infectious, 7 were isolated for part of their infectious period. There were also 4 overseas acquired cases. 76 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 9 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 12 Western Sydney LHD, 5 Sydney LHD, 1 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 76&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 18 in intensive care, 7&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,753.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-18july&#39;21_117-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-18july&#39;21-117">&#91;115&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 19 July, another death from COVID-19 was reported of a woman in her fifties at <a href="/wiki/Green_Valley,_New_South_Wales" title="Green Valley, New South Wales">Green Valley</a> in South West Sydney. It was the fifth in the outbreak that began in Bondi in June, and brought to 61 the number of COVID-19 deaths in NSW since the pandemic began.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-death-№5-19jul&#39;21_119-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-death-№5-19jul&#39;21-119">&#91;117&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-20july&#39;21_120-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-20july&#39;21-120">&#91;118&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 19 July, there were 98 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June 2021 to 1,340. Of those, 20 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 54 were isolated while infectious, 17 were isolated for part of their infectious period. There were also 2 overseas acquired cases. 67 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 7 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 11 Western Sydney LHD, 8 Sydney LHD, 2 Northern Sydney LHD, and 1 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 82&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 24 in intensive care, 7 requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 6,853.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-19july&#39;21_121-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-19july&#39;21-121">&#91;119&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 19 July, in Sydney all public transport services (train, bus and ferry) will operate on a Sunday timetable for at least 7 days. The NSW government announced grants through <a href="/wiki/Service_NSW" title="Service NSW">Service NSW</a> of up to A$15,000 for businesses to assist them during the lockdown.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-grants-transport-cut-19-july&#39;21_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-grants-transport-cut-19-july&#39;21-122">&#91;120&#93;</a></sup> Demand for the grants was enough that the Service NSW grants <a href="/wiki/Crash_(computing)" title="Crash (computing)">website crashed</a> due to the "unprecedented demand".<sup id="cite_ref-news-com-nsw-website-crash-19july&#39;21_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news-com-nsw-website-crash-19july&#39;21-123">&#91;121&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 20 July, the Los Angeles to Sydney route of <a href="/wiki/American_Airlines" title="American Airlines">American Airlines</a> (AA), their only Australian route, was announced by the airline to be cut out from 1 September until at least 28 October 2021. It was in response to COVID travel rules which resulted in AA planes flying with very few passengers.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-amer-airlines-cut-flights_124-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-amer-airlines-cut-flights-124">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> A week prior AA had stated they would fly some planes as cargo only.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-Amer-Airlines-cargo-13july&#39;21_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-Amer-Airlines-cargo-13july&#39;21-125">&#91;123&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h6><span class="mw-headline" id="Lockdown_area_expanded">Lockdown area expanded</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Lockdown area expanded">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>
<p>On 21 July from 12:01am, stay-at-home orders came into force, until 28 July at 12:01am, in the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Orange_(New_South_Wales)" title="City of Orange (New South Wales)">Orange City Council</a>, <a href="/wiki/Blayney_Shire_Council" class="mw-redirect" title="Blayney Shire Council">Blayney Shire Council</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Cabonne_Shire_Council" class="mw-redirect" title="Cabonne Shire Council">Cabonne Shire Council</a> areas of the <a href="/wiki/Central_West_(New_South_Wales)" title="Central West (New South Wales)">Central West of NSW</a>. The orders also applied to anyone who was in these areas on, or after, 17 July.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stay-home-20july&#39;21_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stay-home-20july&#39;21-126">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>masks had to be worn indoors
<ul><li>and outdoors if social distancing couldn't be maintained</li></ul></li>
<li>schools were open</li>
<li>after 12:01am on 23 July 2021 funeral attendance was capped at ten people<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stay-home-20july&#39;21_126-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stay-home-20july&#39;21-126">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>The stay-at-home orders were lifted as planned on 28 July.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-orange-27july&#39;21_127-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-orange-27july&#39;21-127">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p><a href="/wiki/New_South_Wales_Ministry_of_Health" class="mw-redirect" title="New South Wales Ministry of Health">New South Wales Ministry of Health</a> (NSW Health) figures of 21 July showed that, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 20 July, there were 110 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 1,528. Of those, 43 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 37&#160;were isolated while infectious, 17 were isolated for part of their infectious period. There were also 2 overseas acquired cases. 50 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 11 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 29&#160;Western Sydney LHD, 12 Sydney LHD, 6 Northern Sydney LHD, 1 from Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1 from Western NSW LHD. There were 106 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 23 in intensive care, 11&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 7,044.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-21july&#39;21_128-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-21july&#39;21-128">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Week_4">Week 4</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Week 4">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>By 22 July NSW Health statistics showed that, in the preceding 24 hours to 8pm on 21 July, there were 124 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 1,648. Of those, 48 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 37&#160;were isolated while infectious, 22 were isolated for part of their infectious period. There were no new overseas acquired cases. 54 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 8 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 40 Western Sydney LHD, 18 Sydney LHD, 2&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 1 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 118 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 28 in intensive care, 14&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 7,164.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-22july&#39;21_129-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-22july&#39;21-129">&#91;127&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 23 July the death occurred of a 89-year-old man from South West Sydney. He was the 62nd person to die in NSW after contracting COVID-19. The same day restrictions on workers leaving the <a href="/wiki/Cumberland,_New_South_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="Cumberland, New South Wales">Cumberland</a> and <a href="/wiki/Blacktown" title="Blacktown">Blacktown</a> LGAs were tightened. Only authorised workers may leave those LGAs.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-death-№62-23july&#39;21_130-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-death-№62-23july&#39;21-130">&#91;128&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-24july&#39;21_131-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-24july&#39;21-131">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 23 July, Queensland closed its border with NSW from 1:00am due to locations outside Greater Sydney reporting COVID-19 cases.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-qld-rules-23july&#39;21_132-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-qld-rules-23july&#39;21-132">&#91;130&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 24 July NSW Health statistics showed that, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 23 July, there were 163 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 1,940. Of those, 45 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 73&#160;were isolated while infectious, 26 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 67 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 14 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 45 Western Sydney LHD, 31 Sydney LHD, 4&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 1 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1 from Central Coast LHD. There were 139 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 37 in intensive care, 17&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 7,462.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-24july&#39;21_131-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-24july&#39;21-131">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 24 July 2021, there was an anti-lockdown protest in Sydney where several people were arrested, 90 infringement notices issued and 57 people were charged. The Sydney CBD was shut down for hours as several thousand people marched from <a href="/wiki/Camperdown,_New_South_Wales" title="Camperdown, New South Wales">Camperdown</a>, through <a href="/wiki/Broadway,_Sydney" title="Broadway, Sydney">Broadway</a> to <a href="/wiki/George_Street,_Sydney" title="George Street, Sydney">George Street</a>. A police taskforce, 'Seasoned', was established to identify people at the unauthorised march, which breached public health orders. There were also protests that day in Brisbane and Melbourne.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-protest-taskforce-24july&#39;21_133-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-protest-taskforce-24july&#39;21-133">&#91;131&#93;</a></sup> A new record of 102,233 COVID-19 tests were reported to 8pm that day, up from the previous days' 93,910.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21_134-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21-134">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 24 July, NSW local council elections already postponed from September 2020 to 4 September 2021<sup id="cite_ref-regional-nsw-elect-postponed-mar&#39;20_37-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-regional-nsw-elect-postponed-mar&#39;20-37">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup> were postponed again to 4 December. This was due to the wave of Delta COVID-19 variant infections that had caused numerous lockdowns in the state.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-elects-postponed-24july&#39;21_38-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-elects-postponed-24july&#39;21-38">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 25 July there were 2 COVID-19 related deaths early that morning. A woman in her 70s from South West Sydney, and a woman in her 30s from Sydney CBD died.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21_134-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21-134">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 25 July, in 24 hours to 8pm on 24 July, there were 141 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 2,081. Of those, 38 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 65&#160;were isolated while infectious, 24 were isolated for part of their infectious period. No new cases was overseas acquired. 62 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 10 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 46 Western Sydney LHD, 19 Sydney LHD, 1&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, and 3 from Central Coast LHD. There were 141 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 43 in intensive care, 18&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 7,603.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21_134-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-25july&#39;21-134">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 26 July there were 2 more deaths. A man in his 80s died in <a href="/wiki/Campbelltown_Hospital" title="Campbelltown Hospital">Campbelltown Hospital</a>, and a woman in her 80s died in <a href="/wiki/Pendle_Hill" title="Pendle Hill">Pendle Hill</a>. This brought the number of deaths during the state's Delta outbreak to 10 and the total number of deaths from COVID-19 in NSW to 66.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-+2deaths-26jul&#39;21_135-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-+2deaths-26jul&#39;21-135">&#91;133&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 July the 11th death from COVID-19 during the Sydney/NSW outbreak occurred when a 90-year-old woman died at <a href="/wiki/Liverpool_Hospital" title="Liverpool Hospital">Liverpool Hospital</a>. This was the 67th death from COVID-19 in NSW during the pandemic.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-28july&#39;21_136-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-28july&#39;21-136">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 27 July, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 26 July, there were 172 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 2,397. Of those, 60 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 61&#160;were isolated while infectious, 19 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 3 new cases were overseas acquired. 65 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 11 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 54 Western Sydney LHD, 27 Sydney LHD, 12&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, and 1&#160;case each in Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, Nepean Blue Mountains LHD and Southern NSW LHD. There were 169 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 46 in intensive care, 19&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 7,928.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-27july&#39;21_137-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-27july&#39;21-137">&#91;135&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 27 July, Victoria excluded the LGAs of <a href="/wiki/City_of_Wagga_Wagga" title="City of Wagga Wagga">City of Wagga Wagga</a>, <a href="/wiki/Hay_Shire_Council" class="mw-redirect" title="Hay Shire Council">Hay Shire Council</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lockhart_Shire_Council" class="mw-redirect" title="Lockhart Shire Council">Lockhart Shire Council</a> and <a href="/wiki/Murrumbidgee_Council" title="Murrumbidgee Council">Murrumbidgee Council</a> from the cross-border bubble due to the Delta variant outbreak in NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vic-nsw-bubble-exclude-27july&#39;1_138-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vic-nsw-bubble-exclude-27july&#39;1-138">&#91;136&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 28 July there were 2 more deaths. A woman in her 90s died at Liverpool Hospital, and a man in his 80s died <a href="/wiki/Royal_North_Shore_Hospital" title="Royal North Shore Hospital">Royal North Shore Hospital</a>. The total number of deaths from COVID-19 in NSW reached 69.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-29july&#39;21_139-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-29july&#39;21-139">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 28 July, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 27 July, there were 177 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 2,574. Of those, 46 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 47&#160;were isolated while infectious, 22 were isolated for part of their infectious period. No new cases were overseas acquired. 90 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 15 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 46 Western Sydney LHD, 20 Sydney LHD, 2&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, and 1&#160;in Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD and 3 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 165 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 56 in intensive care, 22&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 8,105. COVID-19 tests were 94,532 to 8pm for that day, up from the previous days 84,486, bringing the state total to 8,780,736. There were also 25,375 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,575,052.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-28july&#39;21_136-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-28july&#39;21-136">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup> Also on 28 July, the stay-at-home orders in Orange City Council, Blayney Shire Council, and Cabonne Shire Council areas were lifted as planned. Since 20 July there had been no more cases of COVID-19 in those areas.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-orange-27july&#39;21_127-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-orange-27july&#39;21-127">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h6><span id="Lockdown_extended.2C_again"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Lockdown_extended,_again">Lockdown extended, again</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Lockdown extended, again">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>
<p>Also on 28 July, the lockdown in Greater Sydney, and other NSW LGAs (Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Wollongong, Shellharbour) in lockdown that day, was extended again by 4 weeks, from 31 July to 12:01am on 28 August. Changes to be implemented are:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again_93-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again-93">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-restricts-8-lga-30July&#39;21_140-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-restricts-8-lga-30July&#39;21-140">&#91;138&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>shopping restricted to within 10&#160;km</li>
<li>construction work continuing, in certain situations<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup>
<ul><li>only outside the LGAs of concern</li>
<li>Only non-occupied settings (no residents present)
<ul><li>one worker per 4 square metres.</li></ul></li></ul></li>
<li>cleaners and trade workers allowed in 'occupied settings'
<ul><li>no contact allowed with residents</li></ul></li>
<li>single people living alone to get a 'support bubble'</li>
<li>a plan for students in Year 12 to get back into classrooms from 16 August</li>
<li>businesses and individuals get a new financial support package</li>
<li>Parramatta, Campbelltown and Georges River joined areas now subject to an 'Authorised Workers Order'. (Only authorised workers can leave those LGAs to work)
<ul><li>The same restriction already applied to Fairfield, Canterbury-Bankstown, Liverpool, Cumberland and Blacktown.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again_93-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-lockdown_extended-again-93">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup></li></ul></li></ul>
<p>By 29 July, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 28 July, there were 239 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 2,810. 239 was the highest daily new case number since early 2021 when the virus first arrived in NSW. Of the new cases, 61 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 81&#160;were isolated while infectious, 22 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 104 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 14 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 58 Western Sydney LHD, 51 Sydney LHD, 3&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 4&#160;in Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD and 5 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 182 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 54 in intensive care, 22&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 8,342. COVID-19 tests were 110,962 to 8pm for that day, a new record, up from the previous days 94,532, bringing the state total to 3,651,310. There were also 24,706 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 8,891,698.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-29july&#39;21_139-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-29july&#39;21-139">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-239-new-case-record_142-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-239-new-case-record-142">&#91;140&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 29 July, restrictions were tightened, mostly in Blacktown, Campbelltown, Canterbury-Bankstown, Cumberland, Fairfield Georges River, Liverpool, and Parramatta (the "8 LGAs of concern"):<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 12:01am on 30 July, in those areas people:
</p>
<ul><li>could not travel more than 5&#160;km (3 miles) from their home
<ul><li>including for shopping and exercise</li>
<li>including for 'singles bubble' travel</li></ul></li>
<li>have to always wear face masks while outside their homes.</li></ul>
<p>The fine for not adhering to facemask requirements was increased from A$200 to $500.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Construction will remain banned in the 8 nominated LGAs</li></ul>
<p>From 12:01am on 31 July, if they leave the LGA for work authorised workers in Canterbury-Bankstown must get a COVID-19 test every three days.
</p><p>In Greater Sydney, the Blue Mountains, Central Coast, Shellharbour and Wollongong:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>essential goods shopping only allowed:
<ul><li>within your LGA</li>
<li>within 10&#160;km of home</li></ul></li></ul>
<p>One exception, if the item is not available locally.
</p><p>Under the 'singles bubble', people living alone may nominate a person to visit their home:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Your visitor cannot be from one of the 8 LGAs causing concern, unless you live in one of those LGAs
<ul><li>If you do, the visitor must be from within 5&#160;km of your home<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21_141-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tighter-restricts-29jul&#39;21-141">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup></li></ul></li></ul>
<p>The same day, NSW Police requested Australian Defence Force assistance to help them in compliance and logistics. Commissioner <a href="/wiki/Mick_Fuller" title="Mick Fuller">Mick Fuller</a> requested 300 ADF personnel.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-adf-300-29jul&#39;21_143-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-adf-300-29jul&#39;21-143">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>From 2 August all non-urgent <a href="/wiki/Elective_surgery" title="Elective surgery">elective surgery</a> in Greater Sydney, excepting the Illawarra Shoalhaven and Central Coast Local Health Districts, is to be postponed to ensure resources are available for medical response during the ongoing outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-surgery-suspend_144-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-surgery-suspend-144">&#91;142&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 July a man in his 60s died in South West Sydney, the 14th death of the Delta outbreak,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-+1death-31july&#39;21_145-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-+1death-31july&#39;21-145">&#91;143&#93;</a></sup> and the 70th in NSW.
</p><p>By 30 July, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 29 July, there were 170 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 2,980. Of the new cases, 42 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 41&#160;were isolated while infectious, 10 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 87 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 13 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 32 Western Sydney LHD, 32 Sydney LHD, 2&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, and 4&#160;from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. There were 187 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 58 in intensive care, 24&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 8,514. COVID-19 tests were 95,446 to 8pm for that day, down from the previous days' record 110,962, bringing the state total to 8,987,144. There were also 26,408 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,732,331.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-30july&#39;21_146-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-30july&#39;21-146">&#91;144&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 31 July, 14-day stay-at-home orders were issued, effective from 6pm, for anyone in NSW who, since 21 July, had been in any of the 11 LGAs in <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_Queensland#2021" title="COVID-19 pandemic in Queensland">SE Queensland locked down on 31 July</a>. Anyone sharing such a persons' residence should also stay-at-home.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-ex-qld-stay-at-home_147-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-ex-qld-stay-at-home-147">&#91;145&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 31 July, in the previous 24 hours to 8pm on 30 July, there were 210 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 3,190.  Of the new cases, 21 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 58&#160;were isolated while infectious, 11 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 81 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 11 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 72 Western Sydney LHD, 38 Sydney LHD, 4&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 2 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD and 1 from Central Coast LHD. There were 203 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 53 in intensive care, 27&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 8,725. COVID-19 tests were 105,963 to 8pm for that day, up from the previous days 95,446 and bringing the state total to 9,093,107. There were also 26,872 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,816,432.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-31july&#39;21_90-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-31july&#39;21-90">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="August">August</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: August">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 1 August a man aged in his 90s died at Liverpool Hospital. He was from south west Sydney and is the 15th death in the Delta outbreak and the 71st COVID-19 related death in NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2aug&#39;21_148-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2aug&#39;21-148">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 1 August, to 8pm on 31 July, there were 239 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 3,427. Of the new cases, 26 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 80&#160;were isolated while infectious, 35 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 110 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 3 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 51 Western Sydney LHD, 69 Sydney LHD, 4 from Northern Sydney LHD and 2 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD.  115 cases are linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 124 were under investigation. There were 222 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 54 in intensive care, 25&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 8,964. COVID-19 tests were 87,712 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,180,819.  There were also 21,342 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,893,122.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-stats-1aug&#39;21_149-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-stats-1aug&#39;21-149">&#91;147&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 2 August, to 8pm on 1 August, there were 207 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 3,634. Of the new cases, 51 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 89&#160;were isolated while infectious, 21 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 83 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 17 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 53 Western Sydney LHD, 48 Sydney LHD, and 6 from Northern Sydney LHD. 105 cases are linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 102 were under investigation. There were 232 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 54&#160;in intensive care, 25&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 9,171. COVID-19 tests were a new record of 117,009 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,297,828.There were also 14,497 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,932,108.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2aug&#39;21_148-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2aug&#39;21-148">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 3 August two people died from COVID-19 in Sydney, both were confirmed COVID cases. One was a man in his twenties with no related health conditions who died in his home. The <a href="/wiki/NSW_Coroner" class="mw-redirect" title="NSW Coroner">NSW Coroner</a> had this death referred for investigation. The other death was a woman in her eighties at <a href="/wiki/Royal_Prince_Alfred_Hospital" title="Royal Prince Alfred Hospital">Royal Prince Alfred Hospital</a> (RPA). This brought COVID deaths in NSW to 73.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4aug&#39;21_150-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4aug&#39;21-150">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-+2dead-+233cases-4aug&#39;21_151-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-+2dead-+233cases-4aug&#39;21-151">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 3 August, to 8pm on 2 August, there were 199 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 3,832. Of the new cases, 50 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 70&#160;were isolated while infectious, 32 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 3 new cases were overseas acquired. 73 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 9 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 67 Western Sydney LHD, 35 Sydney LHD, 3 Northern Sydney LHD and 12 from Nepean Blue Mountains LHD. 88 cases are linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 111 were under investigation. There were 250&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 53 in intensive care, 20&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 9,372. COVID-19 tests were 104,536 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,402,364. There were also 25,312 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for a state total of 3,968,811.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3aug&#39;21_152-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3aug&#39;21-152">&#91;150&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 4 August, five people died from COVID-19 in NSW. All were confirmed confirmed COVID cases. Four of the five dead were male, three in their 60s, one in his 70s, and one female in her 80s. Three of the dead were from Sydney's south west, one inner west, and the last western Sydney. This brought deaths in NSW during the Delta outbreak to 21, and the entire pandemic to 78.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5aug&#39;21_153-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5aug&#39;21-153">&#91;151&#93;</a></sup> <br />By 4 August, to 8pm on 3 August, there were 233 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 4,063. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW since the beginning of the pandemic reached 9,604. There were 286 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 53 in intensive care, 23&#160;requiring ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4aug&#39;21_150-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4aug&#39;21-150">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 5 August there was one COVID-19 death, a woman in her 60s died at Liverpool Hospital. She had been admitted for kidney problems, not COVID, and was  infected while in the hospital, which had an outbreak. The number of deaths in NSW reached 79.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6aug&#39;21_154-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6aug&#39;21-154">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-291-6aug&#39;21_155-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-291-6aug&#39;21-155">&#91;153&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 5 August new stay-at-home orders were issued for <a href="/wiki/Cessnock,_New_South_Wales" title="Cessnock, New South Wales">Cessnock</a>, <a href="/wiki/Dungog" class="mw-redirect" title="Dungog">Dungog</a>, Lake Macquarie, Maitland, <a href="/wiki/Muswellbrook" class="mw-redirect" title="Muswellbrook">Muswellbrook</a> Newcastle, <a href="/wiki/Port_Stephens,_New_South_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="Port Stephens, New South Wales">Port Stephens</a> and <a href="/wiki/Singleton,_New_South_Wales" title="Singleton, New South Wales">Singleton</a> from 5pm that day until 12:01am on 13 August. The orders apply to people who have been in these areas on, or after, 31 July.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stay-home-5aug&#39;21_156-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stay-home-5aug&#39;21-156">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> These restrictions were extended to 20 August, on 12 August.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21-157">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup> NSW was to receive about 180,000 doses of Pfizer COVID vaccine from the Commonwealth government to allow NSW Health to rebook vaccinations affected by reallocation of doses to year 12 students in south west and western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stay-home-5aug&#39;21_156-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stay-home-5aug&#39;21-156">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 6 August, another five people died from COVID-19 in NSW. A woman in her 80s, and 2 men, one in his 80s, the other in his 90s, died at Liverpool Hospital. There were now 5 deaths linked to the outbreak at that hospital. A man in his 60s also died there, but was infected elsewhere. The fifth new death was a man in his 80s at Royal Prince Alfred Hospital. Four of the dead were from Sydney's south west, one from the inner west. There were then 27 COVID-related deaths in NSW during the Delta outbreak, and 84 since the pandemic started in 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7aug&#39;21_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7aug&#39;21-158">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 6 August, to 8pm on 5 August, there were 291 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 4,610. Of the new cases, 48 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 91&#160;were isolated while infectious, 48 were isolated for part of their infectious period. No new cases were overseas acquired. 123 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 13 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 84 Western Sydney LHD, 30 Sydney LHD, 5 Northern Sydney LHD,  24 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 8&#160;Central Coast LHD, and 4 Hunter New England LHD. 120 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 161 were under investigation. There were 304 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 50 in intensive care, 22&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 10,157. COVID-19 tests were 109,547 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,726,443. There were 24,894 COVID-19 vaccinations administered by NSW Health, and a state total of 4,221,181.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6aug&#39;21_154-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6aug&#39;21-154">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 7 August there was one COVID-19 death, a woman in her 80s died at RPA Hospital. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 84, and 28 since 16&#160;June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21_159-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21-159">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup> Also on 7 August, the <a href="/wiki/Armidale_Regional_Council" title="Armidale Regional Council">Armidale Regional LGA</a> went into lockdown from 5pm that day until 12.01am on 15&#160;August. The same rules applied as in Greater Sydney and other regions in lockdown. Until 10 August weddings and funerals will be allowed, after which they will be banned, and funeral mourners will be limited to 10. The lockdown applies to anyone who has been in the LGA on, or after, 29 July 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-armidale-lockdown-7aug&#39;21_160-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-armidale-lockdown-7aug&#39;21-160">&#91;158&#93;</a></sup> On 14 August the lockdown in Armidale Regional LGA (including <a href="/wiki/Armidale" class="mw-redirect" title="Armidale">Armidale</a> and <a href="/wiki/Guyra" class="mw-redirect" title="Guyra">Guyra</a> towns) was extended until 12:01am on 22 August,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21-161">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup> but from 5pm that day all of regional NSW joined Sydney in lockdown.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21_94-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21-94">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 7 August, to 8pm on 6 August, there were 319 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 4,929. Of the new cases, 51 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 138&#160;were isolated while infectious, 32 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 112 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 20 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 98 Western Sydney LHD, 57 Sydney LHD, 7 Northern Sydney LHD,  23 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 2 Hunter New England LHD. 125 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 194 were under investigation. There were 345 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 56 in intensive care, 23&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 10,478. COVID-19 tests were 108,449 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,834,892. There were 26,152 COVID-19 vaccinations administered by NSW Health, and a state total of 4,316,065.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7aug&#39;21_158-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7aug&#39;21-158">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 8 August there was one COVID-19 death, a woman in her 90s died at <a href="/wiki/Pallister,_Greenwich" title="Pallister, Greenwich">Greenwich Hospital</a>. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 85 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 29 in NSW since 16&#160;June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9aug&#39;21_162-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9aug&#39;21-162">&#91;160&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 8 August, 12 suburbs in the City of Penrith LGA were identified as areas of concern due to increased community transmission and had extra restrictions applied from 5pm. The affected suburbs were:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21_159-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21-159">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Caddens" class="mw-redirect" title="Caddens">Caddens</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Claremont_Meadows" class="mw-redirect" title="Claremont Meadows">Claremont Meadows</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Colyton,_New_South_Wales" title="Colyton, New South Wales">Colyton</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Erskine_Park" class="mw-redirect" title="Erskine Park">Erskine Park</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Kemps_Creek" class="mw-redirect" title="Kemps Creek">Kemps Creek</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Kingswood,_New_South_Wales" title="Kingswood, New South Wales">Kingswood</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Mount_Vernon,_New_South_Wales" title="Mount Vernon, New South Wales">Mount Vernon</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/North_St_Marys" class="mw-redirect" title="North St Marys">North St Marys</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Orchard_Hills,_New_South_Wales" title="Orchard Hills, New South Wales">Orchard Hills</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Oxley_Park" class="mw-redirect" title="Oxley Park">Oxley Park</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/St_Clair,_New_South_Wales" title="St Clair, New South Wales">St Clair</a></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/St_Marys,_New_South_Wales" title="St Marys, New South Wales">St Marys</a><sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21_159-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21-159">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>By 8 August, to 8pm on 7 August, there were 262 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 5,169. Of the new cases, 51 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 138&#160;were isolated while infectious, 32 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 6 new cases were overseas acquired. 88 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 17 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 88 Western Sydney LHD, 31 Sydney LHD, 3 Northern Sydney LHD, 21 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 12 Hunter New England LHD and 2 Central Coast LHD. 88 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 174 were under investigation. There were 362 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 58 in intensive care, 24 &#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 10,728. COVID-19 tests were 95,480 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 9,930,372 tests. There were 20,612 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,657,342 doses total by NSW Health, plus another 2,742,682 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,400,024 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21_159-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8aug&#39;21-159">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup> Of the days 58&#160;intensive care cases, 5 were aged in their 20s, 7 in their 30s, 4 in their 40s, 17 in their 50s, 7 in their 60s, 15 in their 70s and 3 in their 80s.<sup id="cite_ref-msn-262-cases-8aug&#39;21_163-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msn-262-cases-8aug&#39;21-163">&#91;161&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 9 August there were four COVID-19 deaths. A man in his 80s died at Liverpool Hospital, his was the sixth death linked to the outbreak at that hospital as he acquired his infection as part of it. A woman in her 80s also died at Liverpool Hospital, but her death was not linked to the Hospitals' outbreak. A man in his 70s died at <a href="/wiki/Nepean_Hospital" title="Nepean Hospital">Nepean Hospital</a>, and a man in his 80s at RPA Hospital, but that death was not linked to any outbreak in NSW as his infection was overseas acquired. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 89 since the beginning of the pandemic, 32 in NSW since 16 June caused by the Delta outbreak,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10aug&#39;21_164-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10aug&#39;21-164">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup> and 940  nationwide.<sup id="cite_ref-comm-health-oz-10aug&#39;21_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-comm-health-oz-10aug&#39;21-165">&#91;163&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 9 August the town of <a href="/wiki/Tamworth,_New_South_Wales" title="Tamworth, New South Wales">Tamworth</a> in the <a href="/wiki/New_England_(New_South_Wales)" title="New England (New South Wales)">New England</a> region went into lockdown at 5pm until 12.01am on 17 August. This follows an unknowingly infectious young woman travelling to Tamworth from <a href="/wiki/Newcastle,_New_South_Wales" title="Newcastle, New South Wales">Newcastle</a> on 5 August and visiting several venues in the town. Stay-at-home orders applied to anyone who had been there on, or after, 5 August. The same rules applied as in Greater Sydney and other regions in lockdown<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-tamworth-lockdown-9aug&#39;21_166-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-tamworth-lockdown-9aug&#39;21-166">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The same day <a href="/wiki/Ballina_Shire" title="Ballina Shire">Ballina Shire</a>, <a href="/wiki/Byron_Shire" title="Byron Shire">Byron Shire</a>, the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Lismore" title="City of Lismore">City of Lismore</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Richmond_Valley_Council" title="Richmond Valley Council">Richmond Valley Council</a> Local Government Areas on the <a href="/wiki/North_Coast,_New_South_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="North Coast, New South Wales">NSW north coast</a>, went into lockdown from 6pm until 12:01 pm on 17 August. This occurred when a man from Sydney tested positive to the Delta strain after travelling to the Byron Shire and falling ill. The stay-at-home orders  apply to all people who have been in these areas on, or after, 31 July.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-byron-lockdown-9aug&#39;21_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-byron-lockdown-9aug&#39;21-167">&#91;165&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-nth-coast-lockdown-9aug&#39;21_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-nth-coast-lockdown-9aug&#39;21-168">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup> The man who caused the lockdown was charged by NSW Police with breaching public health orders.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-byron-lockdown-charged-11aug&#39;21_169-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-byron-lockdown-charged-11aug&#39;21-169">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 9 August, to 8pm on 8 August, there were 283 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16 June to 5,452. Of the new cases, 64 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 106&#160;were isolated while infectious, 42 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. Allocation of cases to different LHDs was not reported for this day. 113 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 170 were under investigation.  There were 349 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 67 in intensive care, 29&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 11,012. COVID-19 tests were 133,840 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,064,212 tests. There were 11,327 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,668,669 doses total by NSW Health, plus another 2,780,387 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,449,056 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9aug&#39;21_162-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9aug&#39;21-162">&#91;160&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 10 August there were two COVID-19 deaths. A man in his 30s, with  underlying health conditions,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-+2deaths-11aug&#39;21_170-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-+2deaths-11aug&#39;21-170">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup> died at <a href="/wiki/Northern_Beaches_Hospital" title="Northern Beaches Hospital">Northern Beaches Hospital</a>, and man in his 90s died at <a href="/wiki/Concord_Repatriation_General_Hospital" title="Concord Repatriation General Hospital">Concord Hospital</a> (Concord Repatriation General Hospital aka CRGH). The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 91 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 34 since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21_171-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21-171">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 10 August, to 8pm on 9 August, there were 356 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 5,805. Of the new cases, 57 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 102&#160;were isolated while infectious, 40 were isolated for part of their infectious period. 4 new cases were overseas acquired. 113  of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 38 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 121 Western Sydney LHD, 40 Sydney LHD, 7 Northern Sydney LHD,  24 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 13 Hunter New England LHD. 147 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 209 were under investigation. There were 357 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 60 in intensive care, 28&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 11,369. COVID-19 tests were 95,037 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,159,248 tests. There were 29,160 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,697,829 doses total by NSW Health, plus another 2,794,543 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,492,372 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10aug&#39;21_164-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10aug&#39;21-164">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 11 August there were two COVID-19 deaths. A man in his 90s died at Liverpool Hospital, having acquired his infection as part of the outbreak there, the sixth deaths linked to the outbreak at that hospital. The other death was man in his 90s, a resident at Wyoming Residential Aged Care Facility in Summer Hill, died at <a href="/wiki/Royal_North_Shore_Hospital" title="Royal North Shore Hospital">Royal North Shore Hospital</a> (RNSH). The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 93 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 36 since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12aug&#39;21_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12aug&#39;21-172">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup><br />Also on 11 August, the town of <a href="/wiki/Dubbo" title="Dubbo">Dubbo</a> in the central northern <a href="/wiki/Orana_Region" class="mw-redirect" title="Orana Region">Orana Region</a> went into lockdown at 1pm until 12.01am on 19&#160;August.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21_171-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21-171">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Bogan_Shire" title="Bogan Shire">Bogan</a>, <a href="/wiki/Bourke_Shire" title="Bourke Shire">Bourke</a>, <a href="/wiki/Brewarrina_Shire" title="Brewarrina Shire">Brewarrina</a>, <a href="/wiki/Coonamble_Shire" title="Coonamble Shire">Coonamble</a>, <a href="/wiki/Gilgandra_Shire" title="Gilgandra Shire">Gilgandra</a>, <a href="/wiki/Narromine_Shire" title="Narromine Shire">Narromine</a>, <a href="/wiki/Walgett_Shire" title="Walgett Shire">Walgett</a> and <a href="/wiki/Warren_Shire" title="Warren Shire">Warren</a> LGAs, also locked down from 7pm that day, until the beginning of 19 August 2021. Stay-at-home orders will apply to anyone has been in these areas on, or after, 5&#160;August 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-walgett-etc-lockdown-11aug&#39;21_173-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-walgett-etc-lockdown-11aug&#39;21-173">&#91;171&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-walgett-lockdown-11aug&#39;21_174-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-walgett-lockdown-11aug&#39;21-174">&#91;172&#93;</a></sup> On 13 August NSW Health announced that from 16&#160;August (Monday) non-urgent <a href="/wiki/Elective_surgery" title="Elective surgery">elective surgery</a> was to be postponed at <a href="/w/index.php?title=Dubbo_Base_Hospital&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Dubbo Base Hospital (page does not exist)">Dubbo Base Hospital</a> to keep beds available if needed.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-dubbo-surgery-13aug&#39;21_175-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-dubbo-surgery-13aug&#39;21-175">&#91;173&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 11 August, to 8pm on 10 August, there were 344 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 6,149. Of the new cases, 65 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 43&#160;were isolated while infectious, 36&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. No new cases were overseas acquired. 112 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 23 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 110 Western Sydney LHD, 29 Sydney LHD, 7 Northern Sydney LHD, 43 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 14 Hunter New England LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD, 1 Northern NSW LHD, and 1 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD. 115&#160;cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 229 were under investigation. There were 357 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 60 in intensive care, 28&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 11,713. COVID-19 tests were 119,256, up on the previous days 95,037, to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,278,504 tests. There were 30,510 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,697,829 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 2,863,627 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,532,296 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21_171-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11aug&#39;21-171">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 12 August there were another two COVID-19 deaths. A woman in her 40s, died at home in North West Sydney, and man in his 90s died died at RFBI Hawkins Masonic Retirement Village in <a href="/wiki/Edgeworth,_New_South_Wales" title="Edgeworth, New South Wales">Edgeworth</a>, near Newcastle. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 95 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 38 since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21_78-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21-78">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 12 August, to 8pm on 11 August, there were 345 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 6,491. Of the new cases, 57 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 116&#160;were isolated while infectious, 34&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 120 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 19 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 85 Western Sydney LHD, 61 Sydney LHD, 25 Northern Sydney LHD, 24 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 25 Hunter New England LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD, 7 Northern NSW LHD, 2 Western NSW LHD, and 2 unknown. 128 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 217 were under investigation. There were 374 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 62 in intensive care, 29&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 12,056. COVID-19 tests were 151,830, up on the previous days 119,256, to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,430,334 tests. There were 30,425 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,758,764 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 2,939,709 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,698,473 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12aug&#39;21_172-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12aug&#39;21-172">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 12 August, new restrictions were introduced in some Sydney and regional areas, and a number of changes were made to existing rules:<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21_157-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21-157">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>the stay-at-home orders for the Newcastle and Hunter regions were extended to 20 August</li>
<li>from 5pm additional restrictions applied to residents of Sydney's <a href="/wiki/Bayside_Council" title="Bayside Council">Bayside</a>, <a href="/wiki/Municipality_of_Burwood" title="Municipality of Burwood">Burwood</a> and <a href="/wiki/Municipality_of_Strathfield" title="Municipality of Strathfield">Strathfield</a> Local Government Areas (LGAs) which are now "declared areas"
<ul><li>Bayside LGA includes the suburbs: Banksia, Bexley, Botany, Brighton le-Sands, Kogarah, Mascot, Rockdale and Sans Souci.</li>
<li>Strathfield LGA includes: Belfield, Flemington, Greenacre, Homebush, Homebush West, Strathfield and Strathfield South</li>
<li>Burwood LGA: includes Burwood, Burwood Heights, Enfield and Enfield South</li></ul></li>
<li>those in a declared area can only obtain: food, or other goods and services; or exercise; within 5&#160;km of their home.</li>
<li>they may only travel outside their declared area for work if they are an authorised worker</li></ul>
<p>Following the <a href="/wiki/Australian_Capital_Territory" title="Australian Capital Territory">Australian Capital Territory</a> (ACT) going into lockdown on 12 August at 5pm:<sup id="cite_ref-cbr-times-act-lockdown-12aug&#39;21_176-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbr-times-act-lockdown-12aug&#39;21-176">&#91;174&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Anyone in NSW, who was in the ACT since 5 August, must isolate under stay-at-home rules
<ul><li>may only leave their residence with a "reasonable excuse"<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21_157-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-covid-changes-additions-12aug&#39;21-157">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup></li></ul></li></ul>
<p>On 13 August there were four more COVID-19 deaths. A man in his 70s died at Liverpool Hospital; a woman in her 40s, and a man in his 80s died at Concord Hospital (CRGH); a woman in her 70s died at <a href="/wiki/Campbelltown_Hospital" title="Campbelltown Hospital">Campbelltown Hospital</a>. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 99 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 43 since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21_161-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21-161">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 13 August, restrictions on leaving Greater Sydney were tightened. Residents will have to obtain a permit to leave the region. Visiting holidays homes will only be permitted under "special circumstances", and limited to one person. From 16 August people who had to isolate when awaiting COVID-19 test results could be paid $320 to compensate for lost wages.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-gtrsyd-tightened-13aug&#39;21_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-gtrsyd-tightened-13aug&#39;21-177">&#91;175&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 13 August, to 8pm on 12 August, there were 390 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 6,874. Of the new cases, 58 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 98&#160;were isolated while infectious, 43&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 123 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 30 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 138 Western Sydney LHD, 47 Sydney LHD, 7 Northern Sydney LHD, 32 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 5 Hunter New England LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD, and 6 Western NSW LHD. 140 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 250 were under investigation. There were 391 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 63 in intensive care, 30&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 12,440. COVID-19 tests were 127,988 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,558,322 tests. There were 28,198 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,786,962 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,014,348 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,801,310 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21_78-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13aug&#39;21-78">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="14_August_-_Regional_NSW_in_lockdown">14 August - Regional NSW in lockdown</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: 14 August - Regional NSW in lockdown">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown,_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga,_NSW_26.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg/220px-August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg/330px-August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg/440px-August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown%2C_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga%2C_NSW_26.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4032" data-file-height="3024" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:August_2021_Regional_NSW_snap_lockdown,_16_August_in_Wagga_Wagga,_NSW_26.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Wagga Wagga on 16 August 2021</div></div></div>
<p>On 14 August there were another 4 COVID-19 deaths, a woman in her 50s at Campbelltown Hospital, a woman in her 80s at RPA, a man in his 80s at Liverpool Hospital, and a woman in her 70s at RNSH. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 104 since the beginning of the pandemic, and since 16 June, 48 deaths during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21_178-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21-178">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 14 August, all of regional NSW went into lockdown from 5pm, initially until 12:01am on 22 August (Sunday),<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21_94-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21-94">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup> extended on 19 August to 28 August,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-reg-lckdwn-+7days-19aug&#39;21_179-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-reg-lckdwn-+7days-19aug&#39;21-179">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup> and again extended on 26 August to 10 September due to growing case numbers in Western NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21_180-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21-180">&#91;178&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 14 August, to 8pm on 13 August, there were 466 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 6,874. Of the new cases, 68 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 76&#160;were isolated while infectious, 19&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 106 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 30 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 166 Western Sydney LHD, 37 Sydney LHD, 15 Northern Sydney LHD, 59 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 16 Hunter New England LHD, 5 Central Coast LHD, 26 Western NSW LHD, 2 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, 4&#160;unknown LHD. 121 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 345 were under investigation. There were 378 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 64 in intensive care, 29&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 12,903. COVID-19 tests were 129,352 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,687,674 tests. There were 29,397 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,816,359 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,092,481 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 4,908,840 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21_161-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14aug&#39;21-161">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 15 August there were another 8 deaths of people with COVID-19:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21_178-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21-178">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup> <br />
• A man in his 40s at Liverpool Hospital, and 3 men in their 80s, 2 at Campbelltown Hospital, 1 at Nepean Hospital. <br />
• One woman in her 70s at RNSH.<br />
• A man in his 70s at Liverpool Hospital, a patient in the <a href="/wiki/Geriatric" class="mw-redirect" title="Geriatric">geriatric</a> ward. His was the 8th death linked to this hospital's outbreak.<br />
• A woman in her 80s at RPA, a resident of the Wyoming Residential Aged Care Facility. She is the 3rd death linked to this facilitys' cluster.<br />
• A 15-year-old boy died at <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Children%E2%80%99s_Hospital" class="mw-redirect" title="Sydney Children’s Hospital">Sydney Children’s Hospital</a>. He was a confirmed COVID case, but was also receiving treatment for a serious medical condition.<br />The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 112 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 56 during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21_178-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21-178">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 15 August, to 8pm on 14 August, there were 415 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 7,745. Of the new cases, 42 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 76&#160;were isolated while infectious, 24&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. 2 new case was overseas acquired. 98 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 31 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 167 Western Sydney LHD, 42 Sydney LHD, 6 Northern Sydney LHD, 36 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 9 Hunter New England LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD, 21 Western NSW LHD, 3&#160;unknown LHD. 139 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 276 were under investigation. There were 381 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 62 in intensive care, 24&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 13,314. COVID-19 tests were 126,790 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,814,464 tests. There were 24,419 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,840,778 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,168,679 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,009,457 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-15aug&#39;21_181-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-15aug&#39;21-181">&#91;179&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>There was 1 death reported on 16 August of a person with COVID, a woman in her 70s at <a href="/wiki/Westmead_Hospital" title="Westmead Hospital">Westmead Hospital</a>. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 113 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 57 deaths since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17aug&#39;21_182-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17aug&#39;21-182">&#91;180&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 16 August, to 8pm on 15 August, there were 478 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 8,218. Of the new cases, 61 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 97&#160;were isolated while infectious, 30&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. For 290 cases', the isolation status was under investigation. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 183 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 144 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 183 Western Sydney LHD, 43 Sydney LHD, 4 Northern Sydney LHD, 18 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 16 Hunter New England LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD, 35 Western NSW LHD, 6&#160;not assigned to any LHD. 141 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 337 were under investigation. There were 391 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 66 in intensive care, 28&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 13,789. COVID-19 tests were 156,495 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 10,970,959 tests. There were 18,968 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,859,746 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,209,894 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,069,640 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21_178-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16aug&#39;21-178">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 17 August there were another 3 deaths of people with COVID-19:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21_183-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21-183">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup><br />
• A man in his 60s died at Liverpool Hospital, a geriatric ward patient there, the 9th death linked to this hospitals' outbreak.<br />
• Two men, both in their 70s, died at Nepean Hospital. One of these was the first in an outbreak at Nepean.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21_184-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21-184">&#91;182&#93;</a></sup> <br />
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 116 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 60 deaths during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21_183-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21-183">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 17 August, to 8pm on 16 August, there were 452 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 8,654.  Of the new cases, 30 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 101&#160;were isolated while infectious, 24&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. For 297 cases, their isolation status was under investigation. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 132 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 24 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 189 Western Sydney LHD, 32 Sydney LHD, 13 Northern Sydney LHD, 25 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 10 Hunter New England, 1 Central Coast LHD, 18 Western NSW LHD, 1 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, 7 &#160;not assigned to any LHD. 129 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 323 were under investigation. There were 447 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 69 in intensive care, 24&#160;requiring ventilation. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 14,227. COVID-19 tests were 151,767 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 11,122,726 tests. There were 36,817 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,896,563 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,341,115 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,237,678 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17aug&#39;21_182-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17aug&#39;21-182">&#91;180&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 17 August, a <a href="/wiki/Byron_Bay_Bluesfest" title="Byron Bay Bluesfest">Byron Bay Bluesfest</a> event arranged for October 2021, after the usual April date was cancelled a day before it was to start, was cancelled by the organisers. The next Bluesfest is now scheduled for 15–19 April 2022.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bfnov&#39;21-cancel-17aug&#39;21_185-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bfnov&#39;21-cancel-17aug&#39;21-185">&#91;183&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 18 August there was 1 death reported of a person with COVID, a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/St_George_Hospital,_Sydney" class="mw-redirect" title="St George Hospital, Sydney">St George Hospital</a>. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 117 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 61 deaths since 16 June during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19aug&#39;21_186-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19aug&#39;21-186">&#91;184&#93;</a></sup> Also on 18 August, NSW Health announced, from 23 August (Monday), the " ... temporary suspension of non-urgent elective surgery to free up staff to support the pandemic response." at 29 private hospitals across NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-private-surgery-18aug&#39;21_187-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-private-surgery-18aug&#39;21-187">&#91;185&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 18 August, to 8pm on 17 August, there were 633 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 9,280. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 14,854. Of the new cases, 62 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 94&#160;were isolated while infectious, 30&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. For 444 cases, their isolation status was under investigation. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 224 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 24 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 216 Western Sydney LHD, 52 Sydney LHD, 6 Northern Sydney LHD, 54 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 15 Hunter New England, 23 Western NSW LHD, 4 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, 4 Far West LHD, 11&#160;not assigned to any LHD. 158 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 475 were under investigation. There were 462 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 77 in intensive care, 25&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 102,749 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 11,225,475 tests. There were 36,175 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,932,738 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,420,626 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,353,364 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21_183-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18aug&#39;21-183">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>The same day, <a href="/wiki/Blacktown_City_Council" title="Blacktown City Council">Blacktown City Council</a>, one of the 'LGAs of concern', closed all outdoor gym equipment and playgrounds on police advice as people were using them for recreation, rather than exercising.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-blktown-play-gyms-close-18aug&#39;21_188-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-blktown-play-gyms-close-18aug&#39;21-188">&#91;186&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 19 August there were another 4 deaths reported of people with COVID-19:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21_184-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21-184">&#91;182&#93;</a></sup> <br />
• a woman in her 80s at RNSH, a resident of the Wyoming Aged Care Facility, the 4th death linked to this cluster.<br />
• a woman in her 80s at Campbelltown Hospital <br />
• a man in his 70s  at St George Hospital, where he acquired his infection<br />
• a man in his 80s at Nepean Hospital, where he also acquired the infection.
An outbreak at Nepean has now been linked to 2 deaths. The other was a man in his 70s who died on 17 August as reported previously.
</p><p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 121 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 65 during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21_184-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20aug&#39;21-184">&#91;182&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 19 August, the end of the lockdown of regional NSW was extended from 22 to 28 August.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-reg-lckdwn-+7days-19aug&#39;21_179-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-reg-lckdwn-+7days-19aug&#39;21-179">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 19 August, to 8pm on 18 August, there were 681 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 9,950. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 15,528. Of the new cases, 59 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 135&#160;were isolated while infectious, 28&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. For 459 cases, their isolation status was under investigation. 3 new cases were overseas acquired. 172 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 29 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 291 Western Sydney LHD, 63 Sydney LHD, 14 Northern Sydney LHD, 74 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 15 Hunter New England, 25 Western NSW LHD, 5 Hunter New England LHD, 1 Central Coast LHD, 1 Mid North Coast LHD, and 1 Southern NSW LHD. 5&#160;not assigned to any LHD. 170 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 511 were under investigation. There were 474 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 82 in intensive care, 25&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 119,310 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 11,344,785 tests. There were 42,301 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 1,975,039 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,499,517 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,474,556 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19aug&#39;21_186-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19aug&#39;21-186">&#91;184&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="20_August_-_Sydney_lockdown_extended">20 August - Sydney lockdown extended</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: 20 August - Sydney lockdown extended">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>On 20 August NSW Health reported 4 deaths (from the previous day) and 644 new locally acquired COVID cases in the prior 24&#160;hours. Changes announced that day to lockdown and isolation rules included:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The lockdown of Greater Sydney was extended a month to the end of September.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>A curfew will be introduced in the 12 'LGAs of concern'. As of midnight on 23 August (Monday) people in the affected LGAs must remain home from 9pm to 5am.</li>
<li>In those LGAs only one hour of outdoor exercise allowed. The areas affected are:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>Bayside, Blacktown, Burwood, Campbelltown, Canterbury-Bankstown, Cumberland, Fairfield, Georges River, Liverpool, Parramatta, Penrith and Strathfield<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup></li>
