<li>NSW Police have new authority to enforce curfew restrictions<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup><br /> • They are able to "designate a person to self-isolate for two weeks"</li>
<li>As of midnight on 23 August, mask wearing will be mandatory outside the home everywhere in NSW<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup> <br /> • those exercising are an exception</li>
<li>The Central Coast and Shellharbour, previously considered a part of Greater Sydney for lockdown purposes re-classified as regional areas.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>On 20 August there was another 3 deaths of people with COVID-19:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21_190-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21-190">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/Hornsby_Ku-ring-gai_Hospital" title="Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital">Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 90s also at Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital <br />• Both were residents of Greenwood Aged Care in <a href="/wiki/Normanhurst,_New_South_Wales" title="Normanhurst, New South Wales">Normanhurst</a> and acquired their infections at that care facility.</li>
<li>a woman in her 90s at Liverpool Hospital, a geriatric ward patient there, the tenth death linked to the outbreak there</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 124 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 68 during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21_190-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21-190">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 21 August there was also 3 deaths reported in the 24 hours up to 8pm that day:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22aug&#39;21_191-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22aug&#39;21-191">&#91;189&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 60s at RPA, who was infected at Canterbury Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at <a href="/wiki/Wollongong_Hospital" title="Wollongong Hospital">Wollongong Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 70s at St George Hospital, where he acquired his infection and the second death linked to the outbreak there.</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 127 since the beginning of the pandemic in 2020, and 71 since the Delta outbreak started in June 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22aug&#39;21_191-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22aug&#39;21-191">&#91;189&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 21 August, to 8pm on 20 August, there were 825 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 11,395. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 16,984. Of the new cases, 58 were in the community, not isolated, while infectious, 92&#160;were isolated while infectious, 38&#160;were isolated for part of their infectious period. For 637 cases, their isolation status was under investigation. 7 new cases were overseas acquired. 253 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 61 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 290 Western Sydney LHD, 69 Sydney LHD, 18 Northern Sydney LHD, 65 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1 Hunter New England LHD, 38 Western NSW LHD, 14 Far West LHD, 1 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 1 Central Coast LHD, and 2 Southern NSW LHD. 12&#160;not assigned to any LHD. 149 cases were linked to a known case or cluster, the source for 676 were under investigation. There were 516 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 85 in intensive care, 29&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 124,610 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 11,596,985 tests. There were 50,212 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,071,896 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 3,670,315 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 5,742,211 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21_190-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21-190">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 21 August 2021 there was another anti-lockdown protest in Sydney city. The protest was countered by a pre-planned police response of over 1,500 officers and roadblocks on major roads into the central business district. About 250 protesters got into Sydney and over 45 people were arrested.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-protest-21aug&#39;21_192-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-protest-21aug&#39;21-192">&#91;190&#93;</a></sup> One of its main organisers, a 29-year-old Victorian man, was arrested before the protest on 19 August in <a href="/wiki/Hornsby,_New_South_Wales" title="Hornsby, New South Wales">Hornsby</a> for breaching public health orders by travelling to Sydney from Queensland. On 20 August he pled guilty to 4 counts of: not complying with a direction, and 1 count each of: encouraging the commission of a crime, and; making false representations resulting in a police investigation. He was sentenced to 8 months prison, 3 months non-parole.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-leader-jailed-21aug&#39;21_193-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-leader-jailed-21aug&#39;21-193">&#91;191&#93;</a></sup> Protests were also held that day in Adelaide, Brisbane, Darwin, Melbourne and Perth.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-6protests-21aug&#39;21_194-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-6protests-21aug&#39;21-194">&#91;192&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 22 August there was again 3 deaths reported in the 24 hours up to 8pm that day:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23aug&#39;21_195-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23aug&#39;21-195">&#91;193&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 80s at Campbelltown Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at Liverpool Hospital, where he was infected, the 11th death linked to an outbreak in that hospital's geriatric ward</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/John_Hunter_Hospital" title="John Hunter Hospital">John Hunter Hospital</a> (JHH), having been infected at the RFBI Hawkins Masonic Village, and the second death linked to an outbreak there</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 130 since the beginning of the pandemic in 2020, and 74 since the Delta outbreak started in June 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23aug&#39;21_195-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23aug&#39;21-195">&#91;193&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 23 August, as of midnight, some previously announced added restrictions came into force:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21_189-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-lckdn-+month-20aug&#39;21-189">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a curfew from 9pm to 5am in the 12 'LGAs of concern'</li>
<li>mask wearing became mandatory outside the home everywhere in NSW</li></ul>
<p>On 24 August there were 2 deaths of confirmed COVID cases:
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 30s in her home at <a href="/wiki/Emerton,_New_South_Wales" title="Emerton, New South Wales">Emerton</a> in Western Sydney. Her death is under investigation by the local health district, and was also referred to the <a href="/wiki/NSW_Coroner" class="mw-redirect" title="NSW Coroner">NSW Coroner</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-6mill-vaccns-24aug&#39;21_196-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-6mill-vaccns-24aug&#39;21-196">&#91;194&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>a man in his 80s at Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital<br />• a resident of Greenwood Aged Care in Normanhurst and was infected there, the third death linked to an outbreak there after 2&#160;deaths on 20 August.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25aug&#39;21_197-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25aug&#39;21-197">&#91;195&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21_190-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21aug&#39;21-190">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>Also on that day there were 919 new cases, a record daily high in Australia. As of 24 August, the total number of confirmed COVID cases in NSW reached 20,266 cases during the entire pandemic, 14,673 of them locally acquired in the 10 weeks since 16&#160;June 2021, when the first case of the Delta outbreak was reported in Bondi, Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25aug&#39;21_197-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25aug&#39;21-197">&#91;195&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 24 August 60% of the eligible state population had received their first vaccination.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-60%-1st-dose-5sept&#39;21_198-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-60%-1st-dose-5sept&#39;21-198">&#91;196&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 25 August there were 3 deaths reported of COVID cases who died on different days from 17 to 21 August. All were in western Sydney and died in their homes. At least 8 COVID cases have died in their homes since 16 June. None of these 3 were vaccinated, they were:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21_199-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21-199">&#91;197&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-3-unvacced-die-26aug&#39;21_200-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-3-unvacced-die-26aug&#39;21-200">&#91;198&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 30s, a man in his 60s, and a man in his 80s</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 135 since the beginning of the pandemic in 2020, and 79 since the Delta outbreak started in June 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21_199-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21-199">&#91;197&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the preceding 24 hours to 8pm that day, there were 1,029 new locally acquired cases, another new record daily high in NSW and Australia. As of 25 August, the total number of confirmed COVID cases in NSW reached 21,282 during the entire pandemic, 15,684 of them locally acquired in the 10 weeks since the first case of the Delta outbreak was reported in Bondi  in mid-June 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21_199-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26aug&#39;21-199">&#91;197&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="26_August_-_Regional_lockdown_extended">26 August - Regional lockdown extended</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: 26 August - Regional lockdown extended">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>On 26 August there were 2 deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21_201-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21-201">&#91;199&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 60s at Nepean Hospital, after acquiring his infection there, the third death linked to that hospitals' outbreak</li>
<li>a man in his 90s at Concord Hospital, having been infected at Canterbury Hospital, the fifth death linked to an outbreak there</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 137 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 81 during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21_201-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21-201">&#91;199&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 26 August, the lockdown in regional NSW was extended to 10 September at midnight as COVID has continued to spread in the Western NSW LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21_180-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21-180">&#91;178&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 August there were 2 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21_201-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27aug&#39;21-201">&#91;199&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 70s at Nepean Hospital, after acquiring her infection there, the fourth death linked to an outbreak at that hospital.</li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at Westmead Hospital.</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW reached 139 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 83 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21_202-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21-202">&#91;200&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>During the 24 hours to 8pm on 28 August, there were 6 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21_203-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21-203">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 80s at Nepean Hospital, after being infected there, the fifth death linked to that hospitals' outbreak</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at Concord Hospital, infected at the Wyoming Aged Care facility, the fifth death linked to their outbreak</li>
<li>2 men in their 70s at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s, and a woman in her 80s, at Westmead Hospital</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW reached 145 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 89 during the Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21_203-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21-203">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup> Nationally deaths were approximately 999.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 28 August there was another record high of 1,035 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 17,582. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 21,282. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 316 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 52 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 398 Western Sydney LHD, 100 Sydney LHD, 25&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 78 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 3 Hunter New England LHD, 42 Western NSW LHD, 4 Far West LHD, 7&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, and 2 Central Coast LHD. 8&#160;not assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21_202-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21-202">&#91;200&#93;</a></sup><br />There were 778 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 125 in intensive care, 52&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 129,182 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 12,800,559 tests. There were 61,778 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,417,750 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,153,879 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 6,571,629 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21_202-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28aug&#39;21-202">&#91;200&#93;</a></sup> There was a record total of 156,165 COVID-19 vaccinations administered this day.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-vaccns-record-28aug&#39;21_204-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-vaccns-record-28aug&#39;21-204">&#91;202&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 29 August, there were 4 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21_205-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21-205">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 50s at Dubbo Hospital ‡</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at Westmead Hospital</li>
<li>woman in her 60s at Westmead Hospital, she was infected at <a href="/wiki/Cumberland_Hospital" title="Cumberland Hospital">Cumberland Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 70s from at Concord Hospital, and was infected at Meredith House Aged Care facility</li></ul>
<dl><dd>‡ The man at Dubbo was the first death of an <a href="/wiki/Aboriginal_and_Torres_Strait_Islander" class="mw-redirect" title="Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander">Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander</a> from COVID-19. He was not vaccinated.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-west-outbrk-1st-indig-30aug&#39;21_206-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-west-outbrk-1st-indig-30aug&#39;21-206">&#91;204&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 149 since the beginning of the pandemic, and 93 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21_205-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21-205">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup> National deaths rose to 1,003.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 29 August, new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were again a new record high of 1,218, bringing the total reported since 16&#160;June to 18,792. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 24,396. 3 new cases were overseas acquired. 421 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 67 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 466 Western Sydney LHD, 96 Sydney LHD, 28&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 66 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 7 Hunter New England LHD, 25 Western NSW LHD, 2 Far West LHD, 13&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, and 2 Central Coast LHD. 25&#160;not assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21_203-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21-203">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup><br />There were 813 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 126 in intensive care, 54&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 106,038 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 12,906,597 tests. There were 49,849 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,467,599 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,236,118 total doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 6,703,717 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21_203-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29aug&#39;21-203">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>Also by 29 August, there were 31 cases of COVID at <a href="/wiki/Parklea_Correctional_Centre" title="Parklea Correctional Centre">Parklea Correctional Centre</a> in north-western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-news-com-parklea-29aug&#39;21_207-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news-com-parklea-29aug&#39;21-207">&#91;205&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 30 August, there were 3 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21_208-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21-208">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 50s, and a man in his 90s, at Campbelltown Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at St Vincent's Hospital.</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 152 since the beginning of the pandemic, 96 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21_208-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21-208">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup> National deaths rose to 1,006.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 30 August, new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 set another record high of 1,290, bringing the total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 20,061. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 25,668. 3 new cases were overseas acquired. 434 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 70 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 449 Western Sydney LHD, 126 Sydney LHD, 38&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 83 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 3 Hunter New England LHD, 51 Western NSW LHD, 9 Far West LHD, 5&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 6 Central Coast LHD and 3 Justice Health Forensic Mental Health Network. 13&#160;cases were not assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21_205-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21-205">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup><br />There were  840 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 137 in intensive care, 48&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 157, 221 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,063,818 tests. There were 49,103 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,516,702 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,277,772 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 6,794,474 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21_205-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30aug&#39;21-205">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 31 August, there were 4 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21_209-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21-209">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>2 women, one her 50s, one in her 70s, at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at RPA Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 60s at Concord Hospital</li></ul>
<p>The first 3 people were all from south western Sydney, the last from western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21_209-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21-209">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup><br />The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 156 since the beginning of the pandemic, 100 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21_209-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21-209">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup>National deaths rose to 1,012, as there were also 2 deaths in Victoria.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 31 August, new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 1,164, bringing the total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 21,208. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 26,820. 4 new cases were overseas acquired. 379 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 73 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 417 Western Sydney LHD, 116 Sydney LHD, 15&#160;Northern Sydney LHD, 45 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 2 Hunter New England LHD, 54 Western NSW LHD, 4 Far West LHD, 5&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 4 Central Coast LHD, and 1 Southern NSW LHD. 6&#160;cases were not assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21_208-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21-208">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup><br /> There were 871 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 143 in intensive care, 58&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 130,027 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,193,845 tests. There were 47,429 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,564,131 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,295,148 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 6,859,279 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21_208-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31aug&#39;21-208">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>Also on 31 August, there were numerous anti-lockdown protests across the state. At least 79 protests occurred, including outside the NSW Parliament building and Byron Shire Council Chambers in Mullumbimby. Protests also took place in Blacktown, Fairfield, Sutherland and Liverpool in Sydney, and Ballina, Cessnock, Dubbo, Grafton, Lake Macquarie, Lismore, Mudgee, Nowra, Orange, Port Macquarie, Shellharbour and Wagga Wagga in regional NSW. 24 of the protests were in the state's north alone. Police arrested over 150 people and issued more than 500 infringement notices in connection with the events.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-79protests-31aug&#39;21_210-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-79protests-31aug&#39;21-210">&#91;208&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-protests-newc-31aug&#39;21_211-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-protests-newc-31aug&#39;21-211">&#91;209&#93;</a></sup> Several police officers were injured.<sup id="cite_ref-smh-protest-injured-31ug&#39;21_212-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh-protest-injured-31ug&#39;21-212">&#91;210&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="September">September</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: September">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 1 September, there were 7 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21_213-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21-213">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 50s at <a href="/wiki/Royal_North_Shore_Hospital" title="Royal North Shore Hospital">Royal North Shore Hospital</a> (RNSH)</li>
<li>2 people, a woman in her 70s, and a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/Campbelltown_Hospital" title="Campbelltown Hospital">Campbelltown Hospital</a></li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at <a href="/wiki/Liverpool_Hospital" title="Liverpool Hospital">Liverpool Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/St_George_Hospital_(Sydney)" title="St George Hospital (Sydney)">St George Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 70s at Liverpool Hospital, he acquired his infection there, the 12th death linked to this hospitals' outbreak</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at <a href="/wiki/Hornsby_Ku-ring-gai_Hospital" title="Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital">Hornsby Ku-ring-gai Hospital</a> who acquired his infection at that hospital</li></ul>
<p>The first 6 people were all from south western Sydney, the last from northern Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21_213-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21-213">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup>
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 163 since the beginning of the pandemic, 107 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21_213-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21-213">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup> <br />National deaths rose to 1,019.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 1 September there were 1,116 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 22,308. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 27,922. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. 372 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 52 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 408 Western Sydney LHD, 132 Sydney LHD, 22 Northern Sydney LHD, 68 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 6 Hunter New England LHD, 29 Western NSW LHD, 3 Far West LHD, 8 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 2 Central Coast LHD and 4 are in a correctional centre. 10&#160;were not assigned to any LHD. There were 917&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 150 in intensive care, 66&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 173,913 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,367,758 tests. There were 50,212 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,611,205 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,366,249 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 6,977,454 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21_209-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1sept&#39;21-209">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 1 September the NSW government announced it would cut its international arrivals into the state from 1,500 to 750 until the end of October. This was to allow resources to be moved away from hotel quarantine during the state's continuing, and worsening, Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-int-pax-50%-1sept&#39;21_214-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-int-pax-50%-1sept&#39;21-214">&#91;212&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 2 September, there were 12 more deaths confirmed of COVID cases, a NSW record:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21_215-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21-215">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 30s at home, the source of her infection was being investigated (died on 1 September)</li>
<li>a woman in her 70s at <a href="/wiki/Westmead_Hospital" title="Westmead Hospital">Westmead Hospital</a>, where she became infected</li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at Westmead Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at <a href="/wiki/Concord_Repatriation_General_Hospital" title="Concord Repatriation General Hospital">Concord Hospital</a> (CRGH)</li>
<li>4 people: 3 women, 1 in her 60s, 2 in their 70s; and a man in his 80s, at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at St George Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at Hornsby Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 90s at the 'Hawkesbury Living' aged care facility</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at St George Hospital, a resident of St George Aged Care Centre in <a href="/wiki/Bexley,_New_South_Wales" title="Bexley, New South Wales">Bexley</a> from where he acquired his infection</li></ul>
<p>The first 9 people were all from south western Sydney, the next three were from Sydney's north, the Blue Mountains, and south eastern Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21_215-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21-215">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup>
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 175 since the beginning of the pandemic, 119&#160;during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21_215-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21-215">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup><br />National deaths rose to 1,032. (includes 1 death in Victoria)<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 2 September there were 1,288 new locally acquired cases of COVID-19, bringing the total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 23,586. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 29,202. 1 new case was overseas acquired. 387 of the new cases were from South Western Sydney LHD, 101 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 445 Western Sydney LHD, 149 Sydney LHD, 31 Northern Sydney LHD, 82 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 4 Hunter New England LHD, 23 Western NSW LHD, 5 Far West LHD, 22 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 7 Central Coast LHD and 11 were in a correctional centre. 21&#160;were not yet assigned to any LHD. There were 957&#160;cases in hospital, 160 in intensive care, 64&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 127,428 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,495,186 tests. There were 45,665 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,656,870 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,445,048 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 7,101,918 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21_213-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2sept&#39;21-213">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also by 2 September, 70% of the eligible NSW population had received their first dose of vaccine. NSW was the first Australian state to reach this milestone.<sup id="cite_ref-news.com-nsw-1st-vacc-70%-2sept&#39;21_216-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news.com-nsw-1st-vacc-70%-2sept&#39;21-216">&#91;214&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 3 September, there were 4 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 80s at <a href="/wiki/Fairfield_Hospital_(Sydney)" title="Fairfield Hospital (Sydney)">Fairfield Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 70s at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 50s at Westmead Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 60s at home</li></ul>
<p>The first 2 people were from south western Sydney, the last 2 from western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup> None of them were vaccinated.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21_218-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21-218">&#91;216&#93;</a></sup> 
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 179 since the beginning of the pandemic, 123 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup><br />
</p><p>By 3 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 at 1,431 were again a record high, and brought total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 25,002. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 30,618. 1 new case was overseas acquired. Of the new cases: 508 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 102 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 424 Western Sydney LHD, 152 Sydney LHD, 32 Northern Sydney LHD, 95 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 11 Hunter New England LHD, 53 Western NSW LHD, 7 Far West LHD, 13&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 8 Central Coast LHD, 1 Southern NSW LHD, and 13 were in "correctional settings". 12&#160;were not yet assigned to any LHD. There were 979&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 160 in intensive care, 63&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 154,654 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,649,840 tests. There were 44,248 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 7,223,164 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,522,046 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 7,223,164 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21_215-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3sept&#39;21-215">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also by 3 September, the small country town of <a href="/wiki/Wilcannia" title="Wilcannia">Wilcannia</a> had 9 new cases, bringing the total to 97, around 13% of the population, which is largely indigenous. The NSW Health Minister, Brad Hazzard, said it was the second busiest day for the ambulance service in the state's history.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21_218-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21-218">&#91;216&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 4 September, there were 3 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21_219-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21-219">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 70s at Campbelltown Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 50s at <a href="/wiki/Blacktown_Hospital" title="Blacktown Hospital">Blacktown Hospital</a></li></ul>
<p>The first 2 people were from south western Sydney, the last from western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21_219-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21-219">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup> 
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 182 since the beginning of the pandemic, 126 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21_219-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21-219">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup> <br />National deaths rose to 1,039.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 4 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 1,533, yet again a record high, and brought total new cases reported since 16&#160;June to 26,517. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 32,134. 1 new case was overseas acquired. <br />• Of the new cases: 494 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 122 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 512 Western Sydney LHD, 150&#160;Sydney LHD, 36 Northern Sydney LHD, 90 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 15 Hunter New England LHD, 38 Western NSW LHD, 9&#160;Far West LHD, 17&#160;Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 15 Central Coast LHD, and 13 were in "correctional settings". 22&#160;were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,041&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 173 in intensive care (ICU), 62&#160;requiring ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup> Of the ICU cases, 137 were unvaccinated, 7 fully vaccinated, 29 had one dose of vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21_218-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-4unvaccd-4sept&#39;21-218">&#91;216&#93;</a></sup> COVID-19 tests were 131,174 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,781,014 tests. <br />• There were 49,779 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,750,897 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,601,473 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 7,352,370 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21_217-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4sept&#39;21-217">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 5 September, there were 5 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21_220-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21-220">&#91;218&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>2 women, 1 in her 50s, 1 in her 80s at Westmead Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 80s at <a href="/w/index.php?title=Ryde_Hospital&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Ryde Hospital (page does not exist)">Ryde Hospital</a></li>
<li>a man in his 60s at home</li>
<li>a man in his 90s at St George Hospital, a resident of St George Aged Care Centre in Bexley where he was infected</li></ul>
<p>The first 2 people were from south western Sydney, next northern Sydney, the <a href="/wiki/Southern_Highlands_(New_South_Wales)" title="Southern Highlands (New South Wales)">Southern Highlands</a> and south east Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21_220-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21-220">&#91;218&#93;</a></sup>
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 187 since the beginning of the pandemic, 131 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21_220-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6sept&#39;21-220">&#91;218&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 5 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were at 1,485, and brought total new cases reported since 16&#160;June, during the Delta outbreak, to 27,984. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 33,603. 2 new cases were overseas acquired. <br />• Of the new cases: 518 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 116 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 479 Western Sydney LHD, 174 Sydney LHD, 31 Northern Sydney LHD, 80 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 12 Hunter New England LHD, 32 Western NSW LHD, 4 Far West LHD, 11 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 7 Central Coast LHD, and 15 were in "correctional settings". 15&#160;were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21_219-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21-219">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,030&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 175 in intensive care, 72&#160;requiring ventilation. COVID-19 tests were 115,495 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 13,896,509 tests. <br />• There were 46,502 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,797,399 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 4,676,147 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 7,473,546 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21_219-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5sept&#39;21-219">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also by 5 September, 40% of the NSW population was fully vaccinated.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-40%-full-vaccd-5sept&#39;21_221-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-40%-full-vaccd-5sept&#39;21-221">&#91;219&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 6 September, there were 8 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7sept&#39;21_222-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7sept&#39;21-222">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>2 people, a man in his 50s, and a woman in her 70s, at Nepean Hospital</li>

</p><p>On 9 September, the NSW state government announced that when full vaccination levels reached 70%, those who are fully vaccinated would have greater freedoms than others. This 70% level was predicted to happen in mid-October.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-vacrights-9sept&#39;21_228-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-vacrights-9sept&#39;21-228">&#91;226&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 9 September, the state government announced that NSW would be unable to host the <a href="/wiki/2021_NRL_Grand_Final" title="2021 NRL Grand Final">2021 NRL Grand Final</a>, originally set for 3&#160;October at <a href="/wiki/Stadium_Australia" title="Stadium Australia">Stadium Australia</a> due to "the current Covid-19 situation in Greater Sydney and across the state". The event will instead be held in Brisbane, Queensland at <a href="/wiki/Suncorp_Stadium" class="mw-redirect" title="Suncorp Stadium">Suncorp Stadium</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-news.com-nrl&#39;21final-9sept&#39;21_229-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news.com-nrl&#39;21final-9sept&#39;21-229">&#91;227&#93;</a></sup>

<h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Regional_lockdown_partially_lifted">Regional lockdown partially lifted</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Regional lockdown partially lifted">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>On 11 September at 12:01am, many areas of regional NSW came out of lockdown (<a href="/wiki/Stay-at-home_orders" class="mw-redirect" title="Stay-at-home orders">stay-at-home orders</a> lifted) as planned, after the last extension. Those areas were ones which had no cases of COVID for 14 days, and were also deemed low-risk. Even 'out' of lockdown many restrictions will remain in effect.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-lckdwn-lift-9sept&#39;21_231-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-lckdwn-lift-9sept&#39;21-231">&#91;229&#93;</a></sup> The lockdown started on 14 August,<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21_94-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-regional-lockdown-14aug&#39;21-94">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup> and was extended several times.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21_180-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-rgnl-lckdwn-+14days-26aug&#39;21-180">&#91;178&#93;</a></sup> <br />Within a week Yass, Albury, Lismore, Hilltops and Glen Innes LGAs all had stay-at-home orders re-introduced,<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-yass-lckdwn-13sept&#39;21_232-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-yass-lckdwn-13sept&#39;21-232">&#91;230&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-alby-lsmr-lckdwn-16sept&#39;21_233-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-alby-lsmr-lckdwn-16sept&#39;21-233">&#91;231&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-hill-glenin-lckdwn-17sept&#39;21_234-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-hill-glenin-lckdwn-17sept&#39;21-234">&#91;232&#93;</a></sup> and by 21&#160;September the Cowra, Kempsey, Byron and Tweed Shires' LGAs were also again under stay-at-home orders.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-20sept&#39;21_235-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-20sept&#39;21-235">&#91;233&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-kemp-byr-twd-lckdwn-21sept&#39;21_236-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-kemp-byr-twd-lckdwn-21sept&#39;21-236">&#91;234&#93;</a></sup> <br />On 28 September the Port Macquarie and Muswellbrook Shire LGAs were both placed back into lockdown.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-prtmacq-muswl-lckdwn-28sept&#39;21_237-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-prtmacq-muswl-lckdwn-28sept&#39;21-237">&#91;235&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 11 September, there were 7 more deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21_238-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21-238">&#91;236&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a man in his 20s at Nepean Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 50s at Westmead Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 40s at Campbelltown Hospital</li>
<li>a woman in her 50s at St George Hospital</li>
<li>3 people: a man in his 70s, a man in his 80s, and a woman in her 80s, all at Liverpool Hospital</li></ul>
<p>The first 2 people were from western Sydney, the last 5 all from south western Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21_238-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21-238">&#91;236&#93;</a></sup>
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 233 since the beginning of the pandemic, 177 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21_238-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12sept&#39;21-238">&#91;236&#93;</a></sup> <br />National deaths rose to 1,091.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 11 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 rose to 1,599, a NSW and Australian record high, and brought total new cases reported, during the state's Delta outbreak (since 16 June) to 36,374.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21_230-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21-230">&#91;228&#93;</a></sup> The record of 1,599 stood until 4 October when Victoria had 1,763 new cases.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-vic-1763-nucase-recrd-5oct&#39;21_239-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-vic-1763-nucase-recrd-5oct&#39;21-239">&#91;237&#93;</a></sup> <br />• The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 42,000. 4 new cases were acquired overseas. <br />• Of the new cases: 490 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 177 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 444 Western Sydney LHD, 192&#160;Sydney LHD, 57 Northern Sydney LHD, 94 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 10 Hunter New England LHD, 16 Western LHD, 13 Far West LHD, 37 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 27 Central Coast LHD, 2 Southern LHD, and 7 were in "correctional settings". 33&#160;were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21_230-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21-230">&#91;228&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,164&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 221 in intensive care, 94&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were 147,975 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 14,701,732 tests. <br />• There were 32,150 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 2,981,034 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 5,035,771 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 8,016,805 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21_230-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11sept&#39;21-230">&#91;228&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 24 hours up to 8pm on 12 September, there were another 7 deaths of confirmed COVID cases:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21_240-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21-240">&#91;238&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>a woman in her 60s at Campbelltown Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at Sutherland Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 90s at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at St Vincent’s Hospital</li>

<p>The first 3 people were from south western Sydney, then inner-, inner west-, and north west Sydney, lastly Dubbo.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21_240-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21-240">&#91;238&#93;</a></sup>
The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 240 since the beginning of the pandemic, 184 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21_240-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13sept&#39;21-240">&#91;238&#93;</a></sup> <br />National deaths rose to 1,098.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> 
</p><p>By 12 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 1,262, which brought total new cases reported, during the state's Delta outbreak (since 16 June) to 37,621. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 43,247. No new cases were acquired overseas. <br />• Of the new cases: 399 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 161 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 336 Western Sydney LHD, 135&#160;Sydney LHD, 25 Northern Sydney LHD, 80 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 7 Hunter New England LHD, 14 Western LHD, 5 Far West LHD, 53 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 33 Central Coast LHD. <dl><dt>Yass lockdown</dt></dl>
<p>On 14 September, <a href="/wiki/Yass_Valley_Council" title="Yass Valley Council">Yass Valley Council</a> LGA was placed back into lockdown, 3 days after the regional lockdown lifted there, with stay-at-home orders effective from 12:01am. This followed a local case of COVID-19, and also virus detection in sewage. This lockdown is due to last for 2 weeks and applied to all residents, and anyone who visited the LGA on, or after, 9 September.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-yass-lckdwn-13sept&#39;21_232-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-yass-lckdwn-13sept&#39;21-232">&#91;230&#93;</a></sup>

<dl><dt>Albury – Lismore lockdown</dt></dl>
<p>On 16 September, the LGAs of <a href="/wiki/City_of_Albury" title="City of Albury">City of Albury</a> which borders Victoria, and <a href="/wiki/City_of_Lismore" title="City of Lismore">City of Lismore</a> in NSWs north-east, were both placed back into lockdown with stay-at-home orders effective from 6pm. This occurred less than 6 days after the regional NSW lockdown covering both areas was lifted on 11 September. It applied to all residents, and anyone who visited Albury since 10 September, and Lismore since 7 September. This step was due to what the <a href="/wiki/NSW_Health" class="mw-redirect" title="NSW Health">NSW Health</a> department called "an increased COVID-19 public health risk.".<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-alby-lsmr-lckdwn-16sept&#39;21_233-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-alby-lsmr-lckdwn-16sept&#39;21-233">&#91;231&#93;</a></sup> The lockdown was due to last for 7 days, but the stay-at-home requirement was lifted early, after midnight on 22&#160;September.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-lckdwn-alby-lsmre-lifted-22sept&#39;21_245-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-lckdwn-alby-lsmre-lifted-22sept&#39;21-245">&#91;243&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 16 September, from 1pm stay-at-home orders were lifted in the <a href="/wiki/Local_Government_Areas" class="mw-redirect" title="Local Government Areas">Local Government Areas</a> (LGAs) of: Bega, Blayney, Bogan, Cabonne, Dungog, Forbes, Muswellbrook, Narrabri, Parkes, Singleton, Snowy Monaro and Upper Hunter.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-gov-stay-home-lift-16sept&#39;21_246-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-gov-stay-home-lift-16sept&#39;21-246">&#91;244&#93;</a></sup>

<dl><dt>Hilltops and Glen Innes lockdowns</dt></dl>
<p>On 17 September the <a href="/wiki/Hilltops_Council" title="Hilltops Council">Hilltops Council</a> and <a href="/wiki/Glen_Innes_Severn" title="Glen Innes Severn">Glen Innes Severn</a> LGAs were both placed back into lockdown with stay-at-home orders effective from 6pm. The lockdown was due to last for 7 days due to "an increased COVID-19 public health risk." The stay-at-home orders applied to residents, or visitors to Hilltops, including <a href="/wiki/Young,_New_South_Wales" title="Young, New South Wales">Young</a> and adjoining areas since 3 September, and Glen Innes, since 13 September.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-hill-glenin-lckdwn-17sept&#39;21_234-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-hill-glenin-lckdwn-17sept&#39;21-234">&#91;232&#93;</a></sup> The Hilltops lockdown was extended by 7 days on 23 September.<sup id="cite_ref-yng-wtns-hltp-lkdwn+7-23sept&#39;21_250-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-yng-wtns-hltp-lkdwn+7-23sept&#39;21-250">&#91;248&#93;</a></sup>

(September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> 
</p><p>By 18 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 1,331, which brought total new cases reported since 16 June, during the state's Delta outbreak, to 45,085. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 50,730. 2 new cases were acquired overseas.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21_249-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21-249">&#91;247&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 400 were from South Western Sydney LHD, 164 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 326 Western Sydney LHD, 160&#160;Sydney LHD, 40 Northern Sydney LHD, 47 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 30 Hunter New England LHD, 17 Western LHD, 6&#160;Far West LHD, 75 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 29 Central Coast LHD, 8 Southern NSW LHD and 4 from Murrumbidgee LHD. 8 were in "correctional settings". 17 were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21_249-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21-249">&#91;247&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,219&#160;COVID-19 cases in hospital, 233 in intensive care, 123&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were 120,954 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 15,693,965 tests. <br />• There were 32,994 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 3,183,957 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 5,536,771 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 8,720,728 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21_249-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18sept&#39;21-249">&#91;247&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 19 September there were 4 deaths of confirmed COVID cases in the 24 hours up to 8pm. They were:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20sept&#39;21_253-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20sept&#39;21-253">&#91;251&#93;</a></sup>

<dl><dt>Cowra lockdown</dt></dl>
<p>On 20 September, from 5pm the <a href="/wiki/Cowra_Shire" title="Cowra Shire">Cowra Shire</a> LGA was placed back into lockdown with stay-at-home orders in place. The lockdown was due to last for 7 days and followed "an increased COVID-19 public health risk." The stay-at-home order applied to residents, or visitors to Cowra, since 13 September.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-20sept&#39;21_235-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-20sept&#39;21-235">&#91;233&#93;</a></sup> On 27 September the lockdown was extended by 7 days.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-extend-27sept&#39;21_254-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-cowra-lckdwn-extend-27sept&#39;21-254">&#91;252&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 20 September there were 10 deaths of confirmed COVID cases in the 24 hours up to 8pm.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21_255-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21-255">&#91;253&#93;</a></sup> Of the ten, 6 were not vaccinated, 2 partly vaccinated. The last 2, a woman in her 90s and a man in his 80s were fully vaccinated, but both had serious underlying health conditions. The deaths included:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21_255-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21-255">&#91;253&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>

<li>a man in his 80s at Hornsby Hospital, where he acquired his infection</li>
<li>a man in his 80s at Concord Hospital, he was infected at <a href="/wiki/Canterbury_Hospital" title="Canterbury Hospital">Canterbury Hospital</a></li>
<li>a woman in her 90s at Westmead Hospital <br /> – the third death linked to an outbreak at Hardi Guildford Aged Care</li></ul>
<p>6 were from south western Sydney, 1 western Sydney, 1 south eastern Sydney, 1 northern Sydney and 1 north west Sydney. The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 311 since the beginning of the pandemic, 255 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21_255-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21sept&#39;21-255">&#91;253&#93;</a></sup><br />National deaths rose to 1,178.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. <dl><dt>Friends bubble</dt></dl>
<p>From mid-day on 21 September, those aged 18 and less living in areas of concern, and areas under stay-at-home rules, can create a 3-person 'friends bubble' to visit each other for play activities. Rules to the bubble are:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-hzrd-frnd-bubl-21sept&#39;21_258-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-hzrd-frnd-bubl-21sept&#39;21-258">&#91;256&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>child can have 2 designated friends come to their home
<ul><li>These 2 friends must always be the same 2 friends, creating a 3-person 'friends bubble'</li></ul></li>
<li>all adults (over 18 years) in all the households to be fully vaccinated</li>
<li>friends must live within 5km of each other, or in the same LGA</li>
<li>parents/carers dropping children off, may not interact with other parents/carers<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-hzrd-frnd-bubl-21sept&#39;21_258-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-hzrd-frnd-bubl-21sept&#39;21-258">&#91;256&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<dl><dt>Kempsey - Byron - Tweed lockdowns</dt></dl>
<p>Also on 21 September, from 5pm the <a href="/wiki/Kempsey_Shire" title="Kempsey Shire">Kempsey Shire</a>, <a href="/wiki/Byron_Shire" title="Byron Shire">Byron Shire</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tweed_Shire" title="Tweed Shire">Tweed Shire</a> LGAs in the state's north were placed back into lockdown with stay-at-home orders re-implemented. The lockdown was due to last for 7 days and followed "an increased COVID-19 public health risk." The stay-at-home orders applied to residents, or visitors to:<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-kemp-byr-twd-lckdwn-21sept&#39;21_236-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-kemp-byr-twd-lckdwn-21sept&#39;21-236">&#91;234&#93;</a></sup>

<li>a man in his 70s, a resident of Uniting <a href="/wiki/Springwood,_New_South_Wales" title="Springwood, New South Wales">Springwood</a> Residential Aged Care <br /> – he was not vaccinated</li>
<li>5 were from south western-, 2 south eastern-, 1 western-, 2 -Sydney, 1 the Blue Mountains</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 344 since the beginning of the pandemic, 288 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25sept&#39;21_262-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25sept&#39;21-262">&#91;260&#93;</a></sup><br />National deaths, including 1 death in Victoria, rose to 1,220.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 56,799. <h5><span class="mw-headline" id="Record_daily_deaths">Record daily deaths</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Record daily deaths">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h5>
<p>On 28 September there were 15 deaths of confirmed COVID cases to 8pm, the state's highest COVID-19 death toll in a 24-hour period.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> 9 were not vaccinated, 5&#160;were partially vaccinated, 1 had received 2 doses of COVID-19 vaccine. The deaths included:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>
<ul><li>8 men and 7 women</li>
<li>2 people in their 40s, 2 their 50s, 4 their 60s, 3 their 70s, 1 their 80s, 3 in their 90s</li>
<li>a man in his 40s at Nepean Hospital <br /> – not vaccinated <br /> – underlying health conditions</li>
<li>2 people, a man in his 60s, a woman in her 90s <br /> – both were infected at Liverpool Hospital</li>
<li>2 people at home:
<ul><li>a man in his 40s, receiving community care from Hunter New England Local Health District <br /> – not vaccinated <br /> – underlying health conditions</li>
<li>a woman in her 70s <br /> – had two doses of COVID-19 vaccine, the second shortly before she died <br /> – underlying health conditions <br /> – diagnosed with COVID-19 after death</li></ul></li>
<li>11 were from Sydney: 5 south western, 3 western, 1 inner west, 1 south eastern, and 1 eastern suburban Sydney
<ul><li>4 were from: <a href="/wiki/Bateman%27s_Bay" class="mw-redirect" title="Bateman&#39;s Bay">Bateman's Bay</a>, Dubbo, <a href="/wiki/Lake_Macquarie" class="mw-redirect" title="Lake Macquarie">Lake Macquarie</a> and <a href="/wiki/Newcastle,_New_South_Wales" title="Newcastle, New South Wales">Newcastle</a></li></ul></li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 387 since the beginning of the pandemic, 331 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><br />National deaths rose to 1,278,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> including 7 deaths in other states.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<dl><dt>Port Macquarie and Muswellbrook lockdowns</dt></dl>
<p>Also on 28 September, the <a href="/wiki/Port_Macquarie-Hastings" class="mw-redirect" title="Port Macquarie-Hastings">Port Macquarie-Hastings</a> and <a href="/wiki/Muswellbrook_Shire" title="Muswellbrook Shire">Muswellbrook Shire</a> LGAs were both placed back into lockdown with stay-at-home orders effective from 6pm. The lockdown is due to last for 7 days due to "an increased COVID-19 public health risk." The stay-at-home orders apply to residents, or visitors to Port Macquarie since 17 September, and Muswellbrook since 22 September. That same day the Byron, Kempsey and Tweed Shire LGAs came out of lockdown at midnight as scheduled.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-prtmacq-muswl-lckdwn-28sept&#39;21_237-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-prtmacq-muswl-lckdwn-28sept&#39;21-237">&#91;235&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-byron-etc-lckdwn-end-28sept&#39;21_267-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-byron-etc-lckdwn-end-28sept&#39;21-267">&#91;265&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 28 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 863, up by 76 cases on the previous 24 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21_265-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21-265">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup> Total new cases reported during the state's Delta outbreak rose to 54,714. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 60,372. 2&#160;new cases were acquired overseas, and 1 from interstate.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21_265-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21-265">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 241 (+2) were from South Western Sydney LHD, 98 (+25) South Eastern Sydney LHD, 161 (+3) Western Sydney LHD, 80 (+6)&#160;Sydney LHD, 31(+15) Northern Sydney LHD, 53 (+19) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 63 (+17) Hunter New England LHD, 21&#160;Western LHD, 5&#160;Far West LHD, 62 Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 29 Central Coast LHD,  and 14 (+5) Southern LHD. 3 were in "correctional settings". 2 were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21_265-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21-265">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,155  COVID-19 cases in hospital, 213 in intensive care, 113&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were 132,279 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 16,885,159 tests. <br />• There were 25,942 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 3,491,835 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 6,250,994 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 9,742,829 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21_265-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21-265">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 29 September there were 6 deaths of confirmed COVID cases to 8pm, down from the previous days' record high of 15 deaths. 4&#160;were not vaccinated, 2&#160;were partially vaccinated. The deaths included:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30sept&#39;21_268-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30sept&#39;21-268">&#91;266&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>
<ul><li>4 men and 2 women</li>
<li>2 people in their 70s, 2 their 80s, 1 in their 90s</li>
<li>2 were from south western-, 1 western-, 1 inner west-, 1 south eastern-, and 1 north western-Sydney</li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 393 since the beginning of the pandemic, 337 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30sept&#39;21_268-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30sept&#39;21-268">&#91;266&#93;</a></sup><br />National deaths rose to at least 1,289,<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (September 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> including deaths in other states.

<dl><dt>Oberon lockdown</dt></dl>
<p>Also on 29 September, <a href="/wiki/Oberon_Council" title="Oberon Council">Oberon Council</a> LGA went into lockdown at 6pm for 7 days. The stay-at-home orders apply to residents, or visitors to Oberon, since 20 September.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-oberon-lckdwn-29sept&#39;21_269-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-oberon-lckdwn-29sept&#39;21-269">&#91;267&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 29 September new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 863, the same as in the previous 24 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Total new cases reported during the state's Delta outbreak rose to 55,570. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 61,231. 3&#160;new cases were acquired overseas, none from interstate.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 241 (+14) were from South Western Sydney LHD, 80 (-18) South Eastern Sydney LHD, 187 (+16) Western Sydney LHD, 80 (-12)&#160;Sydney LHD, 38 (+7) Northern Sydney LHD, 34 (-19) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 55 (-8) Hunter New England LHD, 24&#160;Western LHD, 5&#160;Far West LHD, 94 (+32) Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 23 (-6) Central Coast LHD, 18 (+4) Southern LHD and 2&#160;Northern NSW LHD. 3 were in "correctional settings". 5 were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 1,082 COVID-19 cases in hospital, 212 in intensive care, 108&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were 120,281 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 17,005,440 tests. <br />• There were 26,002 COVID-19 vaccinations administered, for 3,517,837 doses total, by NSW Health, plus another 6,349,648 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 9,867,485 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21_8-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29sept&#39;21-8">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 September there were another 15 deaths of confirmed COVID cases to 8pm,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1oct&#39;21_270-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1oct&#39;21-270">&#91;268&#93;</a></sup> matching the states highest 24 hour COVID-19 death toll 2 days earlier on 28 September.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21_265-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28sept&#39;21-265">&#91;263&#93;</a></sup> 9 were not vaccinated, 1&#160;was partially vaccinated, 5 had received 2 doses of COVID-19 vaccine. </p>
