</p><p>By 30 October new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 236, down  by  32  on the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21_304-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21-304">&#91;302&#93;</a></sup> Total new cases reported during the state's Delta outbreak were 69,232. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 74,923. 1 new case  was  acquired overseas. 0 from interstate.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21_304-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21-304">&#91;302&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 24 (-27) were from South Western Sydney LHD, 17 (+6)  South East Sydney LHD,  15 (-6) Western Sydney LHD,  23&#160;(-6) Sydney LHD, 1 (-2) Northern Sydney LHD, 5 (-7) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD,  73 (+19) Hunter New England LHD, 5&#160;(+4)&#160;Western NSW LHD, 0 (-3) Far West LHD, 8  (-)  Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 7 (+3)  Central Coast LHD, 13 (-)  Mid North Coast LHD,  1 (-6) Southern NSW LHD, 1 (-)  Northern NSW LHD, and 33 (-19)  Murrumbidgee LHD. 2 were  in a "correctional setting".  8  were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21_304-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21-304">&#91;302&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 343 (-20)  COVID-19 cases in hospital, 81 (-1)  in intensive care,  33 (+1)&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were  77,271 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 19,647,474 tests. <br />• There had been 4,038,573  total vaccine doses administered by NSW Health, plus another 8,218,032 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 12,256,605 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21_304-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30oct&#39;21-304">&#91;302&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 31 October deaths of confirmed COVID cases were at 4,  up  by 3 on the previous 24 hours to 8pm.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup>  2 were not vaccinated, 2 had 2 doses of COVID-19 vaccine. All had underlying health conditions. The deaths were:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup> 
</p>
<ul><li>2 men, 2 women</li>
<li>2 in their 60s, 1 their 70s, 1 over 100 years of age</li>
<li>a man in his 60s at Concord Hospital <br />– infected at <a href="/wiki/Parklea_Correctional_Centre" title="Parklea Correctional Centre">Parklea Correctional Centre</a></li>
<li>a woman in her 60s at Prince of Wales Hospital</li>
<li>a man in his 70s, a woman aged 101<br />– both infected at Mercy Place aged care, Albury <br />–  the 4th and 5th deaths linked to an outbreak there</li>
<li>2 from Sydney: 1 south western, 1 south eastern
<ul><li>2 from Albury</li></ul></li></ul>
<p>The total number of COVID related deaths in NSW was now 574 since the beginning of the pandemic, 518 during the NSW Delta outbreak.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup> <br />National deaths rose to 1,743, including interstate deaths.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2021)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>By 31 October new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 177, down  by  59  on the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21_305-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21-305">&#91;303&#93;</a></sup> Total new cases reported during the state's Delta outbreak were 69,397. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 75,089. 1 new case  was  acquired overseas. 0 from interstate.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21_305-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21-305">&#91;303&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 25 (+1) were from South Western Sydney LHD, 14 (-3)  South East Sydney LHD, 18 (+2) Western Sydney LHD,  17&#160;(-6) Sydney LHD, 7 (+6) Northern Sydney LHD, 3 (-2) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD,  33 (-40) Hunter New England LHD, 18&#160;(+13)&#160;Western NSW LHD, 1 (+1) Far West LHD, 9 (+1)  Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD, 6 (-1)  Central Coast LHD, 13 (-)  Mid North Coast LHD, 4 (+3) Southern NSW LHD, 7 (+6)  Northern NSW LHD, and 22 (-11)  Murrumbidgee LHD. None were  in a "correctional setting".  3  were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21_305-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21-305">&#91;303&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 340  (-3)  COVID-19 cases in hospital, 78 (-3)  in intensive care,  32 (-1)&#160;requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were  75,378 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 19,722,852 tests. <br />• There had been 4,045,698  total vaccine doses administered by NSW Health, plus another 8,258,696 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 12,304,394 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21_305-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-31oct&#39;21-305">&#91;303&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="November">November</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: November">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 1 November the state government announced $130 million of funding, including for psychology and psychiatry services, to assist those who had been adversely affected mentally by the COVID-19 pandemic.<sup id="cite_ref-nsw-health-mental-funds-1nov&#39;21_307-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw-health-mental-funds-1nov&#39;21-307">&#91;305&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By  1 November new locally acquired cases of COVID-19 were 135, down  by  42  on the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup> Total new cases reported during the state's Delta outbreak were 69,526. The total number of confirmed cases in NSW reached 75,218. No new case was acquired overseas. 1 from interstate.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup> <br />• Of the new cases: 23 (-2) were from South Western Sydney LHD, 2 (-12)  South East Sydney LHD, 9 (-9) Western Sydney LHD, 11&#160;(-6) Sydney LHD, 2 (-5) Northern Sydney LHD, 3  (-) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD,  30 (-3) Hunter New England LHD, 2&#160;(-16)&#160;Western NSW LHD, 1 (-)  Far West LHD, 3 (-6)  Illawarra-Shoalhaven LHD,  1 (-5). Central  Coast  LHD,  14 (+1)  Mid North Coast LHD,  5 (+1) Southern NSW LHD,  0 (-7)  Northern NSW LHD, and 26 (+4)  Murrumbidgee LHD.  3  were  in a "correctional setting". 0 were not yet assigned to any LHD.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup> <br />• There were 349 (+9)  COVID-19 cases in hospital, 77 (-1)  in intensive care,  33&#160;(+1) requiring ventilation. <br />• COVID-19 tests were  62,857 to 8pm for that day bringing the state total to 19,785,709 tests. <br />• There had been  4,050,714  total vaccine doses administered by NSW Health, plus another 8,278,417 doses administered by the GP network and other providers, for a state total to this date of 12,329,131 vaccinations.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21_306-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1nov&#39;21-306">&#91;304&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 28 November, two cases of the <a href="/wiki/SARS-CoV-2_Omicron_variant" title="SARS-CoV-2 Omicron variant">Omicron variant</a> were detected in Sydney. Both people landed in Sydney the previous day, and have travelled from southern Africa to Sydney via Doha, Qatar. The two people, who are fully vaccinated, entered isolation; 12 other travellers from southern Africa also entered quarantine for fourteen days, while about 260 other passengers and crew on the flight have been directed to isolate.<sup id="cite_ref-308" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-308">&#91;306&#93;</a></sup> On 29 November, two more passengers which arrived from southern Africa via Singapore tested positive for the Omicron variant.<sup id="cite_ref-309" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-309">&#91;307&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 November, a positive case of the Omicron variant was recorded in Sydney. The person had visited southern Africa before arriving in Sydney prior to travel restrictions, and was subsequently active in the community in Sydney and the <a href="/wiki/Central_Coast_(New_South_Wales)" title="Central Coast (New South Wales)">Central Coast</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NSW30Nov_310-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NSW30Nov-310">&#91;308&#93;</a></sup> By 3 December, a cluster including Omicron variant cases had developed in western Sydney, in the suburbs of <a href="/wiki/Regents_Park,_New_South_Wales" title="Regents Park, New South Wales">Regents Park</a> and <a href="/wiki/Villawood,_New_South_Wales" title="Villawood, New South Wales">Villawood</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-311" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-311">&#91;309&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="December">December</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: December">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 5 December, new daily case numbers dropped to a low of 208.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5dec&#39;21_312-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5dec&#39;21-312">&#91;310&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 16 December, due to the spread of COVID-19 Omicron variant in the area, NSW Health urged the Newcastle community to consider deferring social events till after Christmas.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16dec&#39;21_313-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16dec&#39;21-313">&#91;311&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On the afternoon of 16 December the Lunar Electric Music Festival in Newcastle, scheduled for December 18, was cancelled by a Public Health Order. This was done because the ongoing spread of the Omicron variant of COVID-19 in that area was too high a risk.<sup id="cite_ref-nswhealth-lunar-electric-cancel-16&#39;dec&#39;21_314-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nswhealth-lunar-electric-cancel-16&#39;dec&#39;21-314">&#91;312&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>After falling as low as 208 then gradually rising, on 13 December new daily case numbers began to rise quickly again. By 18&#160;December they had risen sharply for six consecutive days reaching what was then a new NSW state, and national, record of 2,566 new daily cases,<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18dec&#39;21_315-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18dec&#39;21-315">&#91;313&#93;</a></sup> before dropping slightly again to 2,501 on 19 December.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19dec&#39;21_316-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19dec&#39;21-316">&#91;314&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 22 December, great difficulties in finding <a href="/wiki/Rapid_antigen_test" title="Rapid antigen test">rapid antigen tests</a> (RAT) for COVID-19 became apparent.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-rats-short-22dec&#39;21_317-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-rats-short-22dec&#39;21-317">&#91;315&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 23 December, NSW single-dose vaccinations reached 95%, and 93.5% double dose, for the 16-years and older community<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21_21-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21-21">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> and the NSW government announced that on 27&#160;December until 27 January 2022, QR code check-ins would again be compulsory, including in hospitality and retail settings. Also, hospitality venues such as cafes, clubs, pubs and restaurants would return to a 1-person per 2 square metre rule indoors, but no density limit in outdoor settings.<sup id="cite_ref-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21_318-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21-318">&#91;316&#93;</a></sup> 
</p><p>The same day, the state government also announced that they would source rapid antigen test (RAT) kits and distribute them for free.<sup id="cite_ref-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21_318-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21-318">&#91;316&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 24 December, the states' new daily cases of COVID-19 rose to 6,288.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21_21-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24dec&#39;21-21">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-95%-vaccn-25&#39;dec&#39;21_319-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-95%-vaccn-25&#39;dec&#39;21-319">&#91;317&#93;</a></sup>
Also on 24 December, mask wearing indoors again became mandatory.<sup id="cite_ref-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21_318-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-heath-nsw-rules-changes-23dec&#39;21-318">&#91;316&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 25 December, there were no deaths recorded, and new daily cases of COVID-19 rose to 6,394. Cases admitted to hospital rose to 458, 52 in intensive care, 15 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25dec&#39;21_320-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25dec&#39;21-320">&#91;318&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 26 December NSW had 3 deaths, including its first death related to the Omicron variant, raising to 654 the states' total official COVID deaths. All 3 people were in their 80s or 90s, had 2&#160;doses of vaccine, and underlying health conditions. The Omicron death was a man from western Sydney, at Westmead Hospital. He was infected at Uniting Lilian Wells aged care in North Parramatta where he lived.<sup id="cite_ref-7news-1st-omicron-death-27dec&#39;21_321-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7news-1st-omicron-death-27dec&#39;21-321">&#91;319&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26dec&#39;21_322-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26dec&#39;21-322">&#91;320&#93;</a></sup> New case numbers were down slightly at 6,324. Cases admitted to hospital were 520, with 55 in intensive care, 17 on ventilation, all more than the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26dec&#39;21_322-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26dec&#39;21-322">&#91;320&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>By 27 December, NSW pathology services processed more than 24 million <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_testing" title="COVID-19 testing">PCR tests</a> but, as in other states, resources were being strained by "tourism testing". Consequently, on 29 December the NSW Health Department asked that people getting tested to travel interstate for holidays avoid going to COVID testing sites unnecessarily as it was unlikely they would get test results within 72 hours. If travelling to Qld, this would be after that states' 1 January  2022 changes to test requirements became effective and only a RAT test needed.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-avoid-testing-29dec&#39;21_323-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-avoid-testing-29dec&#39;21-323">&#91;321&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Priority for getting a PCR test was then given to those who:<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-avoid-testing-29dec&#39;21_323-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-avoid-testing-29dec&#39;21-323">&#91;321&#93;</a></sup><br />
• had COVID-19 symptoms or <br /> – a positive <a href="/wiki/Rapid_antigen_test" title="Rapid antigen test">rapid antigen test</a><br />
• were a household contact of a confirmed case<br />
• had been in a venue, for example a club, where there had been high transmission <br />
• had been in a setting with vulnerable people which was experiencing an outbreak, such as an aged care home
</p><p>On 28 December there were 3 more deaths, raising the state total to 658, and new case numbers jumped by about 85% in 24 hours to 11,201<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28dec&#39;21_324-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28dec&#39;21-324">&#91;322&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-new-cases11k+-29dec&#39;21_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-new-cases11k+-29dec&#39;21-9">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> from 6,062 on 27&#160;December.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27dec&#39;21_325-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27dec&#39;21-325">&#91;323&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 30 December there were another 6 deaths raising the state total to 665. They were 4 men and 2 women aged in their 60s, 70s, 80s and 90s. 1 was not vaccinated, 1 had 1 dose, 4 had 2 doses of vaccine. New cases jumped sharply by over 70% to 21,151<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30dec&#39;21_326-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30dec&#39;21-326">&#91;324&#93;</a></sup> from 12,226 on 29 December.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-29dec&#39;21_327-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-29dec&#39;21-327">&#91;325&#93;</a></sup>  Cases admitted to hospital rose to 832, with 69 in intensive care, 19 on ventilation, all above the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-30dec&#39;21_326-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-30dec&#39;21-326">&#91;324&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 31 December there were another 4 deaths raising the state total to 669. They were 1 man and 3 women aged in their 60s, 70s, and 80s. 1 was not vaccinated, 1 had 1 dose, 2 had 2 doses of vaccine. New cases rose to 22,577. Cases admitted to hospital rose to 901, and to 79 in intensive care.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-22577-nucases-31dec&#39;21_328-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-22577-nucases-31dec&#39;21-328">&#91;326&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="2022">2022</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: 2022">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>On 1 January there were another 2 deaths raising the state total to 671. Both were men, aged in their 80s, and 90s. Both had 2 doses of vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22_329-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22-329">&#91;327&#93;</a></sup><br />
Daily new cases fell to 18,278 from 22,577. The majority  were from the Sydney region: 3,740 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,336 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 2,961 Western Sydney LHD, 1,999 Northern Sydney LHD, and 1,918 from Sydney LHD. There were another 1,342 from Hunter New England LHD, with lesser numbers in other health districts.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22_329-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22-329">&#91;327&#93;</a></sup><br />
Cases admitted to hospital rose to 1,066, with 83 in intensive care and 24 on ventilation, both slightly up.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22_329-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1jan&#39;22-329">&#91;327&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 2 January there were another 4 deaths raising the state total to 675. They were 2 men and 2 women, 2 aged in their 70s, 1 each in their 80s, and 90s. Three had 2 doses of vaccine, one had received 3 doses.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22_330-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22-330">&#91;328&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases rose to 20,794 from 18,278. The majority  were from the Sydney region: 3,966 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,576 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 4,047 Western Sydney LHD, 1,889 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,122 from Sydney LHD. There were another 1,612 from Hunter New England LHD, with lesser numbers in other health districts.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22_330-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22-330">&#91;328&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 1,204, with 95 in intensive care and 25 on ventilation, all up on the preceding day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22_330-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22-330">&#91;328&#93;</a></sup><br />Confirmed state COVID-19 cases since the start of the pandemic reached 248,875.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22_330-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2jan&#39;22-330">&#91;328&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 3 January there were another 2 deaths raising the state total to 677. They were 2 men, one aged in his 70s at Westmead Hospital in Sydney, the other his 90s at <a href="/wiki/John_Hunter_Hospital" title="John Hunter Hospital">John Hunter Hospital</a> in Newcastle. Each had 2 doses of vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22_331-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22-331">&#91;329&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases rose to 23,131 from 20,794. The majority were from the Sydney region: 4,258 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 4,602 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 3,680 Western Sydney LHD, 1,979 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,969 from Sydney LHD. There were another 1,689 from Hunter New England LHD, with lesser numbers in other health districts.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22_331-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22-331">&#91;329&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital were 1,344, with 105 in intensive care and 27 on ventilation, all up on the day before.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22_331-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22-331">&#91;329&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was a new record, previously 1,268 cases set on 21 September 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-1344-hosp-3jan&#39;22_259-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-1344-hosp-3jan&#39;22-259">&#91;257&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 4 January there were another 8 deaths raising the state total to 685. They were 6 men and 2 women. 1 was in their 50s, 2 their 60s, 2 their 70s, 2 their 80s, and 1 person their 90s. One death each was at <a href="/w/index.php?title=Coffs_Harbour_Base_Hospital&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Coffs Harbour Base Hospital (page does not exist)">Coffs Harbour Base Hospital</a>, Gosford Hospital and <a href="/wiki/Bupa" title="Bupa">Bupa</a> Aged Care in <a href="/wiki/Ballina,_New_South_Wales" title="Ballina, New South Wales">Ballina</a>. 2 were not vaccinated, 5 had two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, and 1 person had 3 doses of COVID vaccine.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22_332-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22-332">&#91;330&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases rose markedly from 23,131 to 35,054, over 50% increase. The majority of new cases, over 70%, were from the Sydney region: 6,542 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 5,710 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 5,989 Western Sydney LHD, 3,667 Northern Sydney LHD, and 3,827 from Sydney LHD. There were another 2,961 from Hunter New England LHD, 1,502 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 1,496 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, with numbers below 600 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22_332-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22-332">&#91;330&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital were 1,491, with 119 in intensive care and 32 on ventilation, all up on the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22_332-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4jan&#39;22-332">&#91;330&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised set another new record at 1,491, up on the 1,344 set the previous day, the record before that was 1,268 cases on 21 September 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-1344-hosp-3jan&#39;22_259-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-1344-hosp-3jan&#39;22-259">&#91;257&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 4 January, <a href="/wiki/Booster_dose" title="Booster dose">booster shots</a> of COVID-19 vaccine became available for those aged over 18-years, and whose last vaccination was at least 4 months prior. NSW Health also "strongly" recommended a third vaccine dose for those aged 12 years and over who were, severely <a href="/wiki/Immuno-compromised" class="mw-redirect" title="Immuno-compromised">immuno-compromised</a>, and two months since their second dose.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22_331-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3jan&#39;22-331">&#91;329&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Shortage of some foods on supermarket shelves, such as fresh fruit, meat and vegetables, became apparent on 4 January as the effects of the pandemic on supply chains, such as staff shortages caused by transport and distribution centre workers having to isolate after COVID exposure, took hold. The problem is worse because of the extra demand during the Christmas/New Year holiday period coinciding with large increases in COVID-19 infections.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-supply-issues-4jan&#39;22_333-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-supply-issues-4jan&#39;22-333">&#91;331&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 5 January there were another 6 deaths raising the state total to 691. They were 5 men and 1 woman. 1 was in their 20s, others their 60s, 80s, and 90s. 3 were from western Sydney, 2 the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Lake_Macquarie" title="City of Lake Macquarie">Lake Macquarie</a> area. The last 1 was from the ACT, the man in his 20s, at St Vincent's Hospital. He had two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, no known underlying health conditions.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22_10-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases fell slightly from 35,054 to 34,994, detected by 111,231 tests. The majority of new cases, were again from the Sydney region: 5,364 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), <b>5,556</b> South Eastern Sydney LHD, 5,456 Western Sydney LHD, 3,538 Northern Sydney LHD, and 4,226 from Sydney LHD. There were another 3,424 from Hunter New England LHD, 1,452 (down slightly) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1,633 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD and 1,116 Central Coast LHD (up from previous days' 588), with numbers below 700 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22_10-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital were up to 1,609, with 131 in intensive care and 38 on ventilation, all up on the previous day.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22_10-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5jan&#39;22-10">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup>  The number hospitalised set another state record, up on the 1,491 record set the previous day.
</p><p>Also on 5 January, <a href="/wiki/Coles_Supermarkets" title="Coles Supermarkets">Coles Supermarkets</a> introduced limits on some food items. Chicken breasts, chicken thighs, mince and sausages were limited to 2 packs. Matthew Swindells, their chief operations officer, said that east coast stores will be affected the most, particularly NSW and Greater Sydney. <a href="/wiki/Woolworths_Supermarkets" title="Woolworths Supermarkets">Woolworths Supermarkets</a> said it will not be limiting buying.<sup id="cite_ref-9news-food-buy-limits-5jan&#39;22_334-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9news-food-buy-limits-5jan&#39;22-334">&#91;332&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 6 January there was a jump up to 11 deaths that day, raising the state total to 702. They were 6 men and 5 women, aged in their 50s, 60s, 70s, 80s, and 90s. 3 were from south eastern Sydney, 1 western Sydney, 1 south western Sydney, 1 northern Sydney. Another 3 from northern NSW, 1 from <a href="/wiki/Port_Stephens_(New_South_Wales)" title="Port Stephens (New South Wales)">Port Stephens</a> and 1 Lake Macquarie.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22_335-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22-335">&#91;333&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases rose again, to 38,625 from 34,994, detected by 112,725 tests. The majority of new cases, were again from the Sydney region:  6,076 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 6,444 South Eastern Sydney LHD, <b>6,968</b> Western Sydney LHD, 4,172 Northern Sydney LHD, and 4,162 from Sydney LHD. There were another 2,430 from Hunter New England LHD, 1,740 (up ~20%) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 1,606 (up ~25%) Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 1,000 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22_335-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22-335">&#91;333&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital were up to 1,738, with 134 in intensive care and 33 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22_335-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6jan&#39;22-335">&#91;333&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised set another state record, up on the 1,609 record set the previous day.
</p><p>On 7 January there were 9 deaths, raising the official state total to 711. They were 4 men and 5 women, aged in their 50s, 70s, and 90s. 2 were from south eastern Sydney, 1 western Sydney, 5 south western Sydney, 1 northern Sydney. 1 was from Newcastle.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22_11-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases rose again, to 45,098 from 38,625, detected by 116,915 tests. The majority of new cases, ~47%, were again from the Sydney region: <b>7,970</b> (up ~33%) South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 6,413 (down slightly) South Eastern Sydney LHD, 6,972 Western Sydney LHD, 4,392 (up ~5%) Northern Sydney LHD, 4,930 (up ~15%) from Sydney LHD. There were another 4,432 (up ~80%) from Hunter New England LHD, 1,788 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD (up again), 1,691 (up ~5%) Central Coast LHD, 1,154 (up ~70%) Northern NSW LHD, and 1,059 (up ~20%) from Western NSW LHD, with numbers below 800 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22_11-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital were up to 1,795, with 145 in intensive care and 40 on ventilation, both also up.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22_11-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was another record, up on the 1,738 the previous day.
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Restrictions_reintroduced">Restrictions reintroduced</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: Restrictions reintroduced">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>Also on 7 January, the NSW government reintroduced some COVID safety measures. From 8 January, till 27 January:<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-restricts-reintro-7jan&#39;22_336-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-restricts-reintro-7jan&#39;22-336">&#91;334&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>singing and dancing banned in:
<ul><li>hospitality venues (including bars, clubs, nightclubs, pubs and restaurants)</li>
<li>entertainment facilities</li>
<li>major recreation facilities <br />   – weddings are exempted, as are performers, students and instructors in the listed settings</li></ul></li>
<li>non-urgent elective surgery will be paused (until mid-February)<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22_11-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7jan&#39;22-11">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<p>As a result, the <a href="/wiki/Tamworth_Country_Music_Festival" title="Tamworth Country Music Festival">Tamworth Country Music Festival</a>, set to start on 14 January, was postponed to April.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-tmwth-music-fest-2022-postpone_337-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-tmwth-music-fest-2022-postpone-337">&#91;335&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 8 January there was a state record of 16 deaths (previously 15) in a 24-hour period, raising the official state total to 727. They were 8 men and 8 women, aged in their 60s, 70s, 80s, and 90s. 14 were from Sydney: 2 from south eastern, 2&#160;western, 7 south western, 1 northern, and 2 inner-west Sydney. 1 was from the central coast, and 1 the south coast.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22_12-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases <i>fell</i> sharply, to 30,062 from 45,098, detected by 98,986 tests. The majority of new cases, ~75%, were from the Sydney region: <b>5,077</b> (down ~35%) South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 4,442 (down ~30%) South Eastern Sydney LHD, <b>5,077</b>&#160;(down ~40%) Western Sydney LHD, 2,505 (down ~45%) Northern Sydney LHD, 3,184 (down ~33%) from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>2,527</b> (down ~40%) from Hunter New England LHD, 1,535 (down ~15%) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1,121 (down ~33%) Central Coast LHD, 1,027 (down ~10%) Northern NSW LHD, 1,059 (up ~20%) from Western NSW LHD, and 1,386 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, with numbers below 600 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22_12-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital were up to 1,927, with 151 in intensive care and 38 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22_12-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-8jan&#39;22-12">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was a record, up on the 1,795 the previous day.
</p><p>On 9 January there was a state record of 18 (previously 16) deaths reported, raising the official state total to 745 deaths. They were 11 men and 6 women, 3&#160;were aged in their 60s, 4 their 70s,7 their 80s, 2 their 90s, and a child under 5&#160;years. 14 were from Sydney and suburbs: 3 western, 4 south western, 1 northern, 2 southern, 2 inner-west, 1 the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Sydney" title="City of Sydney">inner city</a>, and 1&#160;eastern Sydney. There was also 1 from <a href="/wiki/Penrith,_New_South_Wales" title="Penrith, New South Wales">Penrith</a>, 2 the <a href="/wiki/Hunter_Region" title="Hunter Region">Hunter region</a>, and 1 from  the <a href="/wiki/Riverina" title="Riverina">Riverina region</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22_338-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22-338">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> <br />The deaths included: <br /> • a child from south western Sydney, at home, with "significant underlying health conditions" <br /> • man in his 30s, from eastern Sydney, at Prince of Wales Hospital.<br />Daily new cases were 20,293 (only from PCR testing in the 24 hours to 8pm on 9&#160;January). Total tests were down ~15% at 84,333. NSW Health stated: "As increasingly people follow NSW Health’s advice to use <a href="/wiki/Rapid_antigen_test" title="Rapid antigen test">rapid antigen tests</a> (RAT) for diagnosing COVID-19, the number of PCR tests will underestimate the true number of people who have tested positive for COVID-19.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22_338-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22-338">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> The majority of new cases were from the Sydney region: 3,230 South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD),  2,660  South Eastern Sydney LHD, <b>3,654</b>  Western Sydney LHD, 1,811 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,095 from Sydney LHD. There were another 1,115 from Hunter New England LHD, and <b>1,231</b> Nepean Blue Mountains LHD,  with numbers below 900 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22_338-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22-338">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital were up to 2,030, with 159 in intensive care and 47 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22_338-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-9jan&#39;22-338">&#91;336&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was a record high, up ~5% on the 1,927 the previous day.
</p><p>On 10 January there were 11 deaths reported, raising the official state total to 756 deaths. They were 5 men and 6 women, 1&#160;was aged in their 70s, 7 their 80s, and 3 their 90s. 8 were from Sydney and suburbs: 1 western, 4 south western, 1 northern, 1 southern, and 1 eastern Sydney. There was also 1 from the <a href="/wiki/Central_Coast_Council_(New_South_Wales)" title="Central Coast Council (New South Wales)">Central Coast</a>, and 2 the Hunter Region.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22_339-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22-339">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases were 25,870 (only from PCR testing). Total tests reported were down ~15% at 71,325.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22_339-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22-339">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup> The majority of new cases were from the Sydney region: <b>5,014</b> South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,319 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 4,345 Western Sydney LHD, 2,345 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,640 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>1,661</b> from Hunter New England LHD, 1,425 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1,448 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1,001Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 900 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22_339-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22-339">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,186, with 170 in intensive care and 51 on ventilation. The total of reported cases in NSW since the pandemic began there in March 2019 was 501,200.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22_339-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10jan&#39;22-339">&#91;337&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was again a record high, up on the previous days' 2,030 admissions.
</p><p>On 11 January there were 21 deaths reported, 7 of the deaths were from 2021 in September (1 death), October (2) and December (4), and were added after the end of coronial inquiries. This raised the official state total to 777 deaths. They were 17&#160;men and 4 women, 1&#160;was aged in their 30s, 1 their 40s, 2 their 50s, 4 their 60s, 6 their 70s, 4 their 80s, 2 their 9s and 1 their 100s. 17 were from Sydney and suburbs: 2 western, 4 south western, 2 northern, 4 Northern Beaches, 4 south eastern, 1 the inner city,. There was also 2 from the Newcastle area, and 2 Wollongong.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22_13-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases were 34,759 (only from PCR testing). Total tests reported were up 90% at 134,411 from 71,325.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22_13-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> The majority of new cases were from the Sydney region: <b>7,350</b> South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,911 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 5,394 Western Sydney LHD, 3,237 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,522 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>3,410</b> from Hunter New England LHD, 1,345 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 2,169 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1,054 Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 1,000 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22_13-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> 90% of the new cases were of the Omicron variant, the remainder Delta.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22_340-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22-340">&#91;338&#93;</a></sup><br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,242, with 175 in intensive care and 54 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22_13-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11jan&#39;22-13">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> Half those in ICU were not vaccinated and 67% were infected with Omicron. This contrasts to during the first week of December 2021, when Omicron was 10% of ICU infections.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22_340-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22-340">&#91;338&#93;</a></sup> The number hospitalised was a new record high, slightly up on the previous days' 2,186 admissions.
</p>
<h4><span id="RAT_.28Rapid_Antigen_Test.29_reporting"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="RAT_(Rapid_Antigen_Test)_reporting">RAT (Rapid Antigen Test) reporting</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=35" title="Edit section: RAT (Rapid Antigen Test) reporting">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 12 January, on-line reporting of RAT tests became available, and positive result reporting was made mandatory, backdated to 1 January. Failure to report positives, from 12 January onwards, can result in a $1,000 fine from 19 January After the reporting system went live at 9am that day, 53,909 positives were reported in less than 8 hours.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22_340-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bad-day-21dead-11jan&#39;22-340">&#91;338&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 12 January there were 22 deaths reported. 14 were vaccinated, 8 not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 799 deaths.There were 13 men and 9 women, 1 was aged in their 60s, 8 their 70s, 7 their 80s, 5 their 90s and 1 their 100s. 20 were from Sydney and suburbs: 7 south western, 7 Northern Sydney, 3 south eastern, 2 Inner Sydney, 1 from the Eastern Suburbs. There was also 1&#160;from the Central Coast and 1 person the <a href="/wiki/Cessnock,_New_South_Wales" title="Cessnock, New South Wales">Cessnock</a> area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22_341-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22-341">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases were 30,541 (only from PCR testing). Total tests reported were down 34% at 88,164 from 134,411. RAT test positives reported that day totalled 61,387. These tests cover from 1&#160;January. 50,729 positives are from the last seven days. Multiple positives by one person on different days are included.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22_341-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22-341">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup> <br />Most new cases, ~68%, were from the Sydney region: <b>6,080</b>&#160;(down~27%) South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,655 (down~7%) South Eastern Sydney LHD, 4,929 (down ~9%) Western Sydney LHD, 2,841 (down ~12%) Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,873 (up ~14%) from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>2,491</b> (down ~27%) from Hunter New England LHD, 1,506 (up ~12%) Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1,396 (down ~35%) Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1,424 (up ~40%) Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 800 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22_341-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22-341">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,383, with 182 in intensive care and 60 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22_341-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-12jan&#39;22-341">&#91;339&#93;</a></sup> The 22 deaths was a new state high, and those hospitalised was also a new high, slightly up on the previous days' 2,242 admissions.
</p><p>On 13 January there were 29 deaths reported. 19 were vaccinated, 10 not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 828 deaths. There were 15 men and 14 women, 3 were aged in their 40s, 5 their 60s, 5 their 70s, 11 their 80s, and 5 their 90s. 25 were from Sydney and suburbs: 10 south western Sydney, 5 northern, 5 south eastern, 3 western Sydney, 2 Sydney's Inner West. There was also: 2 people from the <a href="/wiki/Tweed_Heads,_New_South_Wales" title="Tweed Heads, New South Wales">Tweed Heads</a> area, 1 Wollongong and 1 the <a href="/wiki/City_of_Lake_Macquarie" title="City of Lake Macquarie">Lake Macquarie</a> area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22_342-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22-342">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases  reported were down at 63,018 from 88,164. PCR testing results were 25,080 cases, and RAT test positives reported that day totalled 37,938.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22_342-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22-342">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup> Most new cases, were from the Sydney region: <b>4,599 </b>&#160;South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,173 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 4,280 Western Sydney LHD, 2,157 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,480 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>1,554 </b> from Hunter New England LHD, 1,249 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 1,289 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1,094 Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 1,000 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22_342-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22-342">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,525, with 184 in intensive care and 59 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22_342-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-13jan&#39;22-342">&#91;340&#93;</a></sup> The 29 deaths was a new state high, and those hospitalised was also new high, up on the previous days' 2,383 admissions. 
</p><p>On 14 January there were 20 deaths reported. 16 were vaccinated, 4 not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 848 deaths. There were 11 men and 9 women, 1 was aged in their 20s, 3 their 50s, 1 their 60s, 4 their 70s, 9 their 80s and 2 were in their 90s. 15 were from Sydney and suburbs: 7 south western Sydney, 3 south eastern, 4 western, 1 Sydney's Inner West. There was also: 1&#160;from the <a href="/wiki/Mid_North_Coast" title="Mid North Coast">Mid North Coast</a>, 2 Wollongong area and 2 the <a href="/wiki/Riverina" title="Riverina">Riverina</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> <br />One death was a man in his 20s at Albury Base Hospital who had two doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, and serious underlying health conditions.<br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down again at 48,768 from 88,164. PCR testing results were 27,020 cases, and RAT test positives reported that day were 21,748.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> <br />Most new cases were from the Sydney region: <b>5,143</b>&#160;South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 3,072 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 3,805 Western Sydney LHD, 2,483 Northern Sydney LHD, and 2,013 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>2,334 </b> from Hunter New England LHD, 1,221 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, 2,196 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, and 1,166 Central Coast LHD, with numbers below 900 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,576, with 193 in intensive care and 58 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22_7-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-14jan&#39;22-7">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The hospitalisations were a new high, up on the previous days' 2,525 admissions.
</p><p>On 15 January another 20 deaths were reported. 14 were vaccinated, 6 not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 868 deaths. There were 12 men and 8 women, 2 were aged in their 50s, 6 their 70s, 7 their 80s, 4 their 90s, and 1 was in their 100s. 18 were from Sydney and suburbs: 6 south western Sydney, 2 south eastern, 4 western, 4 Inner West, 1 northern, 1 <a href="/wiki/Northern_Beaches" title="Northern Beaches">Northern Beaches</a>. There was also: 1&#160;from the Wollongong area and 1 the <a href="/wiki/Tamworth,_New_South_Wales" title="Tamworth, New South Wales">Tamworth</a> area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22_343-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22-343">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> The 2 deaths in their 50s had serious underlying health conditions. <br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down again at 34,660 from 48,768. PCR testing results were 20,978 cases, and RAT test positives reported were 13,682.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22_343-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22-343">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> <br />Most new cases were from the Sydney region: <b>4,063</b>&#160;South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 2,336 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 3,139 Western Sydney LHD, 1,875 Northern Sydney LHD, and 1,858 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>1,755</b> from Hunter New England LHD, 989 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 1,458 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, with numbers below 700 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22_343-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22-343">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,650, with 191 in intensive care and 61 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22_343-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-15jan&#39;22-343">&#91;341&#93;</a></sup> Numbers hospitalised were a new high, up on the previous days' 2,576.
</p><p>On 16 January another 17 deaths were reported. 14 were vaccinated, 1 had 1 dose, 2 were not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 885 deaths. There were 12 men and 5 women, 1 was aged in their 60s, 4 their 70s, 9 their 80s, and 3 in their 90s. 13 were from Sydney and suburbs: 7 south western Sydney, 2 south eastern, 2&#160;western, 1 northern, 1 south Sydney. There was also: 1&#160;from the Newcastle area, 1 Central Coast, 1 Wagga Wagga, 1 the Tweed Heads area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22_344-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22-344">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down again at 29,504 from 34,660. Of those, 17,646 cases were from PCR tests, 11,858 RAT tests.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22_344-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22-344">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup> <br />Most new cases were from the Sydney region: <b>3,279</b>&#160;South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 1,888 South Eastern Sydney LHD, 3,234 Western Sydney LHD, 1,669 Northern Sydney LHD, and 1,613 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>1,365</b> from Hunter New England LHD, 845 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 1,058 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, with numbers below 700 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22_344-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22-344">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,776, with 203 in intensive care and 61 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22_344-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-16jan&#39;22-344">&#91;342&#93;</a></sup> Numbers hospitalised were a new high, up on the previous days' 2,650.
</p><p>On 17 January another 36 deaths were reported. 33 were vaccinated with at least 2 vaccine doses, 3 were not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 921 deaths. There were 22 men and 14 women, 1 was aged in their 40s, 2 their 50s, 1 their 60s, 11 their 70s, 12 their 80s, and 9 in their 90s. 27 were from Sydney and suburbs: 9 south western Sydney, 8&#160;western, 2 northern, 5 Sydney, 3 Northern Beaches. There was also 9 from regional NSW:  1 the <a href="/wiki/Newcastle,_New_South_Wales" title="Newcastle, New South Wales">Newcastle</a> area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Coffs_Harbour" title="Coffs Harbour">Coffs Harbour</a> area, 1 Lake Macquarie area, 1 <a href="/wiki/New_England_(New_South_Wales)" title="New England (New South Wales)">New England</a> area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Northern_Rivers" title="Northern Rivers">Northern Rivers</a> area, <a href="/wiki/Shellharbour_City_Centre,_New_South_Wales" class="mw-redirect" title="Shellharbour City Centre, New South Wales">Shellharbour</a> area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Bega_Valley_Shire" title="Bega Valley Shire">Bega Valley Shire</a> area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Southern_Tablelands" title="Southern Tablelands">Southern Tablelands</a> area, and 1 from the <a href="/wiki/Taree" title="Taree">Taree</a> area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22_345-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22-345">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were up at 29,830 from 29,504. Of those, 16,067 cases were from PCR tests, 13,763 RAT tests.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22_345-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22-345">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> <br />Most new cases were from the Sydney region: 2,594&#160;South Western Sydney Local Health District (LHD), 2,100 South Eastern Sydney LHD, <b>2,868</b> Western Sydney LHD, 1,489 Northern Sydney LHD, and 1,312 from Sydney LHD. There were another <b>1,035</b> from Hunter New England LHD, 878 Nepean Blue Mountains LHD, and 928 Illawarra Shoalhaven LHD, with numbers below 900 cases in all other LHDs.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22_345-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22-345">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,850, with 209 in intensive care and 63 on ventilation, all up.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22_345-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-17jan&#39;22-345">&#91;343&#93;</a></sup> The 36 deaths was a new state high, and numbers hospitalised were also a new high, up on the previous days' 2,776.
</p><p>On 18 January another 32 deaths were reported. 23 were vaccinated with at least 2 doses of vaccine, 1 had 1 dose, 8 were not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 953 deaths. There were 20 men and 12 women, 3 were aged in their 40s, 3 their 60s, 8 their 70s, 11 their 80s, and 7 in their 90s. 28 were from Sydney and suburbs: 11 south western Sydney, 2&#160;western, 9 south east, 4 northern Sydney, 1 inner west, 1 from the Northern Beaches. There was also 4 from regional NSW: 2 from the Illawarra Shoalhaven region, 1 the Central Coast and 1 New England area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22_346-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22-346">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were up at 32,297 from 29,830. Of those, 19,847 cases were from PCR tests, 12,450 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 10,417 were from the previous seven days.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22_346-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22-346">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose to 2,863, with 217 in intensive care and 66 on ventilation, all up.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22_346-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-18jan&#39;22-346">&#91;344&#93;</a></sup> The numbers hospitalised set a new record high, slightly up on the previous days' 2,850.
</p><p>On 19 January 25 deaths were reported. 16 were vaccinated with at least 2 doses of vaccine, 1 had 1 dose, 8 were not vaccinated. This raised the official state total to 978 deaths. There were 16 men and 9 women, 1 was aged in their 30s, 2 their 50s, 5 their 60s, 5 their 70s, 7 their 80s, 4 in their 90s and 1 over 100 years old. 17 were from Sydney and suburbs: 1 south western, 6 western, 5 south east, 3 inner west, 2 Northern Beaches. There was also 8 from regional NSW: 1 the Illawarra Shoalhaven region, 2 the Central Coast, 2 Lake Macquarie area, 1 Newcastle area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Queanbeyan" title="Queanbeyan">Queanbeyan</a>, and 1 Albury.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22_347-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22-347">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down at 30,825 from 32,297. Of those, 17,647 cases were from PCR tests, 13,178 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 11,034 were from the previous seven days.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22_347-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22-347">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital <i>fell</i> to 2,781, down to 212 in intensive care, and up slightly to 68 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22_347-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-19jan&#39;22-347">&#91;345&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="Over_1.2C000_deaths_total"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Over_1,000_deaths_total">Over 1,000 deaths total</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=36" title="Edit section: Over 1,000 deaths total">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 20 January 46 deaths were reported, a new state record. These deaths raised the official state total to 1,024 deaths. 7 were from 29&#160;December 2021 to 13 January 2022, and were included after coronial enquiries were finished. 1 had 3 doses of  vaccine, 29 had 2 doses, 2 had 1 dose. 14 were not vaccinated. There were 33 men and 13 women, 1 was aged in their 30s, 1 their 40s, 4 their 50s, 8 their 60s, 12 their 70s, 13 their 80s, 7 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22_348-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup> <br /><b>35</b> were from Sydney and suburbs: 20 south western, 5 western, 1 inner west, 2 Eastern Suburbs, 1 inner west, 2 Northern, 1 Northern Beaches, 3 Sydney's south. There was also 11 from regional NSW: 1 Port Macquarie, 1 Coffs Harbour, 1 Bega Valley area, 1 Singleton, 1 Jervis Bay area, 1 Wollongong, 1 the South Coast and 1 the Tweed Heads area,  2 Newcastle area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Queanbeyan" title="Queanbeyan">Queanbeyan</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22_348-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down at 25,168 from 30,825. Of those, 15,153 cases were from PCR tests, 10,015 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 8,774 were from the previous seven days.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22_348-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital <i>fell</i> again to 2,743, down to 209 in intensive care, and unchanged at 68 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22_348-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-20jan&#39;22-348">&#91;346&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 21 January 30 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,054 deaths. 4 had 3 doses of  vaccine, 16 had 2 doses, 1 had 1 dose. 9 were not vaccinated. There were 18 men and 12 women, 1 was aged in their 50s, 7 their 70s, 15 their 80s, 7 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22_349-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22-349">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup> <br />23 were from Sydney and suburbs: 10 south western, 1 inner Sydney, 5 Eastern Suburbs, 2 inner west, 2 north west, 3 Sydney's south. There was also 7 from regional NSW: 2 Northern Rivers, 1 Coffs Harbour, 2 Central Coast, 1 Dubbo, and 1 Wollongong. <sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22_349-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22-349">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down at 20,148 from 25,168. Of those, 11,582 cases were from PCR tests, 8,566 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 7,687 were from the previous seven days.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22_349-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22-349">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose from 2,743 to 2,762, down to 204 in intensive care, and up slightly to 70 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22_349-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-21jan&#39;22-349">&#91;347&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 22 January 34 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,088 deaths. 2 had 3 doses of  vaccine, 23 had 2 doses, 3 had 1 dose. 6 were not vaccinated. There were 26 men and  8 women,  1 was aged in their 40s, 5 their 50s, 5 their 60s, 9 their 70s, 10 their 80s, 4 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22_350-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22-350">&#91;348&#93;</a></sup> <br />23 were from Sydney and suburbs: 11 south western, 4 western, 4 south eastern, 2 north west, 1 northern, 1 inner west Sydney. There was also 10 from regional NSW: 2 Northern Rivers, 3 Newcastle area, 1 Mid North Coast, 1 South Coast, 1 Riverina, 2 Wollongong area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22_350-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22-350">&#91;348&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were up at 20,324 from 20,148. Of those, 13,620 cases were from PCR tests, 6,704 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 6,165 were from the previous seven days. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 748,995.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22_350-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22-350">&#91;348&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell from 2,762 to 2,712, down to 189 in intensive care, and up slightly to 72 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22_350-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-22jan&#39;22-350">&#91;348&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 23 January 24 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,112 deaths. 2 had 3 doses of vaccine, 16 had 2 doses, 3 had 1 dose. 3 were not vaccinated. There were 16 men and 8 women, 2 were aged in their 50s, 1 their 60s, 2 their 70s, 12 their 80s, and 7 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22_351-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22-351">&#91;349&#93;</a></sup> <br /> 22 were from Sydney and suburbs: 10 south western, 3 western, 5 south eastern, 4 inner west. There was also 2 from northern NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22_351-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22-351">&#91;349&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down at 15,091 from 20,324. Of those, 8,190 cases were from PCR tests, 6,901 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 6,336 were from the previous seven days. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 757,386.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22_351-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22-351">&#91;349&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital rose from 2,712 to 2,816, up to 196 in intensive care, and down slightly to 69 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22_351-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-23jan&#39;22-351">&#91;349&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 24 January 29 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,141 deaths. 2 had 3 doses of vaccine, 21 had 2 doses. 6 were not vaccinated. There were 16 men and 13 women, 5 were aged in their 60s, 3 their 70s, 14 their 80s, 6 their 90s and 1 more than 100 years.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22_352-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22-352">&#91;350&#93;</a></sup> <br /> 21 were from Sydney and suburbs: 10 south western, 6 western, 3 south eastern, 2 northern Sydney. There was also 8 from regional NSW: 4 the Shellharbour area, 1 Wollongong area, 1 New England region, 1 <a href="/wiki/Broken_Hill" title="Broken Hill">Broken Hill</a>, and 1 the Central Coast.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22_352-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22-352">&#91;350&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were up at 18,512 from 15,091. Of those, 9,422 cases were from PCR tests, 9,090 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 8,242 were from the previous seven days. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 766,996.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22_352-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22-352">&#91;350&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose from 2,816 to 2,943, down to 183 in intensive care, and up slightly to 72 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22_352-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-24jan&#39;22-352">&#91;350&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Also on 24 January, the restrictions in NSW regarding QR code check-ins, venue capacity, singing, dancing and mask wearing, all due to expire on 27 January, were extended by a month to 28 February.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-masks-extend-25jan&#39;22_353-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-masks-extend-25jan&#39;22-353">&#91;351&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 25 January 29 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,170 deaths. 6 had 3 doses of vaccine, 16 had 2 doses, 7 were not vaccinated. There were 17 men and 12 women, 2 were aged in their 50s, 3 their 60s, 2 their 70s, 16 their 80s and 6 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22_354-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22-354">&#91;352&#93;</a></sup> <br /> 19 were from Sydney and suburbs: 8 south western, 3 western, 4 northern Sydney, 2 Northern Beaches, 1 Eastern Suburbs, 1 Inner West. There was also 10 from regional NSW: 2 the Shellharbour area, 2 Wollongong area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Mid_North_Coast" title="Mid North Coast">Mid North Coast</a>, 1 the <a href="/wiki/Mid-Coast_Council" title="Mid-Coast Council">Mid Coast</a> area, 1 <a href="/wiki/Griffith,_New_South_Wales" title="Griffith, New South Wales">Griffith</a> area, 1 Northern Rivers region, 1 Tamworth region and 1 the Central Coast.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22_354-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22-354">&#91;352&#93;</a></sup> <br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were up at 21,030 from 18,512. Of those, 12,918 cases were from PCR tests, 8,112 RAT tests. Of the RAT positives, 7,416 were from the previous seven days. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 780,467.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22_354-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22-354">&#91;352&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell from 2,943 to 2,794, down to 175 in intensive care, and up slightly to 75 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22_354-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25jan&#39;22-354">&#91;352&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 26 January another 29 deaths were reported. This raised the official state total to 1,198 deaths. 4 had 3 doses of vaccine, 16 had 2 doses, 2 had 1 dose, 7 were not vaccinated. There were 19 men and 10 women, 2 were aged in their 60s, 8 their 70s, 13 their 80s and 6 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22_355-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22-355">&#91;353&#93;</a></sup> <br />23 were from Sydney and suburbs: 9 south western, 2 western, 2 south eastern, 1 northern Sydney, 2 Northern Beaches, 2 Inner Sydney, 2 Inner West, 3 Southern Sydney. There was also 6 from regional NSW: 2 Lake Macquarie area, 1 the Tweed area, 1 Batemans Bay, 1 Northern Rivers region, and 1 the Central Coast.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22_355-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22-355">&#91;353&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases (positive test results) reported were down at 17,316 from 21,030. Of those, 9,934 cases were from PCR tests, 7,382 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January, 229,793 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 780,467.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22_355-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22-355">&#91;353&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell from 2,794 to 2,722, up to 181 in intensive care, and fell slightly to 72 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22_355-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26jan&#39;22-355">&#91;353&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 January 35 deaths were reported in the preceding 24 hours, plus another 35 deaths (19 men and 16 women) from 2 to 20 January, all aged care facility residents in south western Sydney. This 70 dead raised the official state total to 1,268 deaths. Of the 35 most recent deaths, 8 had 3 doses of vaccine, 15 had 2 doses, 12 were not vaccinated. There were 20 men and 15 women, 1 was aged in their 40s, 2 their 60s, 6 their 70s, 11 their 80s, 14 their 90s and 1 was more than 100 years old.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27jan&#39;22_356-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27jan&#39;22-356">&#91;354&#93;</a></sup> <br />27 were from Sydney and suburbs: 12 south western, 7 western, 1 Eastern Suburbs, 2 northern, 1 Northern Beaches, 1 Inner West, 3 Southern Sydney. <h4><span id="Over_1.2C500_deaths_total"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Over_1,500_deaths_total">Over 1,500 deaths total</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=37" title="Edit section: Over 1,500 deaths total">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 3 February 31 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,520 deaths. Of the new deaths, 10 had 3 doses of vaccine, 18 had 2 doses, 3 were not vaccinated. There were 21 men and 10 women; 1 was aged in their 60s, 7 their 70s, 12 their 80s, 10 their 90s, and 1 aged 100.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22_6-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> 20 were from Sydney and suburbs: 9 south western, 1 northern, 1 Northern Beaches, 1 north west, 1 Inner West, 4 western, and 3 southern Sydney. There was also 11 from regional NSW:  1 Riverina region, 2 Shellharbour, 2 Wollongong, 2 Central Coast, 1 Hunter region, 1 South Coast, 1 Northern Rivers, 1 <a href="/wiki/Clarence_Valley_Council" title="Clarence Valley Council">Clarence Valley region</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22_6-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><br />Daily new cases (positive test results) reported fell to 10,698 from 12,632. Of those, 4,576 cases were from PCR tests, 6,122 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 276,418 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 844,422.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22_6-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell from 2,578 to 2,494, unchanged at 160 in intensive care, and up to 75 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22_6-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3feb&#39;22-6">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>

</p><p>On 10 February 19 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,661 deaths. Of the new deaths: 2 were aged <i>under</i> 65, 1 had 3 doses, 1 had 2 doses of vaccine (each had underlying health conditions); of those <i>over</i> 65, 3 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine,  5 had 2 doses,  9 were not vaccinated. There were 14 men and  5 women; 2 were aged in their 50s, 1 their 60s, 7 their 70s, 5 their 80s, and 4 their 90s<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22_370-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22-370">&#91;367&#93;</a></sup> 15 were from Sydney and suburbs: 6 south western, 1 south, 3 northern suburbs, 3 western, and 2 inner west. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 Coffs Harbour, 1 the <a href="/wiki/Upper_Hunter_Shire" title="Upper Hunter Shire">Upper Hunter</a>, 1 the Shellharbour region, 1 <a href="/wiki/Queanbeyan" title="Queanbeyan">Queanbeyan</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22_370-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22-370">&#91;367&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported fell to 8,950 from 10,130. Of those, 3,661 cases were from PCR tests, 5,289 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 310,556 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 872,355.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22_370-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22-370">&#91;367&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell from 1,795 to 1,716, down to 108 in intensive care and 48 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22_370-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-10feb&#39;22-370">&#91;367&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 11 February 32 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. 11 of the deaths occcured from 22 January to 5 February, and were included after the end of coronial inquiries. This raised the official state total to 1,693 deaths. Of the new deaths: 8 were aged <i>under</i> 65, 3 of them had 3 doses, 3 had 2 doses of vaccine; 2 were not vaccinated. 7 had underlying health conditions. There were 25 men and  7 women; 1 was aged in their 40s,  2 their 50s,  7 their 60s, 11 their 70s,  6 their 80s, and  5 their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> 23 were from Sydney and suburbs: 6 south western, 7 south eastern, 1 northern Sydney, 7 western, and 2 inner west. The other 9 were from regional NSW: 1 Mid North Coast, 1 the Lower Hunter, 1 Newcastle area, 1 Riverina,  4 Central Coast, and 1 Western NSW. <sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22_23-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported fell to 8,183 from 8,950. Of those, 3,288 cases were from PCR tests, 4,895 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 314,988 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 876,020.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22_23-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell from 1,716 to 1,650, down to 104 in intensive care and slightly down to 47 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22_23-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-11feb&#39;22-23">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>
