</p><p>On 25 February, 11 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,890 deaths. Of the new deaths: 4 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 6 had two doses. 1 was unvaccinated. They were 7 men, and 4 women; 1 was aged in their 40s, 1 their 60s, 4 their 70s, 3 their 80s, and 2 their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22_384-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22-384">&#91;381&#93;</a></sup> The man in his 40s had 3 vaccine doses, and significant underlying health conditions. 7 were from Sydney and suburbs: 2 south-western, 2 south-western, 1 western, 1 Sydney's Inner West. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 the Tamworth region, 1 the Central Tablelands region, 1 Shellharbour region, and 1 Northern Rivers region.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22_384-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22-384">&#91;381&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported fell from 7,583 to 7,017. Of those, 2,621 cases were from PCR tests, 4,396 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 380,090 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 919,471.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22_384-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22-384">&#91;381&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell to 1,130 from 1,144, down to 59 in intensive care and fell to 24 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22_384-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-25feb&#39;22-384">&#91;381&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 26 February,  7 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,897 deaths. Of the new deaths: 5 had 2 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 1 had 1 dose. 1 was unvaccinated. They were  6 men, and 1 woman; 2 were aged in their 60s, 3 in their 80s, 1 their 90s, and 1 was aged over 100.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22_385-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22-385">&#91;382&#93;</a></sup> 3 were from Sydney and suburbs: 1 south-western, 1 northern beaches, 1 eastern suburbs. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 the Shoalhaven region, 1 the south coast, 1 Newcastle area, and 1 from north western NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22_385-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22-385">&#91;382&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported fell from 7,017 to 6,014 Of those, 2,198 cases were from PCR tests, 3,816 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 383,612 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 921,933.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22_385-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22-385">&#91;382&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose slightly to 1,146 from 1,144, down to 58 in intensive care and fell to 21 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22_385-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-26feb&#39;22-385">&#91;382&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 27 February,  6 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,903 deaths. Of the new deaths: 3 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 1 had 2 doses, 1 had 1 dose. 1 was unvaccinated. They were  5 men, and 1 woman; 1 was aged in their 50s, 1 their 60s,  2 their 70s, and 2 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22_386-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22-386">&#91;383&#93;</a></sup> 2 were from Sydney: 1 south-western, 1 Western Sydney. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 Dubbo, 1 Wollongong area, 1 Northern Rivers, and 1 Queanbeyan.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22_386-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22-386">&#91;383&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported fell from 6,014 to 5,856. Of those, 1,794 cases were from PCR tests, 4,062 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 387,479 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 923,888.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22_386-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22-386">&#91;383&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell to 1,136 from 1,146, down to 55 in intensive care and fell to 16 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22_386-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-27feb&#39;22-386">&#91;383&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 28 February,  9 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,912 deaths. Of the new deaths: 4 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 4 had 2 doses. 1 was unvaccinated. They were  4 men, and 5 woman; 1 was aged in their 60s, 1 their 70s,  4 their 80s, and 3 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22_387-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22-387">&#91;384&#93;</a></sup> 5 were from Sydney: 2 south-western, 1 Inner Sydney., 1 Northern Sydney, 1 Northern Beaches. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 Goulburn, 1 Kiama, 1 Nowra, and 1 <a href="/wiki/Orange,_New_South_Wales" title="Orange, New South Wales">Orange</a>. <sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22_387-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22-387">&#91;384&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported rose to 8,874 from 6,014. Of those, 2,286 cases were from PCR tests, 6,588 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 393,803 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 926,387.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22_387-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22-387">&#91;384&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell from 1,136 to 1,098, down to 49 in intensive care and up to 18 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22_387-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-28feb&#39;22-387">&#91;384&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="March.">March.</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=38" title="Edit section: March.">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>
<p>On 1 March,  5 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,917 deaths. Of the new deaths: 3 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 2 had 2 doses. They were  3 men, and 2 women; 1 was aged in their 70s, 2 their 80s, and 2 in their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22_388-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22-388">&#91;385&#93;</a></sup> 3 were from Sydney: 2 Western, 1 Eastern Suburbs. The other 2 were from regional NSW: 1 Central West, and 1 the Riverina region.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22_388-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22-388">&#91;385&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported rose from 8,874 to 10,650. Of those, 3,706 cases were from PCR tests, 6,944 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 400,363 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 930,443.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22_388-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22-388">&#91;385&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital fell to 1,072 from 1,098, down to 45 in intensive care and up slightly to 19 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22_388-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-1mar&#39;22-388">&#91;385&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 2 March,  9 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,926 deaths. Of the new deaths: 3 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 1 had 2 doses, 1 had 1 dose. 4 were unvaccinated. They were  7 men, and 2 women; 1 was aged in their 30s, 1 their 40s, 2 their 50s, 1 their 60s, 2 their 70s, 1 their 80s, and 1 in their 90s. All those under 65 had underlying health conditions.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22_389-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22-389">&#91;386&#93;</a></sup> 8 were from Sydney and suburbs: 4 south-western, 3 Western, 1 <a href="/wiki/Inner_West" title="Inner West">inner west Sydney</a>. The last 1 was from the Shoalhaven region.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22_389-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22-389">&#91;386&#93;</a></sup><br /> Daily new cases reported rose to 11,338 from 10,650. Of those, 3,673 cases were from PCR tests, 7,665 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 407,597 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 934,494.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22_389-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22-389">&#91;386&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell to 1,035 from 1,072, down to 43 in intensive care and down to 17 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22_389-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-2mar&#39;22-389">&#91;386&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 3 March,  2 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,928 deaths. They were both men, 1 was aged in their 80s, had 2 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, and was from Sydney's Easter Suburbs. The other was in their 90s, not vaccinated, and from the Forster and Taree area.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22_390-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22-390">&#91;387&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases reported fell from 11,338 to 9,466. Of those, 3,416 cases were from PCR tests, 6,050 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 413,297 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 938,224.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22_390-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22-390">&#91;387&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell from 1,035 to 1,000, down to 42 in intensive care and slightly up to 18 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22_390-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-3mar&#39;22-390">&#91;387&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 4 March, 10 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,938 deaths. Of the new deaths: 6 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 3 had 2 doses, 1 had 1 dose. 1 was unvaccinated. They were  5 men, and 5 women; 1 was aged in their 60s, 2 their 70s, 4 their 80s, 2 their 90s, and 1 was aged 100. 6 were from Sydney and suburbs: 1 south-western, 1 north-west, 2 western, 1 inner Sydney, 1 Inner West Sydney. The other 4 were from regional NSW: 1 Port Macquarie region,1 Wollongong, 1 Lake Macquarie region, and 1 from the Northern Rivers region.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases reported rose to 10,017 from 9,466. Of those, 3,395 cases were from PCR tests, 6,622 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 419,573 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 941,918.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22_22-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup> <br />Cases admitted to hospital fell to  995 from 1,035, up to 45 in intensive care and stayed at 18 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22_22-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-4mar&#39;22-22">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 5 March,  5 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,943 deaths. Of the new deaths: 1 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 4 had 2 doses. They were  4 men, and 1 woman; 2 were aged in their 70s, 2 their 90s, and 1 was aged over 100.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22_391-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22-391">&#91;388&#93;</a></sup> 4  were from Sydney and suburbs: 1 south-western, 1 inner, 1 Inner West, and 1 southern Sydney. The last was from western regional NSW.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22_391-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22-391">&#91;388&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases reported fell from 10,017 to 8,782. Of those, 3,273 cases were from PCR tests, 5,509 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 424,709 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 945,542.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22_391-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22-391">&#91;388&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose from 995 to 1,009, down to 43 in intensive care and fell to 16 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22_391-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-5mar&#39;22-391">&#91;388&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 6 March,  5 more deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,948 deaths. All had 2 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine. They were  1 man, and 4 women. 2 were in their 60s, 1 their 70s, and 2 their 80s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22_392-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22-392">&#91;389&#93;</a></sup> All were from Sydney and suburbs: 3 south-western, 1 Inner West, and 1 southern Sydney.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22_392-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22-392">&#91;389&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases reported rose to 9,017 from 8,782. Of those, 3,047 cases were from PCR tests, 5,970 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 430,375 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 948,861.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22_392-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22-392">&#91;389&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose to 1,066 from 1,009, stayed at 43 in intensive care and fell to 15 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22_392-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-6mar&#39;22-392">&#91;389&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On 7 March,  another 5 deaths were reported in the 24 hours to 4pm. This raised the official state total to 1,953 deaths. 1 had 3 doses of a COVID-19 vaccine, 3 had 2 doses. 1 was unvaccinated. They were  3 men, and 2 women. 3 were in their 70s, 1 their 80s, and 1 their 90s.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22_5-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> 3 were from Sydney: 2 south-western, 1 western. The other 2 were from Newcastle and Armidale.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22_5-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Daily new cases reported rose from 9,017 to 13,018. Of those, 3,397 cases were from PCR tests, 9,621 RAT tests. Since reporting started on 12 January 439,637 positive RATs have been reported. Total cases detected by PCR tests since the pandemic began reached 952,596.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22_5-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> <br /> Cases admitted to hospital rose from1,066 to 1,070, stayed at 43 in intensive care and up slightly to 16 on ventilation.<sup id="cite_ref-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22_5-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-health-nsw-stats-7mar&#39;22-5">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Statistics">Statistics</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=39" title="Edit section: Statistics">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p><b>Plot of COVID-19 cumulative cases in New South Wales</b><sup id="cite_ref-covid19data.com.au_393-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-covid19data.com.au-393">&#91;390&#93;</a></sup>
</p>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Event_cancellations">Event cancellations</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=40" title="Edit section: Event cancellations">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/w/index.php?title=List_of_events_affected_by_the_COVID-19_pandemic&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="List of events affected by the COVID-19 pandemic (page does not exist)">List of events affected by the COVID-19 pandemic</a></div>
<p>As a  consequence of social distancing requirements, lockdowns, travel restrictions, and state or national border closures implemented when the COVID-19 pandemic occurred, numerous events in 2020 and 2021 were cancelled, rescheduled, postponed, reduced in size, or changed location. Some went to an online or streaming format. Some events, such as <a href="/wiki/Vivid_Sydney" title="Vivid Sydney">Vivid Sydney</a> were cancelled for the second year in a row. Into early 2021 some events, such as <a href="/wiki/Skyfire_(Canberra)" title="Skyfire (Canberra)">Skyfire</a>, regional <a href="/wiki/Agricultural_shows" class="mw-redirect" title="Agricultural shows">agricultural shows</a>, and music festivals (<a href="/wiki/Byron_Bay_Bluesfest" title="Byron Bay Bluesfest">Byron Bay Bluesfest</a> and <a href="/wiki/Groovin_the_Moo" class="mw-redirect" title="Groovin the Moo">Groovin the Moo</a>)<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel_68-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-musicfeeds-moo-&#39;21-postponed_395-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-musicfeeds-moo-&#39;21-postponed-395">&#91;392&#93;</a></sup> were cancelled. As of 16&#160;January&#160;2021<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup> twenty regional town shows scheduled for January or February 2021 had been postponed or cancelled in New South Wales.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-agri-shows-2021-cancel_396-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-agri-shows-2021-cancel-396">&#91;393&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>In 2020, the <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Royal_Easter_Show" title="Sydney Royal Easter Show">Sydney Royal Easter Show</a>, the largest ticketed event in Australia, was cancelled only for the third time in its 197-year history.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-13-03-2020-cancell_397-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-13-03-2020-cancell-397">&#91;394&#93;</a></sup> The 2021 Easter show went ahead with restrictions such as limits on patron numbers.<sup id="cite_ref-eastershow-2021-covidsafe_398-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-eastershow-2021-covidsafe-398">&#91;395&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Vivid_Sydney" title="Vivid Sydney">Vivid Sydney</a> was cancelled in 2020 for the first time in its history,<sup id="cite_ref-399" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-399">&#91;396&#93;</a></sup> then cancelled again in 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-Vivid-2021-sydney-cancelled_400-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Vivid-2021-sydney-cancelled-400">&#91;397&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>The 2020 <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Writers%27_Festival" title="Sydney Writers&#39; Festival">Sydney Writers' Festival</a> suspended ticket sales and are expected to cancel their seasons.<sup id="cite_ref-sydneycancels_401-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sydneycancels-401">&#91;398&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Festival_of_Dangerous_Ideas" title="Festival of Dangerous Ideas">Festival of Dangerous Ideas</a> 2020 was cancelled on 16 March.<sup id="cite_ref-402" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-402">&#91;399&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>The 2020 <a href="/wiki/Byron_Bay_Bluesfest" title="Byron Bay Bluesfest">Byron Bay Bluesfest</a> was cancelled due to the introduction of 14-day self-isolation for anyone entering Australia.<sup id="cite_ref-403" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-403">&#91;400&#93;</a></sup> The 2021 Bluesfest scheduled for 1–5 April, was also cancelled, one day before it was to commence, by a public health order signed by the Minister for Health <a href="/wiki/Brad_Hazzard" title="Brad Hazzard">Brad Hazzard</a>. A case of community transmission was found in Byron Bay after people linked to the Brisbane 'nurse cluster' visited venues in Byron Bay while unknowingly infectious.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel_68-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-bluesfest&#39;21-cancel-68">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>In 2020, <a href="/wiki/Hunter_Valley_Steamfest" title="Hunter Valley Steamfest">Hunter Valley Steamfest</a> was cancelled,<sup id="cite_ref-404" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-404">&#91;401&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-405" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-405">&#91;402&#93;</a></sup> and cancelled again in 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-newc-weekly-steamfest&#39;21-cancel_406-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-newc-weekly-steamfest&#39;21-cancel-406">&#91;403&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Splendour_in_the_Grass" title="Splendour in the Grass">Splendour in the Grass</a> 2020 was first postponed from July until 23–25 October 2020,<sup id="cite_ref-sitg2020_407-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sitg2020-407">&#91;404&#93;</a></sup> then postponed again to 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-sitg2020to2021_408-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sitg2020to2021-408">&#91;405&#93;</a></sup><i></i></li>
<li>The 2020 <a href="/wiki/Sydney_Film_Festival" title="Sydney Film Festival">Sydney Film Festival</a> was cancelled on 18 March 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-sff2020_409-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sff2020-409">&#91;406&#93;</a></sup> The 2021 "67th Sydney Film Festival: Virtual Edition and Awards" were to be run "virtually" on 10–21 June 2021 via the festival website.<sup id="cite_ref-broad-sht-sff-2021_410-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-broad-sht-sff-2021-410">&#91;407&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>On 17 March 2020, the <a href="/wiki/Canowindra#Ballooning" title="Canowindra">Canowindra International Balloon Challenge</a>, due to be held in April, was cancelled due to concerns about "the spread of coronavirus".<sup id="cite_ref-canow-news-balloon-cancel_411-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-canow-news-balloon-cancel-411">&#91;408&#93;</a></sup> The 2021 event was held as scheduled on 26 April to 1 May.<sup id="cite_ref-liberal-balloon-fest-21_412-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-liberal-balloon-fest-21-412">&#91;409&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-abc-balloon-ch-2021-27apr&#39;21_413-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-balloon-ch-2021-27apr&#39;21-413">&#91;410&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>On 8 September 2020, <a href="/wiki/Tamworth_Regional_Council" title="Tamworth Regional Council">Tamworth Regional Council</a> voted to cancel the 49th <a href="/wiki/Tamworth_Country_Music_Festival" title="Tamworth Country Music Festival">Tamworth Country Music Festival</a>. The <a href="/wiki/Country_Music_Awards_of_Australia" title="Country Music Awards of Australia">Country Music Awards of Australia</a> (Golden Guitar Awards), an annual awards night held during the Festival, is planned to proceed via online <a href="/wiki/Online_streaming" class="mw-redirect" title="Online streaming">streaming</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-414" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-414">&#91;411&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>On 19 December, the 2020 <a href="/wiki/Sydney_to_Hobart_Yacht_Race" title="Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race">Sydney to Hobart Yacht Race</a> was cancelled due to an outbreak in the Greater Sydney region. Crews, officials and supporters would have had to quarantine on arrival in Hobart.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-syd-hobart-cancel_415-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-syd-hobart-cancel-415">&#91;412&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>The 2020 <a href="/wiki/City2Surf_(Sydney)" title="City2Surf (Sydney)">City2Surf</a> 50th-anniversary run was pushed back from 9 August until 18&#160;October, and the live event was cancelled. The event was run as a <a href="/wiki/Virtual_event" title="Virtual event">virtual event</a> where participants ran the length of the course on their local streets using an app.<sup id="cite_ref-msn-city2surf-cancelled_416-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msn-city2surf-cancelled-416">&#91;413&#93;</a></sup> The same happened in 2021, when Sydney was in another lockdown.<sup id="cite_ref-smh-2021-virtual-again-14aug&#39;21_417-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh-2021-virtual-again-14aug&#39;21-417">&#91;414&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li><a href="/w/index.php?title=Under_the_Southern_Stars&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Under the Southern Stars (page does not exist)">Under the Southern Stars</a> music festival was cancelled in 2020, and in April 2021 that years' was postponed to 2022.<sup id="cite_ref-news-com-southern-skies-fest-cancel_418-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news-com-southern-skies-fest-cancel-418">&#91;415&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>An alternate 2021 National <a href="/wiki/NAIDOC_Awards" title="NAIDOC Awards">NAIDOC Awards</a> event was planned for 3 July 2021 at the Sydney Opera House after the awards ceremony in Alice Springs (<a href="/wiki/Mparntwe" class="mw-redirect" title="Mparntwe">Mparntwe</a>) was cancelled.<sup id="cite_ref-naidoc-awards-ceremony-2021-alice-cancel_419-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-naidoc-awards-ceremony-2021-alice-cancel-419">&#91;416&#93;</a></sup>  After Sydney went into COVID lockdown on 23&#160;June, the Sydney ceremony was postponed as rules for travellers returning to the <a href="/wiki/Northern_Territory" title="Northern Territory">Northern Territory</a> meant that most people could not attend the Sydney event without a 14-day quarantine.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-cluster-bondi-№31_81-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-cluster-bondi-№31-81">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-naidoc-awards-July-2021-postpone_420-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-naidoc-awards-July-2021-postpone-420">&#91;417&#93;</a></sup></li>
<li>On 9 September 2021, the <a href="/wiki/2021_NRL_Grand_Final" title="2021 NRL Grand Final">2021 NRL Grand Final</a>, set for 3&#160;October at <a href="/wiki/Stadium_Australia" title="Stadium Australia">Stadium Australia</a> was moved interstate to <a href="/wiki/Suncorp_Stadium" class="mw-redirect" title="Suncorp Stadium">Suncorp Stadium</a> in Queensland due to "the current Covid-19 situation in Greater Sydney and across the state".<sup id="cite_ref-news.com-nrl&#39;21final-9sept&#39;21_229-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-news.com-nrl&#39;21final-9sept&#39;21-229">&#91;227&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>
<ul><li>The <a href="/wiki/Numeralla_Folk_Festival" class="mw-redirect" title="Numeralla Folk Festival">Numeralla Folk Festival</a> was cancelled in 2020 due to the pandemic, and in mid-January 2021 the 2021 event was also cancelled after the state government again tightened restrictions, extending a ban on indoor live singing to outdoors.<sup id="cite_ref-abc-nsw-no-numma-fest-12jan&#39;22_421-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-nsw-no-numma-fest-12jan&#39;22-421">&#91;418&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>

<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=COVID-19_pandemic_in_New_South_Wales&amp;action=edit&amp;section=42" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>

<li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">2 deaths of Queensland residents in NSW are reported under NSW Health's figures, but are excluded from this total.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-103"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-103">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">NSW Health ceased reporting the number of cases directly linked to the Bondi index case on July 10.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-361"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-361">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The reporting period was changed to end at 4pm, previously 8pm</span>
</li>
